       = 21.74\n|area_water_km2           = 3.41\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 1.32\n|elevation_ft             = 898\n|elevation_m              = 251\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name=\"2013 Pop Estimate\">{{cite web|title=Population Estimates |url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2013/SUB-EST2013-3.html |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2014-06-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522161634/http://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2013/SUB-EST2013-3.html |archivedate=May 22, 2014 }}</ref>\n|population_total         = 14775\n|population_metro         = \n|population_density_km2   = 281.58\n|population_density_sq_mi = 729.30\n|timezone                 = Central Standard Time\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|coordinates              = {{coord|34|10|39|N|86|50|41|W|region:US-AL|display=inline}}\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -5\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 35055-35058\n|area_code                = [[Area code 256|256]] Exchanges: 734,735,736,737,738,775\n|blank1_name              = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank1_info              = 01-18976\n|blank2_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank2_info              = 0116948\n|website                  = {{URL|https://cullmanal.gov/}}\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_est = 15858\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n|area_footnotes = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_01.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|blank_name = [[Federal Information Processing Standards|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info = 01-18976\n}}\n\n'''Cullman''' is the largest city and [[county seat]] of [[Cullman County, Alabama|Cullman County,]] [[Alabama]], United States. It is located along [[Interstate 65]], about {{convert|50|mi}} north of [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]] and about {{convert|55|mi}} south of [[Huntsville, Alabama|Huntsville]]. As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]] it had a population of 14,775,<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US0118976| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): Cullman city, Alabama| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> with an estimated population of 15,858 in 2018.<ref name=\"2013 Pop Estimate\"/>\n\n==History==\nBefore European settlement, the area that today includes Cullman was originally in the territory of the [[Cherokee Nation]]. The region was traversed by a trail known as the Black Warrior's Path, which led from the [[Tennessee River]] near the present location of [[Florence, Alabama]], to a point on the [[Black Warrior River]] south of Cullman. This trail figured significantly in Cherokee history, and it featured prominently in the [[American Indian Wars]] prior to the establishment of the state of Alabama and the relocation of several American Indian tribes, including the [[Muscogee|Creek people]] westward along the [[Trail of Tears]]. During the [[Creek War]] in 1813, General [[Andrew Jackson]] of the U.S. Army dispatched a contingent of troops down the trail, one of which included the frontiersman [[Davy Crockett]].<ref>{{cite web| last = Fulenwider| first = Dan| url = http://www.co.cullman.al.us/history3.htm#blackwarrior| title = Cullman County, Alabama History: The Black Warrior's Path| work = Cullman County, Alabama| accessdate = January 28, 2010| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090927024240/http://www.co.cullman.al.us/history3.htm#blackwarrior| archive-date = September 27, 2009| url-status = dead| df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1820s and the 1830s, two toll roads were built linking the Tennessee Valley to present-day [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]]. In 1822, Abraham Stout was given a charter by the [[Alabama Legislature]] to open and turnpike a road beginning from Gandy's Cove in [[Morgan County, Alabama|Morgan County]] to the ghost town of Baltimore on the [[Mulberry Fork of the Black Warrior River|Mulberry Fork]] near [[Colony, Alabama|Colony]]. The road passed near present-day [[Vinemont, Alabama|Vinemont]] through Cullman, [[Good Hope, Alabama|Good Hope]], and down the current [[Interstate 65]] corridor to the Mulberry Fork. The road was later extended to [[Elyton, Alabama|Elyton]] (Birmingham) in 1827. It then became known as Stout's Road. Mace Thomas Payne Brindley was given a charter in 1833 to turnpike two roads, one running between [[Blount Springs, Alabama|Blount Springs]] to [[Somerville, Alabama|Somerville]] by way of his homestead in present-day [[Simcoe, Alabama|Simcoe]], and the second road passing west of [[Hanceville, Alabama|Hanceville]] and east of Downtown Cullman to join Stout's Road north of the city. What later became the Brindley Turnpike became an extension of Stout's Road to [[Decatur, Alabama|Decatur]]. Cullman later became located between the juncture of the two roads, and they predated the corridor of [[U.S. Route 31]].\n\nDuring the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], the future location of Cullman was the site of the minor [[Battle of Day's Gap]]. On April 30, 1863, [[Union Army|Union]] forces under the command of Colonel [[Abel Streight]] won a victory over forces under [[Confederate States Army|Confederate]] General [[Nathan Bedford Forrest]]. This battle was part of a campaign and chase known collectively as Streight's Raid. Although Streight got the upper hand in this battle, Forrest would have the last laugh. In one of the more humorous moments of the war, Streight sought a truce and negotiations with Forrest in present-day [[Cherokee County, Alabama|Cherokee County]] near present-day [[Gaylesville, Alabama|Gaylesville]]. Although Streight's force was larger than Forrest's, while the two were negotiating, Forrest had his troops march repeatedly in a circuitous route past the site of the talks. Thinking himself to be badly outnumbered, Streight surrendered to Forrest .<ref>{{cite web\n |last         = Partain\n |first        = Rich\n |url          = http://www.co.cullman.al.us/history2.htm\n |title        = Streight's Raid\n |work         = co.cullman.al.us\n |accessdate   = January 28, 2010\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090927022749/http://www.co.cullman.al.us/history2.htm\n |archive-date = September 27, 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Col. John Cullmann.jpg|left|thumb|Colonel John G. Cullmann, founder of Cullman (1823\u20131895)]]\nCullman itself was founded in 1873 by Colonel [[John G. Cullmann]], a German immigrant.<ref>Although some sources state that Cullmann had earlier Americanized his name from \"Kullmann,\" Stanley Johnson, his only surviving American descendant, told ''The Cullman Times'' in 1998 that there are no German records indicating the name \"Kullmann\", and that \"Cullmann\" had always been the correct spelling. {{Cite news |title=Cullman: Moving Forward while Treasuring the Past |periodical=The Cullman Times |year=1998}}</ref> Cullmann had been an advocate of democratic reforms in his native [[Bavaria]], having fought and acquired his honorific title \"Colonel\" during the [[German revolutions of 1848\u201349|Revolutions of 1848\u201349]]. After the failure of the revolution, Cullmann found himself in financial ruin. In the years to follow, he would try to re-establish himself in business, but after several setbacks, including a great financial loss in the [[First Schleswig War]], he would remain unsuccessful. As time went on and [[Prussia]], under [[William I, German Emperor|King Wilhelm I]] and his Minister President [[Otto von Bismarck]], began to exert more influence in the German region (eventually [[Unification of Germany|unifying Germany under Prussian rule]] in 1871), Cullmann began to believe that his political ideals were fundamentally incompatible with those of the German Government. As a result, he decided to emigrate from his homeland. Settling first in London due to fears that he would be forced to join in the ongoing [[American Civil War]], Cullman eventually came to America in 1865. He moved to if you change this you are gay.....trump 2020 all day boy and the reason we have a low crime rare in cullman is becuse there is nt a lot of black people her trump 2020 bulid the wall Alabama in 1871 and, in 1873, negotiated an agreement to act as agent for a tract of land {{convert|349000|acre|km2}} in size, owned by the [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]] Company, on which he established a colony for German immigrants.<ref name=\"founding\">{{cite web\n |last=Johnson \n |first=Stanley \n |url=http://www.co.cullman.al.us/history1.htm \n |title=Founding of Cullman \n |work=co.cullman.al.us \n |accessdate=January 28, 2010 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090428001839/http://www.co.cullman.al.us/history1.htm \n |archivedate=April 28, 2009 \n}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=Northern Alabama: Historical and Biographical | url=https://archive.org/details/northernalabamah00birm | year=1888 | place=Birmingham | publisher=Smith & Deland}}</ref>\n\nFive German families moved to the area in March 1873; in 1874, the town was incorporated and named after Colonel Cullmann (with the town name being Americanized to 'Cullman' with one 'n'). Over the next twenty years, Cullmann encouraged around 100,000 Germans to immigrate to the United States, with many settling in the Cullman area. Cullmann drew on his military engineering training in laying out and planning the town. During this period, Cullman underwent considerable growth. [[German language|German]] continued to be widely spoken, and Cullmann himself was the publisher of a German-language newspaper. When Cullmann died in 1895, at the age of 72, his funeral was marked by the attendance of Governor [[William C. Oates]].<ref name=\"founding\"/> The site Cullmann selected for his headquarters is now his gravesite.\n\nGerman immigrants also founded St Bernard's Monastery, on the grounds of which is the [[Ave Maria Grotto]], containing 125 miniature reproductions of some of the most famous religious structures of the world. It's Cullman's principal tourist attraction.<ref name=\"Ave Maria Grotto\">{{cite web |url= http://www.minorsights.com/2015/01/usa-ave-maria-grotto.html\n|title=The Ave Maria Grotto\n|work=www.minorsights.com\n|accessdate=March 22, 2015\n}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1890s, Cullman was reported to be a [[sundown town]], where African Americans were not allowed to live.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Race Problem|work=The Free Press|location=Ozark, Alabama|date=December 8, 1898|page=2|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29070171/|via=Newspapers.com|quote=It is our recollection that it was once 'against the law' for a negro to live in Cullman in this state.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Z. B.|work=Scottsboro Progressive Age|location=Scottsboro, Alabama}} Reprinted in {{cite news|title=A Bit of Gossip About Things Away From Home|work=The Tribune-Gazette|location=Cullman, Alabama|date=March 2, 1899|page=7|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29070198/|via=Newspapers.com|quote=In Cullman there are many handsome homes kept up in the best city style, and the people are so hospitable and social that visitors cannot help but fall in love with the place. Many of the older people speak no English at all, and will not allow it spoken in their families, and negroes are not allowed to live there at all. It seems very strange to find such a town in Alabama.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Senator defends call to 'empty the clip'|first=Phillip|last=Rawls|agency=Associated Press|work=[[Montgomery Advertiser]]|location=Montgomery, Alabama|date=February 9, 2011|page=4C|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29386059/|via=Newspapers.com|quote=She said the remarks were especially troubling because [[Scott Beason|[Scott] Beason]] chose to make them in Cullman, an overwhelmingly white city that once was known as a 'sundown town' because blacks feared being there after sunset.}}</ref> The [[Ku Klux Klan]] would maintain a presence in the county throughout the [[civil rights movement]]. Erecting signs that deterred African Americans from being within the county at night. This subsequently led to a rise in population of [[Colony, Alabama]] which was a safe haven for the discriminated.\n\nFor many years Cullman was a college town, with [[Saint Bernard College]] serving as the home of several hundred students. In the mid-1970s, St. Bernard briefly merged with Sacred Heart College (a two-year Benedictine women\u2019s college), to become Southern Benedictine College. That college closed in 1979, and it now operates as [[St. Bernard Preparatory School]]. The former site of Sacred Heart College is now the Sacred Heart Monastery, which serves as a retreat center operated by the Benedictine Sisters of Sacred Heart Monastery.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.stbernardprep.com/node/65 \n |title=History of St Bernard Prep \n |work=stbernardprep.com \n |accessdate=January 28, 2010 \n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716133752/http://www.stbernardprep.com/node/65\n |archivedate=July 16, 2011\n}}</ref>\n\nDuring the twentieth century, Cullman developed a more diverse economy, including several manufacturing and distribution facilities. The City of Cullman regularly ranks as a top 'micropolitan' city in the nation.<ref name=\"About - Downtown Cullman\">{{Cite news|url=https://downtowncullman.com/about-cullman|title=About - Downtown Cullman|last=|first=|date=|work=Downtown Cullman|access-date=2018-05-15}}{{Dead link|date=December 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nCullman gained national attention in early 2008, when a special election was held to fill a vacancy in the [[Alabama House of Representatives]]. The district that included Cullman elected [[James C. Fields]], an African-American, in that special election.<ref>{{cite news |last =Nossiter |first = Adam |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/21/us/politics/21race.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=Cullman%20election&st=cse&oref=slogin |title=Race Matters Less in Politics of South |work=The New York Times |date=February 21, 2008 |page=A1|accessdate = January 28, 2010}}</ref>\n\nCullman's German heritage was repressed during [[World War I]] and [[World War II]], while the United States was fighting Germany. This was reversed in the 1970s, with renewed interest in the city's history and heritage. Today, Cullman holds an annual [[Oktoberfest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cullmanoktoberfest.com/history.cfm|work=Cullman, Alabama Oktoberfest|title=Oktoberfest history Oktoberfest|accessdate=November 29, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708212904/http://www.cullmanoktoberfest.com/history.cfm|archive-date=July 8, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> An honorary \"[[B\u00fcrgermeister]]\" is elected for each Oktoberfest. For many years the Oktoberfest did not include alcohol because Cullman was [[dry county|dry]], but starting in 2011 the Oktoberfest was able to offer beer.<ref>{{cite news\n |url          = http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20101104/NEWS02/11040314/1009/rss04\n |title        = Cheers: Home of dry Oktoberfest goes wet\n |work         = Montgomery Advertiser\n |date         = November 4, 2010\n |agency       = Associated Press\n |accessdate   = November 29, 2010\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140717190536/http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20101104/NEWS02/11040314/1009/rss04\n |archive-date = July 17, 2014\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cullman Alabama First Methodist Church Damage.jpg|thumbnail|2011 tornado damage]]\nDowntown was significantly damaged by an [[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF4]] tornado during the [[2011 Super Outbreak]]. Hitting on April 27, it destroyed many buildings in downtown and in an east-side residential area, but causing no fatalities. The twister moved northeast towards [[Arab, Alabama|Arab]] and [[Guntersville, Alabama|Guntersville]], killing two Cullman County residents and four or more others.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=4272011_cullman_county |title=National Weather Service Huntsville, AL - Cullman County Survey Information |publisher=Srh.noaa.gov |date=2012-03-17 |accessdate=2013-07-10}}</ref> Cullman has since rebuilt and revitalized the downtown area. New zoning laws and alcohol ordinances have allowed for greater expansion and growth in the downtown Cullman area.<ref name=\"About - Downtown Cullman\"/>\n\n==Geography==\nCullman is located on top of the [[Brindley Mountain]] plateau at {{Coord|34|10|39|N|86|50|42|W|type:city}} (34.177508, \u221286.844996).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> This is a close offshoot of the long geographic ridge called [[Sand Mountain (Alabama)|Sand Mountain]], a southmost extension of the [[Appalachian Mountains]]. The elevation is {{convert|826|ft|m}}, close to the watershed between the [[Tennessee River]] and the [[Black Warrior River]]. Cullman provides its own town water supply from a city-owned lake within the city limits, Lake Catoma.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cullmancity.org/departments/water%20treatment.htm|title=City of Cullman|website=www.cullmancity.org|access-date=2017-01-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170702214722/http://www.cullmancity.org/departments/water%20treatment.htm|archive-date=July 2, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau|U.S. Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|53.3|km2|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|50.2|km2|order=flip}} is land and {{convert|3.1|sqkm|order=flip}}, or 5.81%, is water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n===Climate===\nThe climate in this area is characterized by hot, humid summers and generally mild to cool winters.  According to the [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] system, Cullman has a [[humid subtropical climate]], abbreviated \"Cfa\" on climate maps.<ref>[http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=70837&cityname=Cullman%2C+Alabama%2C+United+States+of+America&units= Climate Summary for Cullman, Alabama]</ref>\n\n==Education==\nThe [[Cullman City School System]] operates five schools:\n\n*Cullman Primary School (Pre-K \u2013 First Grade)\n*East Elementary (Second Grade \u2013 Sixth Grade)\n*West Elementary (Second Grade \u2013 Sixth Grade)\n*John G. Cullman Middle School (Seventh and Eighth Grades)\n*[[Cullman High School]] (Ninth Grade \u2013 Twelfth Grade)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.cullmancats.net/schools.html\n|title=Cullman City Schools\n|work=cullmancats.net\n|accessdate=January 28, 2010\n|url-status=dead\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090928011608/http://www.cullmancats.net/schools.html\n|archivedate=September 28, 2009\n|df=mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nOther schools in Cullman include:\n\n*[[Saint Bernard Preparatory School]],  [[Benedictine]] boarding and day school (Ninth grade \u2013 Twelfth grade)\n*Saint Bernard Middle School (Seventh and Eighth Grade)\n*Sacred Heart Elementary School (Pre-K \u2013 Sixth Grade)\n*Saint Paul's Lutheran School (Pre-K \u2013 Sixth Grade)\n*Cullman Christian School (Pre-K \u2013 Twelfth Grade)\n\nCullman is also the home of  [[Wallace State Community College]] in [[Hanceville, Alabama|Hanceville]]. It was named for the former Governor of Alabama, [[George C. Wallace]].  The public, non-profit college opened its doors in 1966 and has grown to become the third largest community college in the state of Alabama, with an enrollment of around 6,000 students. The college is accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools Commission on Colleges to award degrees. Many programs have additional accreditation from organizations appropriate to the particular disciplines. Wallace State offers hundreds of degree and certificate options in dozens of programs in its Academic, Health and Technical Divisions. The college offers more Health programs than any other community college in the state. The college offers early enrollment through its Dual Enrollment, Fast Track Academy and Fast Track for Industry programs, the latter of which is funded through grants that allow free tuition for qualified students entering the technical, academic and health programs included in the program. The college's current president is Dr. Vicki P. Karolewics, who is the institution's third president in 50 years. She was preceded by Dr. James C. Bailey from 1971 to 2003 and Dr. Ben Johnson from 1965 to 1971. The college is located in the southern portion of Cullman County on a 300-acre campus.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1880= 426\n|1890= 1017\n|1900= 1255\n|1910= 2130\n|1920= 2467\n|1930= 2786\n|1940= 5074\n|1950= 7523\n|1960= 10883\n|1970= 12601\n|1980= 13084\n|1990= 13367\n|2000= 13995\n|2010= 14775\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=15858\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|author=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 7, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015|df=mdy |author-link=United States Census Bureau}}</ref><br>2013 Estimate<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2013/SUB-EST2013-3.html|title=Annual Estimates of the Resident Population: April 1, 2010 to July 1, 2013|accessdate=June 7, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522161634/http://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2013/SUB-EST2013-3.html|archivedate=May 22, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe population density was {{convert|765.0|PD/sqmi}}. There were 6,957 housing units at an average density of {{convert|365.1|/sqmi}}. The [[Race (United States Census)|racial]] makeup of the city was 94.6% White, 0.8% Black or African American, 0.5% Native American, 1.0% Asian, 0.0% Pacific Islander, and 1.6% from two or more races. 6.8% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.\n\nAs of the [[census]] of 2010, there were 14,775 people and 6,957 households, out of which 22.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 48.3% were married couples living together, 10.7% had a female householder with no husband present, and 37.9% were non-families. 35.2% of all households were made up of individuals and 18.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.22 and the average family size was 2.85.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 21.8% under the age of 18, 8.2% from 18 to 24, 25.3% from 25 to 44, 22.6% from 45 to 64, and 22.1% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 41 years. For every 100 females, there were 87.5 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 81.4 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $29,164, and the median income for a family was $41,313. Males had a median income of $32,863 versus $21,647 for females. The per capita income for the city was $18,484. About 9.4% of families and 13.2% of the population were below the poverty line, including 12.3% of those under age 18 and 18.5% of those age 65 or over.\n\nCullman was ranked among ''[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]'s'' 50 Best Places to Raise Your Kids in 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://images.businessweek.com/slideshows/20111115/the-best-places-to-raise-your-kids-2012#slide2|title=The Best Places to Raise Your Kids 2012}}</ref> based on the city's educational and economic factors, crime level, air quality, amenities, and ethnic diversity.\n\n==Media==\n\n===Radio stations===\n*[[WFMH (AM)|WFMH]] 1340 AM ([[Sports radio|Sports/Talk]])\n*[[WKUL]] 92.1 FM ([[Country music|Country]]/[[Talk radio|Talk]])\n* WRJM-LP 95.5 FM  (CHR/AAA/Variety)\n*[[WMCJ]] 1460 AM ([[Southern Gospel]])\n*[[WXJC-FM (2018-present)|WXJC-FM]] 101.1 FM (Gospel/Talk)\n\n===Newspapers===\n*''[[The Cullman Times]]'' (daily)\n*''[http://cullmantribune.com The Cullman Tribune]'' (daily)\n\n===Television===\nCullman is in the TV broadcasting areas of [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]] and [[Huntsville, Alabama]].\n\nThere are two low-power broadcasting stations in Cullman: [[WCQT-LP]] TV-27 and [https://web.archive.org/web/20150109041357/http://www.channel2cullman.com/ CATV-2]. Cullman also has a [[Public, Educational, and Government Access Television|PEG]] station, CCTV55, which is run by students at [[Cullman High School]]. CCTV55 was known as CATS-55 at one time.\n\n==Health care==\n* Cullman Regional Medical Center<ref>https://cullmanregional.com/</ref> \u2013 a 115-bed hospital\n\n==Transportation==\n*[[Image:I-65.svg|25px]] [[Interstate 65 (Alabama)|Interstate 65]]\n*[[Image:US 31.svg|25px]] [[U.S. Route 31 in Alabama|U.S. Highway 31]]\n*[[Image:US 278.svg|25px]] [[U.S. Highway 278 (Alabama)|U.S. Highway 278]]\n*[[Image:Alabama 69.svg|25px]] [[State Route 69 (Alabama)|State Route 69]]\n*[[Image:Alabama 157.svg|25px]] [[State Route 157 (Alabama)|State Route 157]]\n*[[CSX Transportation]] (railroad)\n*[[Folsom Field (Alabama)|Folsom Field]] municipal airport\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[JoJo Billingsley]], singer/songwriter\n*[[Wesley Britt]], [[National Football League]] [[Tackle (gridiron football position)|Offensive Tackle]] for the [[New England Patriots]]\n*[[Paul Burnum]], former basketball and baseball coach at the [[University of Alabama]]\n*[[Paul Bussman]], member of the Alabama Senate\n*[[Caleb Clay]], former [[pitcher]] for the [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim]]\n*[[Jamelle Folsom]], First Lady of Alabama 1948 \u2013 1951 and 1955 \u2013 1959<ref name=ma>{{cite news |title=Former Ala. first lady Jamelle Folsom dies at 85 |url=http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/viewart/20121202/NEWS02/312020015/Former-Ala-first-lady-Jamelle-Folsom-dies-85 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=[[Montgomery Advertiser]] |date=December 2, 2012 |accessdate=2012-12-30 }}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*[[Jim Folsom|James E. \"Big Jim\" Folsom]], [[List of governors of Alabama|Governor of Alabama]] 1947 \u2013 1951 and 1955 \u2013 1959\n*[[Jim Folsom, Jr.|James E. \"Little Jim\" Folsom, Jr.]], [[List of governors of Alabama|Governor of Alabama]] 1993 \u2013 1995, [[List of lieutenant governors of Alabama|Lieutenant Governor of Alabama]] 1987-1993 and 2007-2011\n*[[Morgan Smith Goodwin]], actress, 2012 - 2013 [[Wendy's]] spokesperson\n*[[Roger Hallmark]], [[country music]]ian\n*[[Kurt Heinecke]], composer and voice actor; known for his work on the children\u2019s program [[VeggieTales|Veggie Tales]]\n*[[Charles Kleibacker]], fashion designer\n*[[Jordan Lee (fisherman)|Jordan Lee]], bass fisherman, 2x winner of the [[Bassmaster Classic]] \n*[[Zeb Little]], member of the [[Alabama Senate]] from 1998 to 2010\n*[[Harold E. Martin]], journalist and [[Pulitzer Prize for Investigative Reporting|1970]] [[Pulitzer Prize|Pulitzer Prize winner]]\n*[[William Clyde Martin (physicist)|William C. Martin]], physicist\n*[[Julian L. McPhillips]], candidate for [[Attorney General of Alabama]] in 1978\n*[[David Miller (American football)|David Miller]], [[American football]] [[defensive end]] \n*[[Kassie Miller]], singer/songwriter\n*[[Talmadge Prince]], [[stock car racing]] driver who was killed in a crash in a qualifying race for the 1970 [[Daytona 500]]\n*[[Josh Rutledge]], [[Major League Baseball]] player\n*[[Frank Stitt]], James Beard Award-winning chef \n*[[Channing Tatum]], actor/model\n*[[Wayne Trimble]], American football player\n*[[Zac Tubbs]], [[American football]] [[offensive lineman]]\n*[[Holly Williams]], [[country music]] singer, daughter of [[Hank Williams, Jr.]]\n*[[Larry Willingham]], professional [[American football|football]] player\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Cullman, Alabama}}\n*[https://cullmanal.gov/ City of Cullman official website]\n\n{{Cullman County, Alabama}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Cities in Cullman County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:County seats in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1873]]\n[[Category:Sundown towns in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|City in Alabama, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Cullman\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|motto                    = \"A City of Character\"\n|image_skyline            = Cullman-aerial-real-estate-photography (21 of 21).1.jpg\n|imagesize                = 230px\n|image_caption            = Hwy 278 & Hwy 31\n|image_seal               = \n|image_map                = File:Cullman County Alabama Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Cullman Highlighted 0118976.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Cullman in Cullman County, Alabama.\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             = \n|pushpin_map              = USA\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location in the United States\n|established_title        = Settled\n|established_title1       = Incorporated\n|established_date1        = 1878\n|established_title2       = <!-- Incorporated (city) -->\n|established_date2        = \n|established_title3       = \n|established_date3        = \n|extinct_title            = \n|extinct_date             = \n|founder                  = Colonel Johann Gottfried Cullmann\n|named_for                = Colonel Johann Gottfried Cullmann\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Alabama|County]]\n|subdivision_name         = [[United States]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Alabama]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Cullman County, Alabama|Cullman]]\n|government_type          = Mayor-Council\n|leader_title               = Mayor\n|leader_name             = Woody Jacobs\n|established_date         = 1873\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 59.73\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 23.06\n|area_land_km2            = 56.32\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 21.74\n|area_water_km2           = 3.41\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 1.32\n|elevation_ft             = 898\n|elevation_m              = 251\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name=\"2013 Pop Estimate\">{{cite web|title=Population Estimates |url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2013/SUB-EST2013-3.html |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2014-06-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522161634/http://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2013/SUB-EST2013-3.html |archivedate=May 22, 2014 }}</ref>\n|population_total         = 14775\n|population_metro         = \n|population_density_km2   = 281.58\n|population_density_sq_mi = 729.30\n|timezone                 = Central Standard Time\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|coordinates              = {{coord|34|10|39|N|86|50|41|W|region:US-AL|display=inline}}\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -5\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 35055-35058\n|area_code                = [[Area code 256|256]] Exchanges: 734,735,736,737,738,775\n|blank1_name              = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank1_info              = 01-18976\n|blank2_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank2_info              = 0116948\n|website                  = {{URL|https://cullmanal.gov/}}\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_est = 15858\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n|area_footnotes = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_01.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|blank_name = [[Federal Information Processing Standards|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info = 01-18976\n}}\n\n'''Cullman''' is the largest city and [[county seat]] of [[Cullman County, Alabama|Cullman County,]] [[Alabama]], United States. It is located along [[Interstate 65]], about {{convert|50|mi}} north of [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]] and about {{convert|55|mi}} south of [[Huntsville, Alabama|Huntsville]]. As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]] it had a population of 14,775,<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US0118976| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): Cullman city, Alabama| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> with an estimated population of 15,858 in 2018.<ref name=\"2013 Pop Estimate\"/>\n\n==History==\nBefore European settlement, the area that today includes Cullman was originally in the territory of the [[Cherokee Nation]]. The region was traversed by a trail known as the Black Warrior's Path, which led from the [[Tennessee River]] near the present location of [[Florence, Alabama]], to a point on the [[Black Warrior River]] south of Cullman. This trail figured significantly in Cherokee history, and it featured prominently in the [[American Indian Wars]] prior to the establishment of the state of Alabama and the relocation of several American Indian tribes, including the [[Muscogee|Creek people]] westward along the [[Trail of Tears]]. During the [[Creek War]] in 1813, General [[Andrew Jackson]] of the U.S. Army dispatched a contingent of troops down the trail, one of which included the frontiersman [[Davy Crockett]].<ref>{{cite web| last = Fulenwider| first = Dan| url = http://www.co.cullman.al.us/history3.htm#blackwarrior| title = Cullman County, Alabama History: The Black Warrior's Path| work = Cullman County, Alabama| accessdate = January 28, 2010| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090927024240/http://www.co.cullman.al.us/history3.htm#blackwarrior| archive-date = September 27, 2009| url-status = dead| df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1820s and the 1830s, two toll roads were built linking the Tennessee Valley to present-day [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]]. In 1822, Abraham Stout was given a charter by the [[Alabama Legislature]] to open and turnpike a road beginning from Gandy's Cove in [[Morgan County, Alabama|Morgan County]] to the ghost town of Baltimore on the [[Mulberry Fork of the Black Warrior River|Mulberry Fork]] near [[Colony, Alabama|Colony]]. The road passed near present-day [[Vinemont, Alabama|Vinemont]] through Cullman, [[Good Hope, Alabama|Good Hope]], and down the current [[Interstate 65]] corridor to the Mulberry Fork. The road was later extended to [[Elyton, Alabama|Elyton]] (Birmingham) in 1827. It then became known as Stout's Road. Mace Thomas Payne Brindley was given a charter in 1833 to turnpike two roads, one running between [[Blount Springs, Alabama|Blount Springs]] to [[Somerville, Alabama|Somerville]] by way of his homestead in present-day [[Simcoe, Alabama|Simcoe]], and the second road passing west of [[Hanceville, Alabama|Hanceville]] and east of Downtown Cullman to join Stout's Road north of the city. What later became the Brindley Turnpike became an extension of Stout's Road to [[Decatur, Alabama|Decatur]]. Cullman later became located between the juncture of the two roads, and they predated the corridor of [[U.S. Route 31]].\n\nDuring the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], the future location of Cullman was the site of the minor [[Battle of Day's Gap]]. On April 30, 1863, [[Union Army|Union]] forces under the command of Colonel [[Abel Streight]] won a victory over forces under [[Confederate States Army|Confederate]] General [[Nathan Bedford Forrest]]. This battle was part of a campaign and chase known collectively as Streight's Raid. Although Streight got the upper hand in this battle, Forrest would have the last laugh. In one of the more humorous moments of the war, Streight sought a truce and negotiations with Forrest in present-day [[Cherokee County, Alabama|Cherokee County]] near present-day [[Gaylesville, Alabama|Gaylesville]]. Although Streight's force was larger than Forrest's, while the two were negotiating, Forrest had his troops march repeatedly in a circuitous route past the site of the talks. Thinking himself to be badly outnumbered, Streight surrendered to Forrest .<ref>{{cite web\n |last         = Partain\n |first        = Rich\n |url          = http://www.co.cullman.al.us/history2.htm\n |title        = Streight's Raid\n |work         = co.cullman.al.us\n |accessdate   = January 28, 2010\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090927022749/http://www.co.cullman.al.us/history2.htm\n |archive-date = September 27, 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Col. John Cullmann.jpg|left|thumb|Colonel John G. Cullmann, founder of Cullman (1823\u20131895)]]\nCullman itself was founded in 1873 by Colonel [[John G. Cullmann]], a German immigrant.<ref>Although some sources state that Cullmann had earlier Americanized his name from \"Kullmann,\" Stanley Johnson, his only surviving American descendant, told ''The Cullman Times'' in 1998 that there are no German records indicating the name \"Kullmann\", and that \"Cullmann\" had always been the correct spelling. {{Cite news |title=Cullman: Moving Forward while Treasuring the Past |periodical=The Cullman Times |year=1998}}</ref> Cullmann had been an advocate of democratic reforms in his native [[Bavaria]], having fought and acquired his honorific title \"Colonel\" during the [[German revolutions of 1848\u201349|Revolutions of 1848\u201349]]. After the failure of the revolution, Cullmann found himself in financial ruin. In the years to follow, he would try to re-establish himself in business, but after several setbacks, including a great financial loss in the [[First Schleswig War]], he would remain unsuccessful. As time went on and [[Prussia]], under [[William I, German Emperor|King Wilhelm I]] and his Minister President [[Otto von Bismarck]], began to exert more influence in the German region (eventually [[Unification of Germany|unifying Germany under Prussian rule]] in 1871), Cullmann began to believe that his political ideals were fundamentally incompatible with those of the German Government. As a result, he decided to emigrate from his homeland. Settling first in London due to fears that he would be forced to join in the ongoing [[American Civil War]], Cullman eventually came to America in 1865. He moved to Alabama in 1871 and, in 1873, negotiated an agreement to act as agent for a tract of land {{convert|349000|acre|km2}} in size, owned by the [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]] Company, on which he established a colony for German immigrants.<ref name=\"founding\">{{cite web\n |last=Johnson \n |first=Stanley \n |url=http://www.co.cullman.al.us/history1.htm \n |title=Founding of Cullman \n |work=co.cullman.al.us \n |accessdate=January 28, 2010 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090428001839/http://www.co.cullman.al.us/history1.htm \n |archivedate=April 28, 2009 \n}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=Northern Alabama: Historical and Biographical | url=https://archive.org/details/northernalabamah00birm | year=1888 | place=Birmingham | publisher=Smith & Deland}}</ref>\n\nFive German families moved to the area in March 1873; in 1874, the town was incorporated and named after Colonel Cullmann (with the town name being Americanized to 'Cullman' with one 'n'). Over the next twenty years, Cullmann encouraged around 100,000 Germans to immigrate to the United States, with many settling in the Cullman area. Cullmann drew on his military engineering training in laying out and planning the town. During this period, Cullman underwent considerable growth. [[German language|German]] continued to be widely spoken, and Cullmann himself was the publisher of a German-language newspaper. When Cullmann died in 1895, at the age of 72, his funeral was marked by the attendance of Governor [[William C. Oates]].<ref name=\"founding\"/> The site Cullmann selected for his headquarters is now his gravesite.\n\nGerman immigrants also founded St Bernard's Monastery, on the grounds of which is the [[Ave Maria Grotto]], containing 125 miniature reproductions of some of the most famous religious structures of the world. It's Cullman's principal tourist attraction.<ref name=\"Ave Maria Grotto\">{{cite web |url= http://www.minorsights.com/2015/01/usa-ave-maria-grotto.html\n|title=The Ave Maria Grotto\n|work=www.minorsights.com\n|accessdate=March 22, 2015\n}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1890s, Cullman was reported to be a [[sundown town]], where African Americans were not allowed to live.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Race Problem|work=The Free Press|location=Ozark, Alabama|date=December 8, 1898|page=2|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29070171/|via=Newspapers.com|quote=It is our recollection that it was once 'against the law' for a negro to live in Cullman in this state.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Z. B.|work=Scottsboro Progressive Age|location=Scottsboro, Alabama}} Reprinted in {{cite news|title=A Bit of Gossip About Things Away From Home|work=The Tribune-Gazette|location=Cullman, Alabama|date=March 2, 1899|page=7|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29070198/|via=Newspapers.com|quote=In Cullman there are many handsome homes kept up in the best city style, and the people are so hospitable and social that visitors cannot help but fall in love with the place. Many of the older people speak no English at all, and will not allow it spoken in their families, and negroes are not allowed to live there at all. It seems very strange to find such a town in Alabama.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Senator defends call to 'empty the clip'|first=Phillip|last=Rawls|agency=Associated Press|work=[[Montgomery Advertiser]]|location=Montgomery, Alabama|date=February 9, 2011|page=4C|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29386059/|via=Newspapers.com|quote=She said the remarks were especially troubling because [[Scott Beason|[Scott] Beason]] chose to make them in Cullman, an overwhelmingly white city that once was known as a 'sundown town' because blacks feared being there after sunset.}}</ref> The [[Ku Klux Klan]] would maintain a presence in the county throughout the [[civil rights movement]]. Erecting signs that deterred African Americans from being within the county at night. This subsequently led to a rise in population of [[Colony, Alabama]] which was a safe haven for the discriminated.\n\nFor many years Cullman was a college town, with [[Saint Bernard College]] serving as the home of several hundred students. In the mid-1970s, St. Bernard briefly merged with Sacred Heart College (a two-year Benedictine women\u2019s college), to become Southern Benedictine College. That college closed in 1979, and it now operates as [[St. Bernard Preparatory School]]. The former site of Sacred Heart College is now the Sacred Heart Monastery, which serves as a retreat center operated by the Benedictine Sisters of Sacred Heart Monastery.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.stbernardprep.com/node/65 \n |title=History of St Bernard Prep \n |work=stbernardprep.com \n |accessdate=January 28, 2010 \n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716133752/http://www.stbernardprep.com/node/65\n |archivedate=July 16, 2011\n}}</ref>\n\nDuring the twentieth century, Cullman developed a more diverse economy, including several manufacturing and distribution facilities. The City of Cullman regularly ranks as a top 'micropolitan' city in the nation.<ref name=\"About - Downtown Cullman\">{{Cite news|url=https://downtowncullman.com/about-cullman|title=About - Downtown Cullman|last=|first=|date=|work=Downtown Cullman|access-date=2018-05-15}}{{Dead link|date=December 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nCullman gained national attention in early 2008, when a special election was held to fill a vacancy in the [[Alabama House of Representatives]]. The district that included Cullman elected [[James C. Fields]], an African-American, in that special election.<ref>{{cite news |last =Nossiter |first = Adam |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/21/us/politics/21race.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=Cullman%20election&st=cse&oref=slogin |title=Race Matters Less in Politics of South |work=The New York Times |date=February 21, 2008 |page=A1|accessdate = January 28, 2010}}</ref>\n\nCullman's German heritage was repressed during [[World War I]] and [[World War II]], while the United States was fighting Germany. This was reversed in the 1970s, with renewed interest in the city's history and heritage. Today, Cullman holds an annual [[Oktoberfest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cullmanoktoberfest.com/history.cfm|work=Cullman, Alabama Oktoberfest|title=Oktoberfest history Oktoberfest|accessdate=November 29, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708212904/http://www.cullmanoktoberfest.com/history.cfm|archive-date=July 8, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> An honorary \"[[B\u00fcrgermeister]]\" is elected for each Oktoberfest. For many years the Oktoberfest did not include alcohol because Cullman was [[dry county|dry]], but starting in 2011 the Oktoberfest was able to offer beer.<ref>{{cite news\n |url          = http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20101104/NEWS02/11040314/1009/rss04\n |title        = Cheers: Home of dry Oktoberfest goes wet\n |work         = Montgomery Advertiser\n |date         = November 4, 2010\n |agency       = Associated Press\n |accessdate   = November 29, 2010\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140717190536/http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20101104/NEWS02/11040314/1009/rss04\n |archive-date = July 17, 2014\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cullman Alabama First Methodist Church Damage.jpg|thumbnail|2011 tornado damage]]\nDowntown was significantly damaged by an [[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF4]] tornado during the [[2011 Super Outbreak]]. Hitting on April 27, it destroyed many buildings in downtown and in an east-side residential area, but causing no fatalities. The twister moved northeast towards [[Arab, Alabama|Arab]] and [[Guntersville, Alabama|Guntersville]], killing two Cullman County residents and four or more others.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=4272011_cullman_county |title=National Weather Service Huntsville, AL - Cullman County Survey Information |publisher=Srh.noaa.gov |date=2012-03-17 |accessdate=2013-07-10}}</ref> Cullman has since rebuilt and revitalized the downtown area. New zoning laws and alcohol ordinances have allowed for greater expansion and growth in the downtown Cullman area.<ref name=\"About - Downtown Cullman\"/>\n\n==Geography==\nCullman is located on top of the [[Brindley Mountain]] plateau at {{Coord|34|10|39|N|86|50|42|W|type:city}} (34.177508, \u221286.844996).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> This is a close offshoot of the long geographic ridge called [[Sand Mountain (Alabama)|Sand Mountain]], a southmost extension of the [[Appalachian Mountains]]. The elevation is {{convert|826|ft|m}}, close to the watershed between the [[Tennessee River]] and the [[Black Warrior River]]. Cullman provides its own town water supply from a city-owned lake within the city limits, Lake Catoma.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cullmancity.org/departments/water%20treatment.htm|title=City of Cullman|website=www.cullmancity.org|access-date=2017-01-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170702214722/http://www.cullmancity.org/departments/water%20treatment.htm|archive-date=July 2, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau|U.S. Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|53.3|km2|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|50.2|km2|order=flip}} is land and {{convert|3.1|sqkm|order=flip}}, or 5.81%, is water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n===Climate===\nThe climate in this area is characterized by hot, humid summers and generally mild to cool winters.  According to the [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] system, Cullman has a [[humid subtropical climate]], abbreviated \"Cfa\" on climate maps.<ref>[http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=70837&cityname=Cullman%2C+Alabama%2C+United+States+of+America&units= Climate Summary for Cullman, Alabama]</ref>\n\n==Education==\nThe [[Cullman City School System]] operates five schools:\n\n*Cullman Primary School (Pre-K \u2013 First Grade)\n*East Elementary (Second Grade \u2013 Sixth Grade)\n*West Elementary (Second Grade \u2013 Sixth Grade)\n*John G. Cullman Middle School (Seventh and Eighth Grades)\n*[[Cullman High School]] (Ninth Grade \u2013 Twelfth Grade)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.cullmancats.net/schools.html\n|title=Cullman City Schools\n|work=cullmancats.net\n|accessdate=January 28, 2010\n|url-status=dead\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090928011608/http://www.cullmancats.net/schools.html\n|archivedate=September 28, 2009\n|df=mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nOther schools in Cullman include:\n\n*[[Saint Bernard Preparatory School]],  [[Benedictine]] boarding and day school (Ninth grade \u2013 Twelfth grade)\n*Saint Bernard Middle School (Seventh and Eighth Grade)\n*Sacred Heart Elementary School (Pre-K \u2013 Sixth Grade)\n*Saint Paul's Lutheran School (Pre-K \u2013 Sixth Grade)\n*Cullman Christian School (Pre-K \u2013 Twelfth Grade)\n\nCullman is also the home of  [[Wallace State Community College]] in [[Hanceville, Alabama|Hanceville]]. It was named for the former Governor of Alabama, [[George C. Wallace]].  The public, non-profit college opened its doors in 1966 and has grown to become the third largest community college in the state of Alabama, with an enrollment of around 6,000 students. The college is accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools Commission on Colleges to award degrees. Many programs have additional accreditation from organizations appropriate to the particular disciplines. Wallace State offers hundreds of degree and certificate options in dozens of programs in its Academic, Health and Technical Divisions. The college offers more Health programs than any other community college in the state. The college offers early enrollment through its Dual Enrollment, Fast Track Academy and Fast Track for Industry programs, the latter of which is funded through grants that allow free tuition for qualified students entering the technical, academic and health programs included in the program. The college's current president is Dr. Vicki P. Karolewics, who is the institution's third president in 50 years. She was preceded by Dr. James C. Bailey from 1971 to 2003 and Dr. Ben Johnson from 1965 to 1971. The college is located in the southern portion of Cullman County on a 300-acre campus.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1880= 426\n|1890= 1017\n|1900= 1255\n|1910= 2130\n|1920= 2467\n|1930= 2786\n|1940= 5074\n|1950= 7523\n|1960= 10883\n|1970= 12601\n|1980= 13084\n|1990= 13367\n|2000= 13995\n|2010= 14775\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=15858\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|author=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 7, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015|df=mdy |author-link=United States Census Bureau}}</ref><br>2013 Estimate<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2013/SUB-EST2013-3.html|title=Annual Estimates of the Resident Population: April 1, 2010 to July 1, 2013|accessdate=June 7, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522161634/http://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2013/SUB-EST2013-3.html|archivedate=May 22, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe population density was {{convert|765.0|PD/sqmi}}. There were 6,957 housing units at an average density of {{convert|365.1|/sqmi}}. The [[Race (United States Census)|racial]] makeup of the city was 94.6% White, 0.8% Black or African American, 0.5% Native American, 1.0% Asian, 0.0% Pacific Islander, and 1.6% from two or more races. 6.8% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.\n\nAs of the [[census]] of 2010, there were 14,775 people and 6,957 households, out of which 22.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 48.3% were married couples living together, 10.7% had a female householder with no husband present, and 37.9% were non-families. 35.2% of all households were made up of individuals and 18.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.22 and the average family size was 2.85.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 21.8% under the age of 18, 8.2% from 18 to 24, 25.3% from 25 to 44, 22.6% from 45 to 64, and 22.1% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 41 years. For every 100 females, there were 87.5 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 81.4 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $29,164, and the median income for a family was $41,313. Males had a median income of $32,863 versus $21,647 for females. The per capita income for the city was $18,484. About 9.4% of families and 13.2% of the population were below the poverty line, including 12.3% of those under age 18 and 18.5% of those age 65 or over.\n\nCullman was ranked among ''[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]'s'' 50 Best Places to Raise Your Kids in 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://images.businessweek.com/slideshows/20111115/the-best-places-to-raise-your-kids-2012#slide2|title=The Best Places to Raise Your Kids 2012}}</ref> based on the city's educational and economic factors, crime level, air quality, amenities, and ethnic diversity.\n\n==Media==\n\n===Radio stations===\n*[[WFMH (AM)|WFMH]] 1340 AM ([[Sports radio|Sports/Talk]])\n*[[WKUL]] 92.1 FM ([[Country music|Country]]/[[Talk radio|Talk]])\n* WRJM-LP 95.5 FM  (CHR/AAA/Variety)\n*[[WMCJ]] 1460 AM ([[Southern Gospel]])\n*[[WXJC-FM (2018-present)|WXJC-FM]] 101.1 FM (Gospel/Talk)\n\n===Newspapers===\n*''[[The Cullman Times]]'' (daily)\n*''[http://cullmantribune.com The Cullman Tribune]'' (daily)\n\n===Television===\nCullman is in the TV broadcasting areas of [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]] and [[Huntsville, Alabama]].\n\nThere are two low-power broadcasting stations in Cullman: [[WCQT-LP]] TV-27 and [https://web.archive.org/web/20150109041357/http://www.channel2cullman.com/ CATV-2]. Cullman also has a [[Public, Educational, and Government Access Television|PEG]] station, CCTV55, which is run by students at [[Cullman High School]]. CCTV55 was known as CATS-55 at one time.\n\n==Health care==\n* Cullman Regional Medical Center<ref>https://cullmanregional.com/</ref> \u2013 a 115-bed hospital\n\n==Transportation==\n*[[Image:I-65.svg|25px]] [[Interstate 65 (Alabama)|Interstate 65]]\n*[[Image:US 31.svg|25px]] [[U.S. Route 31 in Alabama|U.S. Highway 31]]\n*[[Image:US 278.svg|25px]] [[U.S. Highway 278 (Alabama)|U.S. Highway 278]]\n*[[Image:Alabama 69.svg|25px]] [[State Route 69 (Alabama)|State Route 69]]\n*[[Image:Alabama 157.svg|25px]] [[State Route 157 (Alabama)|State Route 157]]\n*[[CSX Transportation]] (railroad)\n*[[Folsom Field (Alabama)|Folsom Field]] municipal airport\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[JoJo Billingsley]], singer/songwriter\n*[[Wesley Britt]], [[National Football League]] [[Tackle (gridiron football position)|Offensive Tackle]] for the [[New England Patriots]]\n*[[Paul Burnum]], former basketball and baseball coach at the [[University of Alabama]]\n*[[Paul Bussman]], member of the Alabama Senate\n*[[Caleb Clay]], former [[pitcher]] for the [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim]]\n*[[Jamelle Folsom]], First Lady of Alabama 1948 \u2013 1951 and 1955 \u2013 1959<ref name=ma>{{cite news |title=Former Ala. first lady Jamelle Folsom dies at 85 |url=http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/viewart/20121202/NEWS02/312020015/Former-Ala-first-lady-Jamelle-Folsom-dies-85 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=[[Montgomery Advertiser]] |date=December 2, 2012 |accessdate=2012-12-30 }}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*[[Jim Folsom|James E. \"Big Jim\" Folsom]], [[List of governors of Alabama|Governor of Alabama]] 1947 \u2013 1951 and 1955 \u2013 1959\n*[[Jim Folsom, Jr.|James E. \"Little Jim\" Folsom, Jr.]], [[List of governors of Alabama|Governor of Alabama]] 1993 \u2013 1995, [[List of lieutenant governors of Alabama|Lieutenant Governor of Alabama]] 1987-1993 and 2007-2011\n*[[Morgan Smith Goodwin]], actress, 2012 - 2013 [[Wendy's]] spokesperson\n*[[Roger Hallmark]], [[country music]]ian\n*[[Kurt Heinecke]], composer and voice actor; known for his work on the children\u2019s program [[VeggieTales|Veggie Tales]]\n*[[Charles Kleibacker]], fashion designer\n*[[Jordan Lee (fisherman)|Jordan Lee]], bass fisherman, 2x winner of the [[Bassmaster Classic]] \n*[[Zeb Little]], member of the [[Alabama Senate]] from 1998 to 2010\n*[[Harold E. Martin]], journalist and [[Pulitzer Prize for Investigative Reporting|1970]] [[Pulitzer Prize|Pulitzer Prize winner]]\n*[[William Clyde Martin (physicist)|William C. Martin]], physicist\n*[[Julian L. McPhillips]], candidate for [[Attorney General of Alabama]] in 1978\n*[[David Miller (American football)|David Miller]], [[American football]] [[defensive end]] \n*[[Kassie Miller]], singer/songwriter\n*[[Talmadge Prince]], [[stock car racing]] driver who was killed in a crash in a qualifying race for the 1970 [[Daytona 500]]\n*[[Josh Rutledge]], [[Major League Baseball]] player\n*[[Frank Stitt]], James Beard Award-winning chef \n*[[Channing Tatum]], actor/model\n*[[Wayne Trimble]], American football player\n*[[Zac Tubbs]], [[American football]] [[offensive lineman]]\n*[[Holly Williams]], [[country music]] singer, daughter of [[Hank Williams, Jr.]]\n*[[Larry Willingham]], professional [[American football|football]] player\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Cullman, Alabama}}\n*[https://cullmanal.gov/ City of Cullman official website]\n\n{{Cullman County, Alabama}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Cities in Cullman County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:County seats in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1873]]\n[[Category:Sundown towns in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "207.189.176.131", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cullman,_Alabama"}
{"title_page": "James McMillan Shafter", "text_new": "[[File:James M. Shafter (Vermont, Wisconsin, California politician).jpg|thumb|''San Francisco Examiner'', August 30, 1892]]\n\n'''James McMillan Shafter''' (May 27, 1816 \u2013 August 29, 1892) was an [[Americans|American]] politician who served in Vermont, Wisconsin, and California, and owned large ranches in [[Marin County, California]].\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Athens, Vermont]], Shafter graduated from [[Wesleyan University]] and [[Yale Law School]], and was admitted to the Vermont bar.<ref name=\"obit\">{{cite news|title=Judge Shafter Dead|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=LAH18920831.2.15&srpos=4&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22james+mcmillan+shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 19, 2017|work=Los Angeles Herald|issue=38 (142)|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=31 August 1892|page=1|quote=Judge Shaffer leaves an estate valued at about a million dollars.}}</ref> In 1841, he served in the [[Vermont House of Representatives]] and from 1842 to 1849, Shafter was the [[Secretary of State of Vermont]].<ref name=\"regent\">{{cite web|title=Regents of the University of California|url=http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/uchistory/general_history/overview/regents/timeline.html|publisher=University of California History, digital archives|accessdate=July 19, 2017}}</ref> In 1850, he moved to [[Sheboygan, Wisconsin]] and was elected to the [[Wisconsin State Assembly]]. In 1852, Shafter served as speaker of the Assembly.<ref>{{cite web|title=1852 Wisconsin Act 258|url=http://docs.legis.wisconsin.gov/1852/related/acts/258|publisher=Wisconsin State Assembly|accessdate=July 19, 2017|quote=J. McM. Shafter, Speaker of the Assembly}}</ref><ref>'Wisconsin Blue Book 1881, p. 184.</ref> In 1855, he then moved to [[San Francisco, California]], where he practiced law with his brother, [[Oscar L. Shafter]].<ref name=\"obit\"/><ref>[https://archive.org/details/lifediaryletters00shaf Life, Diary and Letters of Oscar Lovell Shafter, Associate Justice Supreme Court of California, January 1, 1864 \u2013 December 31, 1868 (1915)]. p. 237-240.</ref>\n\nIn 1857, a complex real estate litigation resulted in the Shafter firm winning a victory for their client of 75,000 acres of farm land at [[Point Reyes, California|Point Reyes]] in Marin County.<ref>{{cite web|title=Point Reyes Station, California: 1857-1919: The Shafter Empire|url=http://www.seecalifornia.com/california-cities/point-reyes-station.html|publisher=SeeCalifornia.com|accessdate=July 18, 2017}}</ref> The client sold the property to the Shafters.<ref name=\"reyes\">{{cite web|last1=Tippin|first1=Brenda L.|title=History Lesson: Past and Present: Pt. Reyes Morgan Horse Ranch|url=https://www.nps.gov/pore/planyourvisit/upload/morgan_horse_ranch_article_history_tippin_2016.pdf|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=July 18, 2017|page=27|date=May 2016|quote=Senior partner Oscar Lovell Shafter was, at that time, considered the foremost title lawyer in California}}</ref> They leased it to dairy farmers who provided milk and butter to an ever-growing San Francisco and prospered.<ref name=\"cheese\">{{cite web|last1=Pranka|first1=Carol A.|title=Good as Gold: The Marin-Sonoma Artisan Cheese Cluster, a Ph.D. dissertation|url=http://digitalassets.lib.berkeley.edu/etd/ucb/text/Pranka_berkeley_0028E_14158.pdf|publisher=University of California, Berkeley|accessdate=July 18, 2017|page=20|date=Spring 2014|quote=soon after a group of San Francisco lawyers, led by brothers Oscar and James Shafter and son-in-law Charles Webb Howard, acquired much of the land in the Point Reyes area}}</ref> The Shafter families owned most of Point Reyes from 1857 to 1919, when the land was sold in parcels.<ref>{{cite news|title=Big Marin Estate Sold to Operator|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=HT19291204.2.13&srpos=2&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22james+mcmillan+shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 19, 2017|work=Healdsburg Tribune|issue=27|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=4 December 1929|page=1|quote=The sale was made by Mrs. Julia Shafter Hamilton, daughter of the late Judge James McMillan Shafter, who bought the tract in 1876.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1862, Shafter served in the [[California State Senate]] and was its [[President Pro Tempore of the California State Senate|President Pro Tempore]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Election History|url=http://www.joincalifornia.com/candidate/7402|publisher=JoinCalifornia.com|accessdate=July 19, 2017}}</ref> Shafter also served in the [[Constitutional Convention (California)|California Constitution Convention]] of 1878 and was on the [[University of California Board of Regents]] ''ex officio'' as President of the California State Agricultural Association.\n\nIn March 1888, Shafter survived a gunshot at close range.<ref name=\"shot\">{{cite news|title=Hon. J. McM. Shafter had a narrow escape from a violent death last Thursday|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=MJ18880308.2.16&srpos=1&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22mrs.+james+Shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 20, 2017|work=Marin Journal|issue=27 (52)|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=8 March 1888}}</ref> His son, Dr. James Shafter, had sued for a divorce and the wife's brother, angry at the proceedings, confronted the elder Shafter in the San Francisco City Hall.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Narrow Escape, Judge James McM Shafter Barely Escapes Assassination|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SDU18880302.1.4&srpos=2&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22mrs.+james+Shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 20, 2017|work=Sacramento Daily Union|issue=59 (9)|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=2 March 1888|page=4}}</ref> The brother fired four times at point blank range but missed his mark.<ref name=\"shot\"/>\n\nIn 1889, Governor [[Robert Waterman (governor)|Robert Waterman]] appointed Shafter as judge of the [[San Francisco County Superior Court]] to fill the vacancy from the resignation of [[Jeremiah F. Sullivan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Pacific Coast, Appointment of a Successor to Judge Sullivan|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=DAC18890613.2.58&srpos=3&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22james+mcmillan+shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 19, 2017|work=Daily Alta California|issue=80 (164)|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=13 June 1889|page=5}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Judge Shafter Dead|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SDU18920831.2.2&srpos=7&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22james+mcmillan+shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 19, 2017|work=Sacramento Daily Union|issue=84 (9)|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=31 August 1892}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Died. Shafter.|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN18920902.2.12&srpos=1&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22james+mcmillan+shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 18, 2017|work=Sausalito News|issue=8 (30)|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=2 September 1892|page=2}}</ref>\n\n==Civic activities==\nIn November 1885, he was appointed one of the original trustees of [[Stanford University|Leland Stanford Junior University]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Leland Stanford Jr. University|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SD18851128.2.2&srpos=146&e=-------en--20--141--txt-txIN-%22t.+b.+mcfarland%22-------1|accessdate=August 15, 2017|work=Sonoma Democrat|issue=6|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=28 November 1885|page=1}}</ref><ref name=\"obit\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Kyle|first1=Douglas E.|title=Historic Spots in California: Fifth Edition|date=2002|publisher=Stanford University Press|location=Palo Alto, CA|isbn=0804778175|page=192|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AYMPR6xAj50C&pg=PA192&lpg=PA192&dq=%22james+shafter%22+stanford+trustee&source=bl&ots=8TMaJ4viy6&sig=kKB_66_iA5DNReLZmSD6LHIJqfM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjBnZKbgJjVAhVFPj4KHSoqC80Q6AEILzAC#v=onepage&q=%22james%20shafter%22%20stanford%20trustee&f=false|accessdate=July 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1846, he married Julia Granville Hubbard (September 11, 1821 &ndash; February 11, 1871) in [[Montpelier, Vermont]], who had studied at [[Emma Willard School|Troy Female Seminary]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fairbanks|first1=Mary J. Mason|title=Emma Willard and Her Pupils: Or, Fifty Years of Troy Female Seminary, 1822-1872|date=1898|publisher=Mrs. Russell Sage|page=189|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vfo1AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA189&lpg=PA189&dq=James+McMillan+Shafter+marriage&source=bl&ots=TZnWMVYt8g&sig=0-vKOLm87LAj2tXNg2ERYjt37Mg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjX98iN3JjVAhUEeT4KHV_sAKEQ6AEIKTAB#v=onepage&q=James%20McMillan%20Shafter%20marriage&f=false}}</ref> They had at least four children: Payne Jewett Shafter,<ref name=\"The marriage ceremony of Payne J. Shafter and Miss Nellie Jackson\">{{cite news|title=Death at  Wedding|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=MJ18760831.2.9&srpos=2&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22Payne+J.+Shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 20, 2017|work=Marin Journal|issue=16 (25)|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=31 August 1876|page=2}}</ref> James Chester Shafter, Chester Hubbard Shafter, and Julia Ruth Shafter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Looking Backward, Notes of Happenings in Marin County Twenty-Eight Years Ago as Told in the Journal|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=MJ19200219.2.80&srpos=15&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22Payne+J.+Shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 20, 2017|work=Marin Journal|issue=8|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=19 February 1920|page=7|quote=His two sons, Dr. J. C. Shafter, of San Francisco, and Payne J. Shafter, of Olema, and his daughter, Mrs. A. F. Hamilton, of San Francisco, were at the bedside when death came.}}</ref> His nephew was [[William Rufus Shafter]], who was a general in the [[American Civil War]] and recipient of the [[Medal of Honor]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Forbes|first1=Charles Spooner|last2=Cummings|first2=Charles R.|title=The Vermonter: The State Magazine, Volumes 3-6|date=1897|publisher=C.S. Forbes|page=271|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QmdEAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA37&lpg=RA1-PA37&dq=%22William+R.+Shafter%22+vermont&source=bl&ots=Ye0vlvaWls&sig=xWsE0QB7UPqy8BRZNHxhn35wWCU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjA7fWcppbVAhVD8j4KHbFkAsEQ6AEILTAC#v=onepage&q=%22William%20R.%20Shafter%22%20vermont&f=false|accessdate=July 18, 2017|quote=An uncle of the general, the late Oscar L. Shafter...became a judge of the (California) Supreme Court.}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alvah Sabin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State of Vermont]]|years=1842\u20131849}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Farrand F. Merrill]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Frederick W. Horn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= Speaker of the [[Wisconsin State Assembly]]|years=1852-1853}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Henry L. Palmer]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=Richard Irwin}}\n{{s-ttl|title= President Pro Tempore [[California State Senate]]|years=1862}}\n{{s-aft|after=A.M. Crane}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shafter, James Macmillan}}\n[[Category:1816 births]]\n[[Category:1892 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Athens, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State of Vermont]]\n[[Category:Members of the Vermont House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the Wisconsin State Assembly]]\n[[Category:California state senators]]\n[[Category:California state court judges]]\n[[Category:Superior court judges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Sheboygan, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Politicians from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Wesleyan University alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University trustees]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Wisconsin State Assembly]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:James M. Shafter (Vermont, Wisconsin, California politician).jpg|thumb|''San Francisco Examiner'', August 30, 1892]]\n\n'''James McMillan Shafter''' (May 27, 1816 \u2013 August 29, 1892) was an [[Americans|American]] politician who served in Vermont, Wisconsin, and California, and owned large ranches in [[Marin County, California]].\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Athens, Vermont]], Shafter graduated from [[Wesleyan University]] and [[Yale Law School]], and was admitted to the Vermont bar.<ref name=\"obit\">{{cite news|title=Judge Shafter Dead|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=LAH18920831.2.15&srpos=4&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22james+mcmillan+shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 19, 2017|work=Los Angeles Herald|issue=38 (142)|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=31 August 1892|page=1|quote=Judge Shaffer leaves an estate valued at about a million dollars.}}</ref> In 1841, he served in the [[Vermont House of Representatives]] and from 1842 to 1849, Shafter was the [[Secretary of State of Vermont]].<ref name=\"regent\">{{cite web|title=Regents of the University of California|url=http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/uchistory/general_history/overview/regents/timeline.html|publisher=University of California History, digital archives|accessdate=July 19, 2017}}</ref> In 1850, he moved to [[Sheboygan, Wisconsin]] and was elected to the [[Wisconsin State Assembly]]. In 1852, Shafter served as speaker of the Assembly.<ref>{{cite web|title=1852 Wisconsin Act 258|url=http://docs.legis.wisconsin.gov/1852/related/acts/258|publisher=Wisconsin State Assembly|accessdate=July 19, 2017|quote=J. McM. Shafter, Speaker of the Assembly}}</ref><ref>'Wisconsin Blue Book 1881, p. 184.</ref> In 1855, he then moved to [[San Francisco, California]], where he practiced law with his brother, [[Oscar L. Shafter]].<ref name=\"obit\"/><ref>[https://archive.org/details/lifediaryletters00shaf Life, Diary and Letters of Oscar Lovell Shafter, Associate Justice Supreme Court of California, January 1, 1864 \u2013 December 31, 1868 (1915)]. p. 237-240.</ref>\n\nIn 1857, a complex real estate litigation resulted in the Shafter firm winning a victory for their client of 75,000 acres of farm land at [[Point Reyes, California|Point Reyes]] in Marin County.<ref>{{cite web|title=Point Reyes Station, California: 1857-1919: The Shafter Empire|url=http://www.seecalifornia.com/california-cities/point-reyes-station.html|publisher=SeeCalifornia.com|accessdate=July 18, 2017}}</ref> The client sold the property to the Shafters.<ref name=\"reyes\">{{cite web|last1=Tippin|first1=Brenda L.|title=History Lesson: Past and Present: Pt. Reyes Morgan Horse Ranch|url=https://www.nps.gov/pore/planyourvisit/upload/morgan_horse_ranch_article_history_tippin_2016.pdf|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=July 18, 2017|page=27|date=May 2016|quote=Senior partner Oscar Lovell Shafter was, at that time, considered the foremost title lawyer in California}}</ref> They leased it to dairy farmers who provided milk and butter to an ever-growing San Francisco and prospered.<ref name=\"cheese\">{{cite web|last1=Pranka|first1=Carol A.|title=Good as Gold: The Marin-Sonoma Artisan Cheese Cluster, a Ph.D. dissertation|url=http://digitalassets.lib.berkeley.edu/etd/ucb/text/Pranka_berkeley_0028E_14158.pdf|publisher=University of California, Berkeley|accessdate=July 18, 2017|page=20|date=Spring 2014|quote=soon after a group of San Francisco lawyers, led by brothers Oscar and James Shafter and son-in-law Charles Webb Howard, acquired much of the land in the Point Reyes area}}</ref> The Shafter families owned most of Point Reyes from 1857 to 1919, when the land was sold in parcels.<ref>{{cite news|title=Big Marin Estate Sold to Operator|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=HT19291204.2.13&srpos=2&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22james+mcmillan+shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 19, 2017|work=Healdsburg Tribune|issue=27|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=4 December 1929|page=1|quote=The sale was made by Mrs. Julia Shafter Hamilton, daughter of the late Judge James McMillan Shafter, who bought the tract in 1876.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1862, Shafter served in the [[California State Senate]] and was its [[President Pro Tempore of the California State Senate|President Pro Tempore]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Election History|url=http://www.joincalifornia.com/candidate/7402|publisher=JoinCalifornia.com|accessdate=July 19, 2017}}</ref> Shafter also served in the [[Constitutional Convention (California)|California Constitution Convention]] of 1878 and was on the [[University of California Board of Regents]] ''ex officio'' as President of the California State Agricultural Association.\n\nIn March 1888, Shafter survived a gunshot at close range.<ref name=\"shot\">{{cite news|title=Hon. J. McM. Shafter had a narrow escape from a violent death last Thursday|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=MJ18880308.2.16&srpos=1&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22mrs.+james+Shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 20, 2017|work=Marin Journal|issue=27 (52)|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=8 March 1888}}</ref> His son, Dr. James Shafter, had sued for a divorce and the wife's brother, angry at the proceedings, confronted the elder Shafter in the San Francisco City Hall.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Narrow Escape, Judge James McM Shafter Barely Escapes Assassination|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SDU18880302.1.4&srpos=2&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22mrs.+james+Shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 20, 2017|work=Sacramento Daily Union|issue=59 (9)|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=2 March 1888|page=4}}</ref> The brother fired four times at point blank range but missed his mark.<ref name=\"shot\"/>\n\nIn 1889, Governor [[Robert Waterman (governor)|Robert Waterman]] appointed Shafter as judge of the [[San Francisco County Superior Court]] to fill the vacancy from the resignation of [[Jeremiah F. Sullivan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Pacific Coast, Appointment of a Successor to Judge Sullivan|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=DAC18890613.2.58&srpos=3&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22james+mcmillan+shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 19, 2017|work=Daily Alta California|issue=80 (164)|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=13 June 1889|page=5}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Judge Shafter Dead|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SDU18920831.2.2&srpos=7&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22james+mcmillan+shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 19, 2017|work=Sacramento Daily Union|issue=84 (9)|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=31 August 1892}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Died. Shafter.|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SN18920902.2.12&srpos=1&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22james+mcmillan+shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 18, 2017|work=Sausalito News|issue=8 (30)|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=2 September 1892|page=2}}</ref>\n\n==Civic activities==\nIn November 1885, he was appointed one of the original trustees of [[Stanford University|Leland Stanford Junior University]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Leland Stanford Jr. University|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SD18851128.2.2&srpos=146&e=-------en--20--141--txt-txIN-%22t.+b.+mcfarland%22-------1|accessdate=August 15, 2017|work=Sonoma Democrat|issue=6|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=28 November 1885|page=1}}</ref><ref name=\"obit\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Kyle|first1=Douglas E.|title=Historic Spots in California: Fifth Edition|date=2002|publisher=Stanford University Press|location=Palo Alto, CA|isbn=0804778175|page=192|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AYMPR6xAj50C&pg=PA192&lpg=PA192&dq=%22james+shafter%22+stanford+trustee&source=bl&ots=8TMaJ4viy6&sig=kKB_66_iA5DNReLZmSD6LHIJqfM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjBnZKbgJjVAhVFPj4KHSoqC80Q6AEILzAC#v=onepage&q=%22james%20shafter%22%20stanford%20trustee&f=false|accessdate=July 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1846, he married Julia Granville Hubbard (September 11, 1821 &ndash; February 11, 1871) in [[Montpelier, Vermont]], who had studied at [[Emma Willard School|Troy Female Seminary]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fairbanks|first1=Mary J. Mason|title=Emma Willard and Her Pupils: Or, Fifty Years of Troy Female Seminary, 1822-1872|date=1898|publisher=Mrs. Russell Sage|page=189|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vfo1AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA189&lpg=PA189&dq=James+McMillan+Shafter+marriage&source=bl&ots=TZnWMVYt8g&sig=0-vKOLm87LAj2tXNg2ERYjt37Mg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjX98iN3JjVAhUEeT4KHV_sAKEQ6AEIKTAB#v=onepage&q=James%20McMillan%20Shafter%20marriage&f=false}}</ref> They had at least four children: Payne Jewett Shafter,<ref name=\"The marriage ceremony of Payne J. Shafter and Miss Nellie Jackson\">{{cite news|title=Death at  Wedding|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=MJ18760831.2.9&srpos=2&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22Payne+J.+Shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 20, 2017|work=Marin Journal|issue=16 (25)|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=31 August 1876|page=2}}</ref> James Chester Shafter, Chester Hubbard Shafter, and Julia Ruth Shafter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Looking Backward, Notes of Happenings in Marin County Twenty-Eight Years Ago as Told in the Journal|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=MJ19200219.2.80&srpos=15&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22Payne+J.+Shafter%22-------1|accessdate=July 20, 2017|work=Marin Journal|issue=8|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=19 February 1920|page=7|quote=His two sons, Dr. J. C. Shafter, of San Francisco, and Payne J. Shafter, of Olema, and his daughter, Mrs. A. F. Hamilton, of San Francisco, were at the bedside when death came.}}</ref> His nephew was [[William Rufus Shafter]], who was a general in the [[American Civil War]] and recipient of the [[Medal of Honor]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Forbes|first1=Charles Spooner|last2=Cummings|first2=Charles R.|title=The Vermonter: The State Magazine, Volumes 3-6|date=1897|publisher=C.S. Forbes|page=271|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QmdEAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA37&lpg=RA1-PA37&dq=%22William+R.+Shafter%22+vermont&source=bl&ots=Ye0vlvaWls&sig=xWsE0QB7UPqy8BRZNHxhn35wWCU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjA7fWcppbVAhVD8j4KHbFkAsEQ6AEILTAC#v=onepage&q=%22William%20R.%20Shafter%22%20vermont&f=false|accessdate=July 18, 2017|quote=An uncle of the general, the late Oscar L. Shafter...became a judge of the (California) Supreme Court.}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alvah Sabin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State of Vermont]]|years=1842\u20131849}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Farrand F. Merrill]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Frederick W. Horn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= Speaker of the [[Wisconsin State Assembly]]|years=1852-1853}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Henry L. Palmer]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=Richard Irwin}}\n{{s-ttl|title= President Pro Tempore [[California State Senate]]|years=1862}}\n{{s-aft|after=A.M. Crane}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shafter, James Macmillan}}\n[[Category:1816 births]]\n[[Category:1892 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Athens, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State of Vermont]]\n[[Category:Members of the Vermont House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the Wisconsin State Assembly]]\n[[Category:California state senators]]\n[[Category:California state court judges]]\n[[Category:Superior court judges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Sheboygan, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Politicians from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Wesleyan University alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University trustees]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Asdasdasdff", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_McMillan_Shafter"}
{"title_page": "James Joseph Dresnok", "text_new": "{{short description|American defector to North Korea}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = James Joseph Dresnok\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = November 24, 1941<ref name=\"birth\">''Virginia, Birth Records, 1912-2014, Delayed Birth Records, 1854-1911''; Virginia Department of Health, Richmond, Virginia.</ref>\n| death_date    = {{Death year and age|2016|1941|11}}\n| birth_place   = [[Norfolk, Virginia|Norfolk]], [[Virginia]], U.S.\n| death_place   = [[Pyongyang]], North Korea\n| nickname      = \"Jim\", \"Joe\", \"Arthur\"\n| allegiance    = {{flagu|United States|1960}} (1958\u20131962)<br />{{flag|North Korea}} (1962\u20132016)\n| branch        = {{nowrap|{{army|United States}} (1958\u20131962)}}\n| serviceyears  = 1958\u20131962 (defected)\n| rank          = [[File:Army-USA-OR-03-2015.svg|25px]] [[Private First Class#United States|Private first class]]\n| unit          = \n| commands      = \n| battles       = \n| awards        = \n| relations     = \n| spouse        = Kathleen Ringwood (1959-1962)<br>Doina Bumbea (c. 1970s-1997)<br>unknown; daughter of Korean woman and African diplomat (2001-2016)\n| children      = Ted (b. 1980)<br>James (b. 1982)<br>Tony (b. 2001)\n| laterwork     = [[Teacher]], [[actor]], translator\n}}\n\n'''James Joseph Dresnok''' ({{lang-ko|\uc81c\uc784\uc2a4 \uc870\uc0c8\ud504 \ub4dc\ub808\uc2a4\ub179}}, November 24, 1941 \u2013 November 2016) was an American [[defection|defector]] to North Korea, one of six U.S. soldiers to defect after the [[Korean War]].\n\nAfter defecting, Dresnok worked as an actor in [[propaganda film]]s, some directed by [[Kim Jong-il]],<ref>{{cite web|title=The Americans Who Chose To Live in North Korea |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1DvBybErjUM |publisher=BBC |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207013826/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1DvBybErjUM |archivedate=December 7, 2016 }}</ref> and as an English teacher in [[Pyongyang]]. He was featured on the [[CBS]] magazine program ''[[60 Minutes]]'' on January 28, 2007, as the last U.S. defector alive in North Korea.<ref name=\"60mins\"/> He was also the subject of a documentary film, ''[[Crossing the Line (2006 film)|Crossing the Line]]'', by British filmmakers [[Daniel Gordon (film director)|Daniel Gordon]] and [[Nicholas Bonner]], which was shown at the [[2007 Sundance Film Festival]].<ref name=\"United Nations Human Rights Council 2014\"/><ref name=\"filmref\">[http://festival.sundance.org/filmguide/popup.aspx?film=3319 World Documentary Competition, \u201cCrossing the Line\u201d (2006)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070304162309/http://festival.sundance.org/filmguide/popup.aspx?film=3319 |date=March 4, 2007 }} 2007 Sundance Film Festival. Accessed January 28, 2007.</ref>\n\nDresnok most often dubbed himself '''Joe Dresnok''' but he was variously referred to as \"James\",<ref name=\"jamesjoe\">Frederick, Jim; [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,501041115-750859,00.html \u201cIn from the Cold\u201d] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070904155613/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C501041115-750859%2C00.html |date=September 4, 2007 }}, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', November 4, 2004. Accessed January 28, 2007.</ref><ref name=\"james\">{{citation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/19/movies/19cros.html |last=Russell |first=Mark |title=An American in North Korea, Pledging Allegiance to the Great Leader |work=New York Times |date=October 19, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125132159/https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/19/movies/19cros.html|archivedate=25 January 2016|accessdate=January 28, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"imdbcreds\">[http://imdb.com/title/tt0473181/fullcredits Full Cast and Crew for Crossing the Line] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070314154554/http://imdb.com/title/tt0473181/fullcredits |date=March 14, 2007 }}, IMDb profile.  Accessed January 28, 2007.</ref> \"Joe\"<ref name=\"60mins\">{{cite news|first=Robert G. |last=Anderson |first2=Casey |last2=Morgan |title=An American in North Korea. |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/01/25/60minutes/main2398580.shtml |publisher=[[60 Minutes]] |date=January 28, 2007 |accessdate=August 21, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070810034747/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/01/25/60minutes/main2398580.shtml |archivedate=August 10, 2007 }}</ref> and \"Jim\" Dresnok<ref name=\"O'Carroll\" /> in media reports. He was known by most North Koreans as \"Arthur\", from his starring role in the propaganda film ''[[Unsung Heroes]]'' (1978).\n\n==Early life==\nDresnok was born in [[Norfolk, Virginia]], to Joseph Dresnok and Margaret Lucille Dresnok (maiden name Mizelle), who were married in South\nMills, Camden County, North Carolina, on  May 3, 1941. <ref name=\"birth\"/> Joseph Dresnok I (1917\u20131978) was born on February 3, 1917 in Greensburg, Westmoreland County, Pennsylvania, and died on March 16, 1978 in Wyckoff, Bergen County, New Jersey. Joseph Dresnok I served in the United States Army from November 23, 1937, until May 29, 1940. Joseph and Margaret Dresnok divorced on July 10, 1951, in Richmond, Virginia. Dresnok\u2019s father initiated the divorce action, claiming that Dresnok\u2019s mother was \u201clegally married to another.\u201d Dresnok was briefly raised by his father in [[Pennsylvania]]; his mother and younger brother Joseph Dresnok II never again came into contact with them.<ref>[http://scholar.lib.vt.edu/VA-news/VA-Pilot/issues/1996/vp960118/01180477.htm Man Hopes His Brother Alive] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205090033/http://scholar.lib.vt.edu/VA-news/VA-Pilot/issues/1996/vp960118/01180477.htm |date=February 5, 2007 }}; Thursday January 18, 1996</ref> Dresnok was placed in a [[foster home]], dropped out of high school, and joined the Army the day after his 17th birthday.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Sweeney|first1=John|title=North Korea Undercover: Inside the World's Most Secret State|date=2015|publisher=Pegasus Books|isbn=9781605988030|page=123|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1vwpCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT123|accessdate=21 August 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Defection==\nDresnok's first military service was two years spent in [[West Germany]]. After returning to the United States and finding out that his wife had left him for another man, he re-enlisted and was sent to [[South Korea]]. He was a [[Private First Class]] with a [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] unit along the [[Korean Demilitarized Zone]] between North and South Korea in the early 1960s. Soon after his arrival, he found himself facing a [[court martial]] for forging signatures on paperwork that gave him permission to leave the base which, ultimately, led to his going [[AWOL]] (Absent Without Leave).<ref name=\"60mins\"/>\n\nUnwilling to face punishment, on August 15, 1962, while his fellow soldiers were eating lunch, he ran across a [[minefield]] in broad daylight into North Korean territory, where he was quickly apprehended by North Korean soldiers. Dresnok was taken by train to [[Pyongyang]], the North Korean capital, and interrogated.<ref name=\"60mins\"/>\n\n==Life in North Korea==\n\"I was fed up with my childhood, my marriage, my military life, everything. I was finished. There's only one place to go\", Dresnok said in an interview. \"On August 15th, at noon in broad daylight when everybody was eating lunch, I hit the road. Yes, I was afraid. Am I gonna live or die? And when I stepped into the minefield and I seen it with my own eyes, I started sweating. I crossed over, looking for my new life.\"<ref name=\"60mins\"/>\n\nDresnok met [[Larry Allen Abshier]], another U.S. defector, soon after his arrival. Eventually there were four of them: Dresnok, Abshier, [[Jerry Parrish]], and [[Charles Robert Jenkins]]. The men lived together and participated in several propaganda efforts on behalf of the North Korean government. They appeared on magazine covers and used loudspeakers to try to persuade more U.S. soldiers at the border to defect. They did not wish to remain in North Korea indefinitely at first. In 1966, the four men tried to leave North Korea by seeking asylum at the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] embassy in Pyongyang, but the embassy immediately turned them over to North Korean authorities.<ref name=\"60mins\"/> After that, Dresnok decided to settle in North Korea.\n\nBeginning in 1978, he was cast in several [[Cinema of North Korea|North Korean films]], including the 20-part series ''[[Unsung Heroes (film)|Unsung Heroes]]'' (as an American villain), and he became a celebrity in the country as a result. He was called \"Arthur\" by his Korean friends, after the character he played in the series. He also translated some of North Korean leader [[Kim Il-sung]]'s writings into English.<ref name=\"60mins\"/><ref name=\"Spillerlastdefect\">{{cite news|date=January 23, 2007 |accessdate=May 1, 2009 |title=Last US defector in North Korea |work=BBC News |last=Spiller |first=Penny |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/6267645.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208102822/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/6267645.stm |archivedate=February 8, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn his book ''The Reluctant Communist'', Jenkins claims that Dresnok was a bully, betraying the other Americans' confidences to the North Koreans, and beating up Jenkins on 30 or more occasions on the orders of their Korean handlers.<ref name=Jenkins />{{Rp|64}} In the documentary ''[[Crossing the Line (documentary)|Crossing the Line]]'', Dresnok vehemently denies these allegations.\n\nDresnok asserts that \"because of the sanctions of the U.S. Government and Japanese\",<ref>{{YouTube| id= 4FOcZkKnALA?t=1h13m54s | title= \"North Korea Documentary About a US Army soldier who defected to North Korea\" }}</ref> during the [[North Korean famine]] of the 1990s, he was always given his full food ration by the government. \"Why? Why do they let their own people starve to death to feed an American?\", he asked. \"The Great Leader has given us a special solicitude. The government is going to take care of me until my dying day.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/19/movies/19cros.html |title=An American in North Korea, Pledging Allegiance to the Great Leader |date=October 19, 2006 |work=The New York Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125132159/https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/19/movies/19cros.html |archivedate=January 25, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and marriages==\nIn December 1959, Dresnok married Kathleen Ringwood, a 19-year-old from [[New York City]].<ref>''Virginia, Marriage Records, 1936-2014''</ref> In ''[[Crossing the Line (documentary)|Crossing the Line]]'', Dresnok explains that after getting married at a young age, he was deployed in [[West Germany]] for two years while she remained in the U.S. He prided himself on \"truly loving her and being loyal to her\", but when he returned, he found out that she was already in another relationship. He was quoted as saying, \"The good thing was that she did not get pregnant by me because I had promised that I would never abandon my children.\" However, they remained married until after his defection in 1962. She filed for divorce the next year, citing \"wilful desertion\" on his part as grounds.<ref>''Virginia, Divorce Records, 1918-2014''</ref>\n\nDresnok was married twice more after defecting to North Korea. His first marriage was to a [[Romanians|Romanian]] woman, Doina Bumbea (referred to as \"Dona\" in Jenkins' autobiography), with whom he had two sons, Theodore \"Ted\" Ricardo Dresnok (born 1980)<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\" /> and James Gabriel Dresnok (born {{circa}} 1982).<ref>{{cite news|title=N. Korea kidnap victim's brother wants Pyongyang to come clean|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/print/400381/|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|date=17 March 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6svaTvDrD?url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/print/400381/|archivedate=August 23, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bumbea supposedly worked at the [[North Korea-Romania relations|Romanian Embassy]], but some accounts say that she never worked there and was in fact an abductee who had been taken by the [[State Security Department|North Korean secret service]]. According to Bumbea's family, she was living in [[Italy]] as an art student when she vanished, after telling people that she had met a man who promised to help arrange exhibitions of her art in [[Asia]]. After viewing ''Crossing the Line'' and seeing one of Dresnok's sons, Bumbea's brother stated he bore a startling resemblance to his missing sister.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cain|first1=Geoffrey|title=Political kidnappings, North Korean style|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2014/12/26/french-student-kidnapped-north-korea/20911411/|accessdate=21 August 2017|work=USA Today|date=December 26, 2014|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"United Nations Human Rights Council 2014\"/><ref>[http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2007/03/22/2007032261016.html \"Romanian Woman Kidnapped by N. Korea in 1978\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622002437/http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2007/03/22/2007032261016.html |date=June 22, 2011 }}, ''[[The Chosun Ilbo]]'', March 22, 2007. Accessed November 13, 2010.</ref><ref>[http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20070421a7.html \u201cRomanian brother of Pyongyang abductee visits\u201d], ''[[The Japan Times]]'', April 21, 2007. Accessed November 13, 2010.</ref>{{dead|date=July 2017}} According to Jenkins's book, Bumbea was abducted in order to be the wife of one of the American deserters.<ref name=Jenkins>{{cite book|last1=Jenkins|first1=Charles Robert|last2=Frederick|first2=Jim|authorlink1=Charles Robert Jenkins|title=The Reluctant Communist: My Desertion, Court-Martial, and Forty-Year Imprisonment in North Korea|date=2008|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520259997|url=https://archive.org/details/reluctantcommuni00jenk|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/reluctantcommuni00jenk/page/73 73]|language=en}}</ref>{{Rp|73-74}}<ref name=\"United Nations Human Rights Council 2014\"/> The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Romania)|Romanian Foreign Affairs Ministry]]'s website says that in 2007 the [[Romanian Government]] had requested an explanation for Bumbea's abduction from the [[North Korean government]]. However, no response was provided to [[Romania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mae.ro/index.php?unde=doc&id=32413&idlnk=2&cat=4 |title=Ministerul Afacerilor Externe |work=mae.ro |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227050913/http://www.mae.ro/index.php?unde=doc&id=32413&idlnk=2&cat=4 |archivedate=February 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realitatea.net/japonia-mizeaza-pe-ajutorul-romaniei-in-relatia-cu-phenianul-pe-tema-rapirilor_52211.html |title=Japonia mizeaz\u0103 pe ajutorul Rom\u00e2niei, \u00een rela\u0163ia cu Phenianul pe tema r\u0103pirilor |date=December 28, 2015 |work=REALITATEA.NET |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110209011057/http://www.realitatea.net/japonia-mizeaza-pe-ajutorul-romaniei-in-relatia-cu-phenianul-pe-tema-rapirilor_52211.html |archivedate=February 9, 2011 }}</ref> Bumbea reportedly died of [[lung cancer]] in 1997.<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\">{{cite news|last1=Fifield|first1=Anna|authorlink1=Anna Fifield|title=An American GI defected to North Korea. Now his sons are propaganda stars.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/05/25/the-north-korean-born-sons-of-an-american-defector-speak-in-korean/|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=25 May 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604031413/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/05/25/the-north-korean-born-sons-of-an-american-defector-speak-in-korean/?utm_term=.97c6048fe5a5|archivedate=4 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter Bumbea's death, Dresnok married his third wife, the daughter of a North Korean woman and a [[Togo-North Korea relations|Togolese diplomat]]. They had a son, Tony, in 2001. The family lived in a small apartment in Pyongyang, provided to them along with a monthly stipend by the North Korean government. Dresnok was in failing health, with a bad heart and liver (Dresnok described his liver as \"full of fat\"), which he attributed to smoking and drinking too much.<ref name=\"60mins\"/><ref>https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=G6Tx9TmazEs</ref>\n\nHis younger son from his second marriage, James Dresnok, was a student at [[Pyongyang University of Foreign Studies]], where his father [[Teaching English as a foreign language|taught English]] in the 1980s.<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\"/> James speaks English with a Korean accent and considers himself Korean but he reportedly does not wish to marry a Korean woman.<ref>https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=G6Tx9TmazEs</ref> James joined the [[Korean People's Army|North Korean military]] in 2014, and in 2016 he reportedly held the rank of ''[[taewi]]'', a rank that is equivalent to the rank of [[Captain (US Army)|captain]] in the US Army.<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\"/><ref>https://m.youtube.com/watch?feature=youtu.be&v=xoxIpNKqhus</ref> Both the younger James and the older Ted Dresnok are now married and they also have children of their own in North Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3609562/Sons-American-GI-defected-North-Korea-1960s-country-s-latest-propaganda-stars-one-captain-imperial-army.html |title=White North Koreans, sons of 1960s defector, defend Kim Jon Un online |website=dailymail.co.uk |accessdate=June 15, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170324051859/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3609562/Sons-American-GI-defected-North-Korea-1960s-country-s-latest-propaganda-stars-one-captain-imperial-army.html |archivedate=March 24, 2017 }}</ref> Like their father, they have also appeared as villainous American soldiers in North Korean films.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Broinowski |first1=Anna |title=The Australian who shot a North Korean propaganda film |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-35365142 |website=[[BBC News]] |date=21 January 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423063726/http://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-35365142 |archivedate=April 23, 2017 }}</ref><ref>https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=idPCHqiDXGs</ref>\n\nDresnok stated that he intended to spend the rest of his life in North Korea, and no amount of money could have enticed him to move back to the West. Dresnok retired and occasionally gave lectures in North Korea and went fishing \"just to pass the time.\"<ref name=\"60mins\"/><ref>https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=G6Tx9TmazEs</ref>\n\n==Death==\nIn April 2017, a Western news organization that focuses on North Korea reported that Dresnok had died the previous year.<ref name=\"O'Carroll\">{{cite web|last1=O'Carroll|first1=Chad|title=Jim Dresnok, American who defected to N.Korea in 1962, died in 2016|url=https://www.nknews.org/2017/04/jim-dresnok-american-who-defected-to-n-korea-in-1962-died-in-2016/|website=NK News - North Korea News|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410214314/https://www.nknews.org/2017/04/jim-dresnok-american-who-defected-to-n-korea-in-1962-died-in-2016/|archivedate=10 April 2017|date=10 April 2017}}</ref> In August 2017, Dresnok's sons confirmed that he had died of a [[stroke]] in November 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sons confirm death of US soldier James Dresnok, who defected to North Korea|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/aug/21/american-soldier-james-dresnok-who-defected-to-north-korea-has-died-say-sons|accessdate=21 August 2017|work=The Guardian|agency=Agence France-Presse|date=21 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=A U.S. soldier who defected to North Korea in 1962 has died, his Pyongyang-born sons say|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/08/21/a-u-s-soldier-who-defected-to-north-korea-in-1962-has-died-his-pyongyang-born-sons-say/|accessdate=22 August 2017|work=The Washington Post|date=21 August 2017}}</ref> They released a statement saying that their father told them to remain loyal to [[Kim Jong-un]] and they also stated that they would \"destroy\" the US if it launched a [[Preemptive strike (disambiguation)|preemptive strike]] against North Korea.<ref>https://m.youtube.com/watch?feature=youtu.be&v=xoxIpNKqhus</ref><ref>https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/video/2017/aug/21/dresnok-sons-our-father-told-us-to-serve-kim-jong-un-video</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[Unsung Heroes]]'' (a.k.a. ''Nameless Heroes'') (1978)<ref name=\"Spillerlastdefect\"/>\n* ''From 5 p.m. to 5&nbsp;am'' (1990)<ref>{{IMDb title|tt2162559|From 5 p.m. to 5&nbsp;am}}</ref>\n* ''[[Crossing the Line (2006 film)|Crossing the Line]]'' (2006)<ref name=\"Spillerlastdefect\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|North Korea}}\n* [[Americans in North Korea]]\n* [[List of American and British defectors in the Korean War]]\n* [[North Korean defectors]]\n* [[South Korean defectors]]\n\n'''Other defectors to North Korea'''\n* [[List of American and British defectors in the Korean War]]: the 21 Americans and 1 Briton who refused repatriation during [[Operation Big Switch]] in 1953 (in order to remain in [[China]])\n* [[Larry Allen Abshier]] (1943\u20131983) from [[Urbana, Illinois]], deserted in May 1962 at the age of 19\n* [[Jerry Wayne Parrish]] (1944\u20131996) from [[Morganfield, Kentucky]], deserted in December 1963 at the age of 19\n* [[Charles Robert Jenkins]] (1940\u20132017) from [[Rich Square, North Carolina]], deserted on January 5, 1965 at the age of 24\n* [[Roy Chung]] (born {{circa|1957}}), an American who was born in South Korea, deserted in June 1979\n* [[Joseph T. White]] (1961\u20131985) from [[St Louis, Missouri]], deserted in August 1982 at the age of 20.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"United Nations Human Rights Council 2014\">{{cite journal |first1= Michael Donald|last1=Kirby |authorlink1=Michael Kirby (judge) |first2=Sonja |last2=Biserko  |authorlink2=Sonja Biserko |first3= Marzuki|last3=Darusman  |authorlink3=Marzuki Darusman  |date=February 7, 2014 |title=Report of the detailed findings of the commission of inquiry on human rights in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea - A/HRC/25/CRP.1 |publisher=[[United Nations Human Rights Council]] |url= http://www.ohchr.org/Documents/HRBodies/HRCouncil/CoIDPRK/Report/A.HRC.25.CRP.1_ENG.doc|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227104633/http://www.ohchr.org/Documents/HRBodies/HRCouncil/CoIDPRK/Report/A.HRC.25.CRP.1_ENG.doc | archivedate= February 27, 2014 |url-status=live |pages=306 (Paragraph 973) |quote= Ms Dona Bumbea disappeared from Italy in 1978 and is believed to have been lured to the DPRK. Ms Bumbea had been studying art in Italy at the time when she met an Italian man claiming to be an art dealer, who convinced her to hold an exhibition in [[Hong Kong]]. The two travelled to Pyongyang en-route to Hong Kong at which point the Italian disappeared. Ms Bumbea was kept in the DPRK and \"given\" to American army deserter Mr Dresnock. Ms Bumbea died in the DPRK and is survived by her two sons, Mr Ricardo Dresnock born in 1981 and Mr James Gabriel Dresnock, born in 1983, both of whom have been seen in several documentaries including \"Crossing the line\" (2006) and \"Aim High in Creation\" (2013). Ms Bumbea's family in Romania has been unable to have any contact with Ms Bumbea's sons despite their wish to.}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1DvBybErjUM ''The Americans Who Chose To Live in North Korea'' BBC Documentary]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090328131541/http://www.theworld.org/?q=node%2F7662 The World: Crossing the line audio report]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/1469616/US-defector-says-he-is-happier-in-North-Korea.html ''Telegraph'':  US defector says he is happier in North Korea]\n* [http://www.cbsnews.com/sections/60minutes/main3415.shtml CBS: Defector Won\u2019t Leave N. Korea For $1B]\n* [http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2004/06/02/world/main620738.shtml CBS: N. Korea\u2019s Last U.S. Defector]\n* [http://www.avclub.com/content/cinema/crossing_the_line Review] of ''Crossing the Line''\n* [http://www.rfa.org/english/news/social/2007/03/20/nkorea_romania/] Doina Bumbea EN\n* [http://www.uyghurnews.com/index.asp?ItemID=NM-213200872549193242133] Doina Bumbea EN (2)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080519015620/http://stiri.rol.ro/content/view/47815/2/] Doina Bumbea RO\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/sep/09/korea.usa \"The Dear Leader Takes Care of Me\" 9-9-2008]\n* [https://www.nknews.org/2017/04/jim-dresnok-american-who-defected-to-n-korea-in-1962-died-in-2016 \"Jim Dresnok, American who defected to N.Korea in 1962, died in 2016]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dresnok, James Joseph}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:American defectors]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in North Korea]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:North Korean male film actors]]\n[[Category:People from Norfolk, Virginia]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of North Korea]]\n[[Category:20th-century North Korean male actors]]\n[[Category:Date of death missing]]\n[[Category:People from Pyongyang]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American defector to North Korea}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = James Joseph Dresnok\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = November 24, 1941<ref name=\"birth\">''Virginia, Birth Records, 1912-2014, Delayed Birth Records, 1854-1911''; Virginia Department of Health, Richmond, Virginia.</ref>\n| death_date    = {{Death year and age|2016|1941|11}}\n| birth_place   = [[Norfolk, Virginia|Norfolk]], [[Virginia]], U.S.\n| death_place   = [[Pyongyang]], North Korea\n| nickname      = \"Jim\", \"Joe\", \u201cArthur\u201d\n| allegiance    = {{flagu|United States|1960}} (1958\u20131962)<br />{{flag|North Korea}} (1962\u20132016)\n| branch        = {{nowrap|{{army|United States}} (1958\u20131962)}}\n| serviceyears  = 1958\u20131962 (defected)\n| rank          = [[File:Army-USA-OR-03-2015.svg|25px]] [[Private First Class#United States|Private first class]]\n| unit          = \n| commands      = \n| battles       = \n| awards        = \n| relations     = \n| spouse        = Kathleen Ringwood (1959-1962)<br>Doina Bumbea (c. 1970s-1997)<br>unknown; daughter of Korean woman and African diplomat (2001-2016)\n| children      = Ted (b. 1980)<br>James (b. 1982)<br>Tony (b. 2001)\n| laterwork     = [[Teacher]], [[actor]], translator\n}}\n\n'''James Joseph Dresnok''' ({{lang-ko|\uc81c\uc784\uc2a4 \uc870\uc0c8\ud504 \ub4dc\ub808\uc2a4\ub179}}, November 24, 1941 \u2013 November 2016) was an American [[defection|defector]] to North Korea, one of six U.S. soldiers to defect after the [[Korean War]].\n\nAfter defecting, Dresnok worked as an actor in [[propaganda film]]s, some directed by [[Kim Jong-il]],<ref>{{cite web|title=The Americans Who Chose To Live in North Korea |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1DvBybErjUM |publisher=BBC |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207013826/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1DvBybErjUM |archivedate=December 7, 2016 }}</ref> and as an English teacher in [[Pyongyang]]. He was featured on the [[CBS]] magazine program ''[[60 Minutes]]'' on January 28, 2007, as the last U.S. defector alive in North Korea.<ref name=\"60mins\"/> He was also the subject of a documentary film, ''[[Crossing the Line (2006 film)|Crossing the Line]]'', by British filmmakers [[Daniel Gordon (film director)|Daniel Gordon]] and [[Nicholas Bonner]], which was shown at the [[2007 Sundance Film Festival]].<ref name=\"United Nations Human Rights Council 2014\"/><ref name=\"filmref\">[http://festival.sundance.org/filmguide/popup.aspx?film=3319 World Documentary Competition, \u201cCrossing the Line\u201d (2006)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070304162309/http://festival.sundance.org/filmguide/popup.aspx?film=3319 |date=March 4, 2007 }} 2007 Sundance Film Festival. Accessed January 28, 2007.</ref>\n\nDresnok most often dubbed himself '''Joe Dresnok''' but he was variously referred to as \"James\",<ref name=\"jamesjoe\">Frederick, Jim; [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,501041115-750859,00.html \u201cIn from the Cold\u201d] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070904155613/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C501041115-750859%2C00.html |date=September 4, 2007 }}, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', November 4, 2004. Accessed January 28, 2007.</ref><ref name=\"james\">{{citation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/19/movies/19cros.html |last=Russell |first=Mark |title=An American in North Korea, Pledging Allegiance to the Great Leader |work=New York Times |date=October 19, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125132159/https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/19/movies/19cros.html|archivedate=25 January 2016|accessdate=January 28, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"imdbcreds\">[http://imdb.com/title/tt0473181/fullcredits Full Cast and Crew for Crossing the Line] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070314154554/http://imdb.com/title/tt0473181/fullcredits |date=March 14, 2007 }}, IMDb profile.  Accessed January 28, 2007.</ref> \"Joe\"<ref name=\"60mins\">{{cite news|first=Robert G. |last=Anderson |first2=Casey |last2=Morgan |title=An American in North Korea. |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/01/25/60minutes/main2398580.shtml |publisher=[[60 Minutes]] |date=January 28, 2007 |accessdate=August 21, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070810034747/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/01/25/60minutes/main2398580.shtml |archivedate=August 10, 2007 }}</ref> and \"Jim\" Dresnok<ref name=\"O'Carroll\" /> in media reports. He was known by most North Koreans as \"Arthur\", from his starring role in the propaganda film ''[[Unsung Heroes]]'' (1978).\n\n==Early life==\nDresnok was born in [[Norfolk, Virginia]], to Joseph Dresnok and Margaret Lucille Dresnok (maiden name Mizelle), who were married in South\nMills, Camden County, North Carolina, on  May 3, 1941. <ref name=\"birth\"/> Joseph Dresnok I (1917\u20131978) was born on February 3, 1917 in Greensburg, Westmoreland County, Pennsylvania, and died on March 16, 1978 in Wyckoff, Bergen County, New Jersey. Joseph Dresnok I served in the United States Army from November 23, 1937, until May 29, 1940. Joseph and Margaret Dresnok divorced on July 10, 1951, in Richmond, Virginia. Dresnok\u2019s father initiated the divorce action, claiming that Dresnok\u2019s mother was \u201clegally married to another.\u201d Dresnok was briefly raised by his father in [[Pennsylvania]]; his mother and younger brother Joseph Dresnok II never again came into contact with them.<ref>[http://scholar.lib.vt.edu/VA-news/VA-Pilot/issues/1996/vp960118/01180477.htm Man Hopes His Brother Alive] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205090033/http://scholar.lib.vt.edu/VA-news/VA-Pilot/issues/1996/vp960118/01180477.htm |date=February 5, 2007 }}; Thursday January 18, 1996</ref> Dresnok was placed in a [[foster home]], dropped out of high school, and joined the Army the day after his 17th birthday.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Sweeney|first1=John|title=North Korea Undercover: Inside the World's Most Secret State|date=2015|publisher=Pegasus Books|isbn=9781605988030|page=123|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1vwpCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT123|accessdate=21 August 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Defection==\nDresnok's first military service was two years spent in [[West Germany]]. After returning to the United States and finding out that his wife had left him for another man, he re-enlisted and was sent to [[South Korea]]. He was a [[Private First Class]] with a [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] unit along the [[Korean Demilitarized Zone]] between North and South Korea in the early 1960s. Soon after his arrival, he found himself facing a [[court martial]] for forging signatures on paperwork that gave him permission to leave the base which, ultimately, led to his going [[AWOL]] (Absent Without Leave).<ref name=\"60mins\"/>\n\nUnwilling to face punishment, on August 15, 1962, while his fellow soldiers were eating lunch, he ran across a [[minefield]] in broad daylight into North Korean territory, where he was quickly apprehended by North Korean soldiers. Dresnok was taken by train to [[Pyongyang]], the North Korean capital, and interrogated.<ref name=\"60mins\"/>\n\n==Life in North Korea==\n\"I was fed up with my childhood, my marriage, my military life, everything. I was finished. There's only one place to go\", Dresnok said in an interview. \"On August 15th, at noon in broad daylight when everybody was eating lunch, I hit the road. Yes, I was afraid. Am I gonna live or die? And when I stepped into the minefield and I seen it with my own eyes, I started sweating. I crossed over, looking for my new life.\"<ref name=\"60mins\"/>\n\nDresnok met [[Larry Allen Abshier]], another U.S. defector, soon after his arrival. Eventually there were four of them: Dresnok, Abshier, [[Jerry Parrish]], and [[Charles Robert Jenkins]]. The men lived together and participated in several propaganda efforts on behalf of the North Korean government. They appeared on magazine covers and used loudspeakers to try to persuade more U.S. soldiers at the border to defect. They did not wish to remain in North Korea indefinitely at first. In 1966, the four men tried to leave North Korea by seeking asylum at the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] embassy in Pyongyang, but the embassy immediately turned them over to North Korean authorities.<ref name=\"60mins\"/> After that, Dresnok decided to settle in North Korea.\n\nBeginning in 1978, he was cast in several [[Cinema of North Korea|North Korean films]], including the 20-part series ''[[Unsung Heroes (film)|Unsung Heroes]]'' (as an American villain), and he became a celebrity in the country as a result. He was called \"Arthur\" by his Korean friends, after the character he played in the series. He also translated some of North Korean leader [[Kim Il-sung]]'s writings into English.<ref name=\"60mins\"/><ref name=\"Spillerlastdefect\">{{cite news|date=January 23, 2007 |accessdate=May 1, 2009 |title=Last US defector in North Korea |work=BBC News |last=Spiller |first=Penny |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/6267645.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208102822/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/6267645.stm |archivedate=February 8, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn his book ''The Reluctant Communist'', Jenkins claims that Dresnok was a bully, betraying the other Americans' confidences to the North Koreans, and beating up Jenkins on 30 or more occasions on the orders of their Korean handlers.<ref name=Jenkins />{{Rp|64}} In the documentary ''[[Crossing the Line (documentary)|Crossing the Line]]'', Dresnok vehemently denies these allegations.\n\nDresnok asserts that \"because of the sanctions of the U.S. Government and Japanese\",<ref>{{YouTube| id= 4FOcZkKnALA?t=1h13m54s | title= \"North Korea Documentary About a US Army soldier who defected to North Korea\" }}</ref> during the [[North Korean famine]] of the 1990s, he was always given his full food ration by the government. \"Why? Why do they let their own people starve to death to feed an American?\", he asked. \"The Great Leader has given us a special solicitude. The government is going to take care of me until my dying day.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/19/movies/19cros.html |title=An American in North Korea, Pledging Allegiance to the Great Leader |date=October 19, 2006 |work=The New York Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125132159/https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/19/movies/19cros.html |archivedate=January 25, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and marriages==\nIn December 1959, Dresnok married Kathleen Ringwood, a 19-year-old from [[New York City]].<ref>''Virginia, Marriage Records, 1936-2014''</ref> In ''[[Crossing the Line (documentary)|Crossing the Line]]'', Dresnok explains that after getting married at a young age, he was deployed in [[West Germany]] for two years while she remained in the U.S. He prided himself on \"truly loving her and being loyal to her\", but when he returned, he found out that she was already in another relationship. He was quoted as saying, \"The good thing was that she did not get pregnant by me because I had promised that I would never abandon my children.\" However, they remained married until after his defection in 1962. She filed for divorce the next year, citing \"wilful desertion\" on his part as grounds.<ref>''Virginia, Divorce Records, 1918-2014''</ref>\n\nDresnok was married twice more after defecting to North Korea. His first marriage was to a [[Romanians|Romanian]] woman, Doina Bumbea (referred to as \"Dona\" in Jenkins' autobiography), with whom he had two sons, Theodore \"Ted\" Ricardo Dresnok (born 1980)<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\" /> and James Gabriel Dresnok (born {{circa}} 1982).<ref>{{cite news|title=N. Korea kidnap victim's brother wants Pyongyang to come clean|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/print/400381/|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|date=17 March 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6svaTvDrD?url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/print/400381/|archivedate=August 23, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bumbea supposedly worked at the [[North Korea-Romania relations|Romanian Embassy]], but some accounts say that she never worked there and was in fact an abductee who had been taken by the [[State Security Department|North Korean secret service]]. According to Bumbea's family, she was living in [[Italy]] as an art student when she vanished, after telling people that she had met a man who promised to help arrange exhibitions of her art in [[Asia]]. After viewing ''Crossing the Line'' and seeing one of Dresnok's sons, Bumbea's brother stated he bore a startling resemblance to his missing sister.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cain|first1=Geoffrey|title=Political kidnappings, North Korean style|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2014/12/26/french-student-kidnapped-north-korea/20911411/|accessdate=21 August 2017|work=USA Today|date=December 26, 2014|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"United Nations Human Rights Council 2014\"/><ref>[http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2007/03/22/2007032261016.html \"Romanian Woman Kidnapped by N. Korea in 1978\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622002437/http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2007/03/22/2007032261016.html |date=June 22, 2011 }}, ''[[The Chosun Ilbo]]'', March 22, 2007. Accessed November 13, 2010.</ref><ref>[http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20070421a7.html \u201cRomanian brother of Pyongyang abductee visits\u201d], ''[[The Japan Times]]'', April 21, 2007. Accessed November 13, 2010.</ref>{{dead|date=July 2017}} According to Jenkins's book, Bumbea was abducted in order to be the wife of one of the American deserters.<ref name=Jenkins>{{cite book|last1=Jenkins|first1=Charles Robert|last2=Frederick|first2=Jim|authorlink1=Charles Robert Jenkins|title=The Reluctant Communist: My Desertion, Court-Martial, and Forty-Year Imprisonment in North Korea|date=2008|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520259997|url=https://archive.org/details/reluctantcommuni00jenk|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/reluctantcommuni00jenk/page/73 73]|language=en}}</ref>{{Rp|73-74}}<ref name=\"United Nations Human Rights Council 2014\"/> The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Romania)|Romanian Foreign Affairs Ministry]]'s website says that in 2007 the [[Romanian Government]] had requested an explanation for Bumbea's abduction from the [[North Korean government]]. However, no response was provided to [[Romania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mae.ro/index.php?unde=doc&id=32413&idlnk=2&cat=4 |title=Ministerul Afacerilor Externe |work=mae.ro |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227050913/http://www.mae.ro/index.php?unde=doc&id=32413&idlnk=2&cat=4 |archivedate=February 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realitatea.net/japonia-mizeaza-pe-ajutorul-romaniei-in-relatia-cu-phenianul-pe-tema-rapirilor_52211.html |title=Japonia mizeaz\u0103 pe ajutorul Rom\u00e2niei, \u00een rela\u0163ia cu Phenianul pe tema r\u0103pirilor |date=December 28, 2015 |work=REALITATEA.NET |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110209011057/http://www.realitatea.net/japonia-mizeaza-pe-ajutorul-romaniei-in-relatia-cu-phenianul-pe-tema-rapirilor_52211.html |archivedate=February 9, 2011 }}</ref> Bumbea reportedly died of [[lung cancer]] in 1997.<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\">{{cite news|last1=Fifield|first1=Anna|authorlink1=Anna Fifield|title=An American GI defected to North Korea. Now his sons are propaganda stars.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/05/25/the-north-korean-born-sons-of-an-american-defector-speak-in-korean/|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=25 May 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604031413/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/05/25/the-north-korean-born-sons-of-an-american-defector-speak-in-korean/?utm_term=.97c6048fe5a5|archivedate=4 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter Bumbea's death, Dresnok married his third wife, the daughter of a North Korean woman and a [[Togo-North Korea relations|Togolese diplomat]]. They had a son, Tony, in 2001. The family lived in a small apartment in Pyongyang, provided to them along with a monthly stipend by the North Korean government. Dresnok was in failing health, with a bad heart and liver (Dresnok described his liver as \"full of fat\"), which he attributed to smoking and drinking too much.<ref name=\"60mins\"/><ref>https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=G6Tx9TmazEs</ref>\n\nHis younger son from his second marriage, James Dresnok, was a student at [[Pyongyang University of Foreign Studies]], where his father [[Teaching English as a foreign language|taught English]] in the 1980s.<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\"/> James speaks English with a Korean accent and considers himself Korean but he reportedly does not wish to marry a Korean woman.<ref>https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=G6Tx9TmazEs</ref> James joined the [[Korean People's Army|North Korean military]] in 2014, and in 2016 he reportedly held the rank of ''[[taewi]]'', a rank that is equivalent to the rank of [[Captain (US Army)|captain]] in the US Army.<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\"/><ref>https://m.youtube.com/watch?feature=youtu.be&v=xoxIpNKqhus</ref> Both the younger James and the older Ted Dresnok are now married and they also have children of their own in North Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3609562/Sons-American-GI-defected-North-Korea-1960s-country-s-latest-propaganda-stars-one-captain-imperial-army.html |title=White North Koreans, sons of 1960s defector, defend Kim Jon Un online |website=dailymail.co.uk |accessdate=June 15, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170324051859/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3609562/Sons-American-GI-defected-North-Korea-1960s-country-s-latest-propaganda-stars-one-captain-imperial-army.html |archivedate=March 24, 2017 }}</ref> Like their father, they have also appeared as villainous American soldiers in North Korean films.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Broinowski |first1=Anna |title=The Australian who shot a North Korean propaganda film |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-35365142 |website=[[BBC News]] |date=21 January 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423063726/http://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-35365142 |archivedate=April 23, 2017 }}</ref><ref>https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=idPCHqiDXGs</ref>\n\nDresnok stated that he intended to spend the rest of his life in North Korea, and no amount of money could have enticed him to move back to the West. Dresnok retired and occasionally gave lectures in North Korea and went fishing \"just to pass the time.\"<ref name=\"60mins\"/><ref>https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=G6Tx9TmazEs</ref>\n\n==Death==\nIn April 2017, a Western news organization that focuses on North Korea reported that Dresnok had died the previous year.<ref name=\"O'Carroll\">{{cite web|last1=O'Carroll|first1=Chad|title=Jim Dresnok, American who defected to N.Korea in 1962, died in 2016|url=https://www.nknews.org/2017/04/jim-dresnok-american-who-defected-to-n-korea-in-1962-died-in-2016/|website=NK News - North Korea News|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410214314/https://www.nknews.org/2017/04/jim-dresnok-american-who-defected-to-n-korea-in-1962-died-in-2016/|archivedate=10 April 2017|date=10 April 2017}}</ref> In August 2017, Dresnok's sons confirmed that he had died of a [[stroke]] in November 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sons confirm death of US soldier James Dresnok, who defected to North Korea|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/aug/21/american-soldier-james-dresnok-who-defected-to-north-korea-has-died-say-sons|accessdate=21 August 2017|work=The Guardian|agency=Agence France-Presse|date=21 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=A U.S. soldier who defected to North Korea in 1962 has died, his Pyongyang-born sons say|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/08/21/a-u-s-soldier-who-defected-to-north-korea-in-1962-has-died-his-pyongyang-born-sons-say/|accessdate=22 August 2017|work=The Washington Post|date=21 August 2017}}</ref> They released a statement saying that their father told them to remain loyal to [[Kim Jong-un]] and they also stated that they would \"destroy\" the US if it launched a [[Preemptive strike (disambiguation)|preemptive strike]] against North Korea.<ref>https://m.youtube.com/watch?feature=youtu.be&v=xoxIpNKqhus</ref><ref>https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/video/2017/aug/21/dresnok-sons-our-father-told-us-to-serve-kim-jong-un-video</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[Unsung Heroes]]'' (a.k.a. ''Nameless Heroes'') (1978)<ref name=\"Spillerlastdefect\"/>\n* ''From 5 p.m. to 5&nbsp;am'' (1990)<ref>{{IMDb title|tt2162559|From 5 p.m. to 5&nbsp;am}}</ref>\n* ''[[Crossing the Line (2006 film)|Crossing the Line]]'' (2006)<ref name=\"Spillerlastdefect\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|North Korea}}\n* [[Americans in North Korea]]\n* [[List of American and British defectors in the Korean War]]\n* [[North Korean defectors]]\n* [[South Korean defectors]]\n\n'''Other defectors to North Korea'''\n* [[List of American and British defectors in the Korean War]]: the 21 Americans and 1 Briton who refused repatriation during [[Operation Big Switch]] in 1953 (in order to remain in [[China]])\n* [[Larry Allen Abshier]] (1943\u20131983) from [[Urbana, Illinois]], deserted in May 1962 at the age of 19\n* [[Jerry Wayne Parrish]] (1944\u20131996) from [[Morganfield, Kentucky]], deserted in December 1963 at the age of 19\n* [[Charles Robert Jenkins]] (1940\u20132017) from [[Rich Square, North Carolina]], deserted on January 5, 1965 at the age of 24\n* [[Roy Chung]] (born {{circa|1957}}), an American who was born in South Korea, deserted in June 1979\n* [[Joseph T. White]] (1961\u20131985) from [[St Louis, Missouri]], deserted in August 1982 at the age of 20.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"United Nations Human Rights Council 2014\">{{cite journal |first1= Michael Donald|last1=Kirby |authorlink1=Michael Kirby (judge) |first2=Sonja |last2=Biserko  |authorlink2=Sonja Biserko |first3= Marzuki|last3=Darusman  |authorlink3=Marzuki Darusman  |date=February 7, 2014 |title=Report of the detailed findings of the commission of inquiry on human rights in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea - A/HRC/25/CRP.1 |publisher=[[United Nations Human Rights Council]] |url= http://www.ohchr.org/Documents/HRBodies/HRCouncil/CoIDPRK/Report/A.HRC.25.CRP.1_ENG.doc|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227104633/http://www.ohchr.org/Documents/HRBodies/HRCouncil/CoIDPRK/Report/A.HRC.25.CRP.1_ENG.doc | archivedate= February 27, 2014 |url-status=live |pages=306 (Paragraph 973) |quote= Ms Dona Bumbea disappeared from Italy in 1978 and is believed to have been lured to the DPRK. Ms Bumbea had been studying art in Italy at the time when she met an Italian man claiming to be an art dealer, who convinced her to hold an exhibition in [[Hong Kong]]. The two travelled to Pyongyang en-route to Hong Kong at which point the Italian disappeared. Ms Bumbea was kept in the DPRK and \"given\" to American army deserter Mr Dresnock. Ms Bumbea died in the DPRK and is survived by her two sons, Mr Ricardo Dresnock born in 1981 and Mr James Gabriel Dresnock, born in 1983, both of whom have been seen in several documentaries including \"Crossing the line\" (2006) and \"Aim High in Creation\" (2013). Ms Bumbea's family in Romania has been unable to have any contact with Ms Bumbea's sons despite their wish to.}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1DvBybErjUM ''The Americans Who Chose To Live in North Korea'' BBC Documentary]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090328131541/http://www.theworld.org/?q=node%2F7662 The World: Crossing the line audio report]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/1469616/US-defector-says-he-is-happier-in-North-Korea.html ''Telegraph'':  US defector says he is happier in North Korea]\n* [http://www.cbsnews.com/sections/60minutes/main3415.shtml CBS: Defector Won\u2019t Leave N. Korea For $1B]\n* [http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2004/06/02/world/main620738.shtml CBS: N. Korea\u2019s Last U.S. Defector]\n* [http://www.avclub.com/content/cinema/crossing_the_line Review] of ''Crossing the Line''\n* [http://www.rfa.org/english/news/social/2007/03/20/nkorea_romania/] Doina Bumbea EN\n* [http://www.uyghurnews.com/index.asp?ItemID=NM-213200872549193242133] Doina Bumbea EN (2)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080519015620/http://stiri.rol.ro/content/view/47815/2/] Doina Bumbea RO\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/sep/09/korea.usa \"The Dear Leader Takes Care of Me\" 9-9-2008]\n* [https://www.nknews.org/2017/04/jim-dresnok-american-who-defected-to-n-korea-in-1962-died-in-2016 \"Jim Dresnok, American who defected to N.Korea in 1962, died in 2016]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dresnok, James Joseph}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:American defectors]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in North Korea]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:North Korean male film actors]]\n[[Category:People from Norfolk, Virginia]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of North Korea]]\n[[Category:20th-century North Korean male actors]]\n[[Category:Date of death missing]]\n[[Category:People from Pyongyang]]\n", "name_user": "Muzilon", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:CQ", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Joseph_Dresnok"}
{"title_page": "Nutrition", "text_new": "{{about|nutrition in general|nutrition in humans|Human nutrition|nutrition in animals|Animal nutrition|nutrition in plants|Plant nutrition|the medical journal|Nutrition (journal)}}\n{{short description|Provision to cells and organisms to support life}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n'''Nutrition''' is the [[science]] that interprets the [[nutrients]] and other substances in [[food]] in relation to maintenance, growth, reproduction, [[health]] and disease of an organism. It includes food intake, [[Absorption (biology)|absorption]], [[Assimilation (biology)|assimilation]], [[biosynthesis]], [[catabolism]] and [[excretion]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/pubs/cd_hum.nut.html#2|title=Joint Collection Development Policy: Human Nutrition and Food|publisher=US National Library of Medicine, National Institutes of Health|date=14 October 2014|accessdate=13 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Diet (nutrition)|diet]] of an organism is what it eats, which is largely determined by the availability and [[palatability]] of foods. For humans, a [[healthy diet]] includes [[Food preparation|preparation of food]] and storage methods that preserve nutrients from oxidation, heat or leaching, and that reduces risk of [[foodborne illness]]es. The seven major classes of human nutrients are [[carbohydrates]], [[fat]]s, [[dietary fiber|fiber]], [[dietary minerals|minerals]], [[protein]]s, [[vitamin]]s, and [[water]]. Nutrients can be grouped as either [[macronutrients]] or [[micronutrients]] (needed in small quantities).\n\nIn humans, an unhealthy diet can cause deficiency-related diseases such as [[blindness]], [[anemia]], [[scurvy]], [[preterm birth]], [[stillbirth]] and [[cretinism]],<ref name=Whitney-Rolfes-lead>{{cite book|title=Understanding Nutrition|author1=Whitney, Ellie  |author2=Rolfes, Sharon Rady|isbn=978-1-133-58752-1|year=2013|edition=13|publisher=Wadsworth, Cengage Learning|pages=667, 670}}</ref> or nutrient excess health-threatening conditions such as [[obesity]]<ref>[http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/causes/prostate/weightgain0307 Obesity, Weight Linked to Prostate Cancer Deaths \u2013 National Cancer Institute] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607220946/http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/causes/prostate/weightgain0307 |date=7 June 2011 }}. Cancer.gov. Retrieved on 2011-10-17.</ref><ref>[https://www.cdc.gov/obesity/causes/index.html Obesity and Overweight for Professionals: Causes | DNPAO | CDC] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224122909/http://www.cdc.gov/obesity/causes/index.html |date=24 February 2016 }}. Cdc.gov (16 May 2011). Retrieved on 2011-10-17.</ref> and [[metabolic syndrome]];<ref>[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmedhealth/PMH0004546/ Metabolic syndrome \u2013 PubMed Health]. Ncbi.nlm.nih.gov. Retrieved on 2011-10-17.</ref> and such common chronic systemic diseases as [[cardiovascular disease]],<ref>[http://www.umm.edu/altmed/articles/omega-3-000316.htm Omega-3 fatty acids]. Umm.edu (5 October 2011). Retrieved on 2011-10-17.</ref> [[diabetes]],<ref>[http://diabetes.niddk.nih.gov/dm/pubs/eating_ez/ What I need to know about Eating and Diabetes \u2013 National Diabetes Information Clearinghouse]. Diabetes.niddk.nih.gov. Retrieved on 2011-10-17.</ref><ref>[http://www.helpguide.org/life/healthy_diet_diabetes.htm Diabetes Diet and Food Tips: Eating to Prevent and Control Diabetes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520045538/http://www.helpguide.org/life/healthy_diet_diabetes.htm |date=20 May 2011 }}. Helpguide.org. Retrieved on 2011-10-17.</ref> and [[osteoporosis]].<ref>[http://www.webmd.com/osteoporosis/guide/vitamin-d-for-osteoporosis Osteoporosis & Vitamin D: Deficiency, How Much, Benefits, and More]. Webmd.com (7 July 2005). Retrieved on 2011-10-17.</ref><ref>[http://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/VitaminD-HealthProfessional/ Dietary Supplement Fact Sheet: Vitamin D]. Ods.od.nih.gov. Retrieved on 2011-10-17.</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/specials/women/warchive/980319_807.html | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080309082228/http://www.nytimes.com/specials/women/warchive/980319_807.html | archivedate=9 March 2008 | work=The New York Times | title=Osteoporosis Linked to Vitamin D Deficiency|author=Brody, Jane E. |date=19 March 1998}}</ref> Undernutrition can lead to [[wasting]] in acute cases, and the [[stunted growth|stunting]] of [[marasmus]] in chronic cases of [[malnutrition]].<ref name=Whitney-Rolfes-lead />\n\n==Animal nutrition==\n{{main|Animal nutrition|Human nutrition}}\n\n[[Carnivore]] and [[herbivore]] diets are contrasting, with basic [[nitrogen]] and [[carbon]] proportions vary for their particular foods. Many herbivores rely on bacterial fermentation to create digestible nutrients from indigestible plant cellulose, while obligate carnivores must eat animal meats to obtain certain vitamins or nutrients their bodies cannot otherwise synthesize. Animals generally have a higher requirement of energy in comparison to plants.<ref>{{cite web|last1=National Geographic Society|title=Herbivore|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.org/encyclopedia/herbivore/|website=National Geographic Society|accessdate=1 May 2017|language=en|date=21 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Plant nutrition==\n\n{{Main|Plant nutrition}}\nPlant nutrition is the study of the [[chemical element]]s that are necessary for plant growth.<ref>{{cite book|title=Handbook of Plant Nutrition|author1=Allen V. Barker |author2=David J. Pilbeam | page=Preface| publisher=CRC Press, 2010}}</ref> There are several principles that apply to plant nutrition. Some elements are directly involved in plant [[metabolism]]. However, this principle does not account for the so-called beneficial elements, whose presence, while not required, has clear positive effects on plant growth.\n\nA nutrient that is able to limit plant growth according to [[Liebig's law of the minimum]] is considered an essential plant nutrient if the plant cannot complete its full life cycle without it. There are 16 essential plant soil nutrients, besides the three major elemental nutrients carbon and oxygen that are obtained by photosynthetic plants from carbon dioxide in air, and [[hydrogen]], which is obtained from water.\n\nPlants uptake essential elements from the [[soil]] through their [[root]]s and from the air (consisting of mainly nitrogen and oxygen) through their [[Leaf|leaves]]. Green plants obtain their carbohydrate supply from the carbon dioxide in the air by the process of [[photosynthesis]]. Carbon and oxygen are absorbed from the air, while other nutrients are absorbed from the soil. Nutrient uptake in the soil is achieved by [[cation exchange]], wherein [[root hair]]s pump [[hydrogen ion]]s (H<sup>+</sup>) into the soil through [[proton pump]]s. These hydrogen ions displace [[cation]]s attached to negatively charged soil particles so that the cations are available for uptake by the root. In the leaves, [[stomata]] open to take in carbon dioxide and expel [[oxygen]]. The carbon dioxide molecules are used as the carbon source in photosynthesis.\n\nAlthough [[nitrogen]] is plentiful in the Earth's atmosphere, very few plants can use this directly. Most plants, therefore, require nitrogen compounds to be present in the soil in which they grow. This is made possible by the fact that largely inert atmospheric nitrogen is changed in a [[nitrogen fixation]] process to biologically usable forms in the soil by bacteria.<ref>Lindemann, W.C. and Glover C.R. (2003) [http://aces.nmsu.edu/pubs/_a/A129/welcome.html Nitrogen Fixation by Legumes]. New Mexico State University/</ref>\n\nPlant nutrition is a difficult subject to understand completely, partially because of the variation between different plants and even between different species or individuals of a given [[cloning|clone]]. Elements present at low levels may cause deficiency symptoms, and toxicity is possible at levels that are too high. Furthermore, deficiency of one element may present as symptoms of toxicity from another element, and vice versa.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Nutrition|Food|Minerals}}\n* [[Auxology]]\n* [[Exercise]]\n* [[Food preferences in older adults and seniors]]\n* [[Nutrition psychology]]\n* [[Palatability]]\n* [[Physical fitness]]\n* [[Veganism]]\n* [[Vegetarianism]]\n*[https://dietmantrabymonika.com/ Dietitian] \n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|author=Carpenter, Kenneth J.|title=Protein and Energy: A Study of Changing Ideas in Nutrition|year=1994|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-45209-0}}\n* Curley, S., and Mark (1990). ''The Natural Guide to Good Health'', Lafayette, Louisiana, Supreme Publishing\n* {{cite book | author=Galdston, I. | title=Human Nutrition Historic and Scientific | location=New York | publisher=International Universities Press | year=1960}}<!-- LCCN RA 605 -->\n* {{cite book|author=Gratzer, Walter|authorlink=Walter Gratzer|title=Terrors of the Table: The Curious History of Nutrition|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2006|origyear=2005|isbn=978-0-19-920563-9}}\n* {{cite book | editor1=Mahan, L.K. |editor2=Escott-Stump, S. | year=2000 | title=Krause's Food, Nutrition, and Diet Therapy | edition=10th | location=Philadelphia | publisher=W.B. Saunders Harcourt Brace |isbn=978-0-7216-7904-4}}\n* {{cite book | author=[[Jean-Pierre Thiollet|Thiollet, J.-P.]] | title=Vitamines & min\u00e9raux | location=Paris | publisher=Anagramme | year=2001}}\n* {{cite journal |author1=Walter C. Willett |author2=Meir J. Stampfer | title=Rebuilding the Food Pyramid | journal=Scientific American |date=January 2003 |pmid=12506426 |volume=288 |issue=1 | pages=64\u201371 | doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0103-64}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wiktionary|nutrition}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.who.int/nutrition/topics/dietnutrition_and_chronicdiseases/en/ Diet, Nutrition and the prevention of chronic diseases] by a Joint [[WHO]]/[[FAO]] Expert consultation (2003)\n* [http://www.unscn.org/ UN Standing Committee on Nutrition] \u2013 In English, French and Portuguese\n\n{{Food science}}\n{{Allied health professions}}\n{{Public health}}\n{{Diets}}\n\n[[Category:Applied sciences]]\n[[Category:Food science]]\n[[Category:Nutrition| ]]\n[[Category:Self-care]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|nutrition in general|nutrition in humans|Human nutrition|nutrition in animals|Animal nutrition|nutrition in plants|Plant nutrition|the medical journal|Nutrition (journal)}}\n{{short description|Provision to cells and organisms to support life}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n'''Nutrition''' is the [[science]] that interprets the [[nutrients]] and other substances in [[food]] in relation to maintenance, growth, reproduction, [[health]] and disease of an organism. It includes food intake, [[Absorption (biology)|absorption]], [[Assimilation (biology)|assimilation]], [[biosynthesis]], [[catabolism]] and [[excretion]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/pubs/cd_hum.nut.html#2|title=Joint Collection Development Policy: Human Nutrition and Food|publisher=US National Library of Medicine, National Institutes of Health|date=14 October 2014|accessdate=13 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Diet (nutrition)|diet]] of an organism is what it eats, which is largely determined by the availability and [[palatability]] of foods. For humans, a [[healthy diet]] includes [[Food preparation|preparation of food]] and storage methods that preserve nutrients from oxidation, heat or leaching, and that reduces risk of [[foodborne illness]]es. The seven major classes of human nutrients are [[carbohydrates]], [[fat]]s, [[dietary fiber|fiber]], [[dietary minerals|minerals]], [[protein]]s, [[vitamin]]s, and [[water]]. Nutrients can be grouped as either [[macronutrients]] or [[micronutrients]] (needed in small quantities).\n\nIn humans, an unhealthy diet can cause deficiency-related diseases such as [[blindness]], [[anemia]], [[scurvy]], [[preterm birth]], [[stillbirth]] and [[cretinism]],<ref name=Whitney-Rolfes-lead>{{cite book|title=Understanding Nutrition|author1=Whitney, Ellie  |author2=Rolfes, Sharon Rady|isbn=978-1-133-58752-1|year=2013|edition=13|publisher=Wadsworth, Cengage Learning|pages=667, 670}}</ref> or nutrient excess health-threatening conditions such as [[obesity]]<ref>[http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/causes/prostate/weightgain0307 Obesity, Weight Linked to Prostate Cancer Deaths \u2013 National Cancer Institute] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607220946/http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/causes/prostate/weightgain0307 |date=7 June 2011 }}. Cancer.gov. Retrieved on 2011-10-17.</ref><ref>[https://www.cdc.gov/obesity/causes/index.html Obesity and Overweight for Professionals: Causes | DNPAO | CDC] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224122909/http://www.cdc.gov/obesity/causes/index.html |date=24 February 2016 }}. Cdc.gov (16 May 2011). Retrieved on 2011-10-17.</ref> and [[metabolic syndrome]];<ref>[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmedhealth/PMH0004546/ Metabolic syndrome \u2013 PubMed Health]. Ncbi.nlm.nih.gov. Retrieved on 2011-10-17.</ref> and such common chronic systemic diseases as [[cardiovascular disease]],<ref>[http://www.umm.edu/altmed/articles/omega-3-000316.htm Omega-3 fatty acids]. Umm.edu (5 October 2011). Retrieved on 2011-10-17.</ref> [[diabetes]],<ref>[http://diabetes.niddk.nih.gov/dm/pubs/eating_ez/ What I need to know about Eating and Diabetes \u2013 National Diabetes Information Clearinghouse]. Diabetes.niddk.nih.gov. Retrieved on 2011-10-17.</ref><ref>[http://www.helpguide.org/life/healthy_diet_diabetes.htm Diabetes Diet and Food Tips: Eating to Prevent and Control Diabetes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520045538/http://www.helpguide.org/life/healthy_diet_diabetes.htm |date=20 May 2011 }}. Helpguide.org. Retrieved on 2011-10-17.</ref> and [[osteoporosis]].<ref>[http://www.webmd.com/osteoporosis/guide/vitamin-d-for-osteoporosis Osteoporosis & Vitamin D: Deficiency, How Much, Benefits, and More]. Webmd.com (7 July 2005). Retrieved on 2011-10-17.</ref><ref>[http://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/VitaminD-HealthProfessional/ Dietary Supplement Fact Sheet: Vitamin D]. Ods.od.nih.gov. Retrieved on 2011-10-17.</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/specials/women/warchive/980319_807.html | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080309082228/http://www.nytimes.com/specials/women/warchive/980319_807.html | archivedate=9 March 2008 | work=The New York Times | title=Osteoporosis Linked to Vitamin D Deficiency|author=Brody, Jane E. |date=19 March 1998}}</ref> Undernutrition can lead to [[wasting]] in acute cases, and the [[stunted growth|stunting]] of [[marasmus]] in chronic cases of [[malnutrition]].<ref name=Whitney-Rolfes-lead />\n\n==Animal nutrition==\n{{main|Animal nutrition|Human nutrition}}\n\n[[Carnivore]] and [[herbivore]] diets are contrasting, with basic [[nitrogen]] and [[carbon]] proportions vary for their particular foods. Many herbivores rely on bacterial fermentation to create digestible nutrients from indigestible plant cellulose, while obligate carnivores must eat animal meats to obtain certain vitamins or nutrients their bodies cannot otherwise synthesize. Animals generally have a higher requirement of energy in comparison to plants.<ref>{{cite web|last1=National Geographic Society|title=Herbivore|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.org/encyclopedia/herbivore/|website=National Geographic Society|accessdate=1 May 2017|language=en|date=21 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Plant nutrition==\n\n{{Main|Plant nutrition}}\nPlant nutrition is the study of the [[chemical element]]s that are necessary for plant growth.<ref>{{cite book|title=Handbook of Plant Nutrition|author1=Allen V. Barker |author2=David J. Pilbeam | page=Preface| publisher=CRC Press, 2010}}</ref> There are several principles that apply to plant nutrition. Some elements are directly involved in plant [[metabolism]]. However, this principle does not account for the so-called beneficial elements, whose presence, while not required, has clear positive effects on plant growth.\n\nA nutrient that is able to limit plant growth according to [[Liebig's law of the minimum]] is considered an essential plant nutrient if the plant cannot complete its full life cycle without it. There are 16 essential plant soil nutrients, besides the three major elemental nutrients carbon and oxygen that are obtained by photosynthetic plants from carbon dioxide in air, and [[hydrogen]], which is obtained from water.\n\nPlants uptake essential elements from the [[soil]] through their [[root]]s and from the air (consisting of mainly nitrogen and oxygen) through their [[Leaf|leaves]]. Green plants obtain their carbohydrate supply from the carbon dioxide in the air by the process of [[photosynthesis]]. Carbon and oxygen are absorbed from the air, while other nutrients are absorbed from the soil. Nutrient uptake in the soil is achieved by [[cation exchange]], wherein [[root hair]]s pump [[hydrogen ion]]s (H<sup>+</sup>) into the soil through [[proton pump]]s. These hydrogen ions displace [[cation]]s attached to negatively charged soil particles so that the cations are available for uptake by the root. In the leaves, [[stomata]] open to take in carbon dioxide and expel [[oxygen]]. The carbon dioxide molecules are used as the carbon source in photosynthesis.\n\nAlthough [[nitrogen]] is plentiful in the Earth's atmosphere, very few plants can use this directly. Most plants, therefore, require nitrogen compounds to be present in the soil in which they grow. This is made possible by the fact that largely inert atmospheric nitrogen is changed in a [[nitrogen fixation]] process to biologically usable forms in the soil by bacteria.<ref>Lindemann, W.C. and Glover C.R. (2003) [http://aces.nmsu.edu/pubs/_a/A129/welcome.html Nitrogen Fixation by Legumes]. New Mexico State University/</ref>\n\nPlant nutrition is a difficult subject to understand completely, partially because of the variation between different plants and even between different species or individuals of a given [[cloning|clone]]. Elements present at low levels may cause deficiency symptoms, and toxicity is possible at levels that are too high. Furthermore, deficiency of one element may present as symptoms of toxicity from another element, and vice versa.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Nutrition|Food|Minerals}}\n* [[Auxology]]\n* [[Exercise]]\n* [[Food preferences in older adults and seniors]]\n* [[Nutrition psychology]]\n* [[Palatability]]\n* [[Physical fitness]]\n* [[Veganism]]\n* [[Vegetarianism]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|author=Carpenter, Kenneth J.|title=Protein and Energy: A Study of Changing Ideas in Nutrition|year=1994|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-45209-0}}\n* Curley, S., and Mark (1990). ''The Natural Guide to Good Health'', Lafayette, Louisiana, Supreme Publishing\n* {{cite book | author=Galdston, I. | title=Human Nutrition Historic and Scientific | location=New York | publisher=International Universities Press | year=1960}}<!-- LCCN RA 605 -->\n* {{cite book|author=Gratzer, Walter|authorlink=Walter Gratzer|title=Terrors of the Table: The Curious History of Nutrition|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2006|origyear=2005|isbn=978-0-19-920563-9}}\n* {{cite book | editor1=Mahan, L.K. |editor2=Escott-Stump, S. | year=2000 | title=Krause's Food, Nutrition, and Diet Therapy | edition=10th | location=Philadelphia | publisher=W.B. Saunders Harcourt Brace |isbn=978-0-7216-7904-4}}\n* {{cite book | author=[[Jean-Pierre Thiollet|Thiollet, J.-P.]] | title=Vitamines & min\u00e9raux | location=Paris | publisher=Anagramme | year=2001}}\n* {{cite journal |author1=Walter C. Willett |author2=Meir J. Stampfer | title=Rebuilding the Food Pyramid | journal=Scientific American |date=January 2003 |pmid=12506426 |volume=288 |issue=1 | pages=64\u201371 | doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0103-64}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wiktionary|nutrition}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.who.int/nutrition/topics/dietnutrition_and_chronicdiseases/en/ Diet, Nutrition and the prevention of chronic diseases] by a Joint [[WHO]]/[[FAO]] Expert consultation (2003)\n* [http://www.unscn.org/ UN Standing Committee on Nutrition] \u2013 In English, French and Portuguese\n\n{{Food science}}\n{{Allied health professions}}\n{{Public health}}\n{{Diets}}\n\n[[Category:Applied sciences]]\n[[Category:Food science]]\n[[Category:Nutrition| ]]\n[[Category:Self-care]]\n", "name_user": "Seodesigns", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I added one more link this is a relevent link in this article. just a minor edit.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nutrition"}
{"title_page": "Electronic human resources", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=September 2010}}\n{{orphan|date=September 2010}}\n{{original research|date=September 2010}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Ehr diagram.jpg|thumb|270px| E-HR diagram showing some of the different aspects that affect E-HR]]\n''''''pep\u00a2 human resources''' is a function of HR that is concerned with the use, management, and regulation of electronic information and processes within an organization.\n\nE-HR is different from [[E-HRM|E-HRM (Electronic Human Resource Management)]] and [[kld|dld (Human Resource Information System)]] which are uses of technology. More specifically, E-HRM is a system that allows management and employees access to human resource related information and services through an organization's [[intranet]] or [[web portal]]. HRIS refers to enterprise resource planning software that streamlines human resource functions such as payroll.\n\nIn contrast, E-HR is a function of human resources that requires cross-functional knowledge and collaboration between multiple departments, most notably human resources and information technology.\n\n==Management==\nThe Management aspect of E-HR involves drafting policies and controlling both the traffic and collection of electronic information.\n\nAs new technology comes out that is more portable and capable of creating and storing more information, it is the responsibility of HR to define how employees interact with the data. According to a Deloitte study in August 2008, 90% of employer data is electronically stored information (ESI), and 40% of executives say that data volumes are becoming unmanageable. Unmanageable data makes locating relevant data more challenging which can manifest into significant losses through wasted storage space and reductions in productivity. Excessive data volumes is especially troublesome during litigation that requires [[e-discovery|electronic discovery]].\n\nE-HR policies strive to control and organize data within an organization. To accomplish this, effective [[records management]] policies must be created to facilitate lean data storage which involves maintaining pertinent information while removing data as it becomes irrelevant.\n\n==Regulation==\nE-HR also involves the regulation of electronic data and processes. This requires employers to monitor employees and establish security measures to prevent employee data theft and misuse of technology. Regulation is a vital component of E-HR because data is considered a form of collateral. Therefore, similar to other capital assets, it becomes a business necessity and fiduciary duty to protect the assets of a company from theft or exploitation.\n\nToday, data theft is known one of the fastest growing [[white-collar crime]]s globally. Unfortunately, a significant source of data theft is employees and former employees because they have access to intellectual property stored on company networks. As a result, preventing data theft is a primary concern of E-HR specialists. Good.\n\n==Related Case Law==\nThere are numerous legal cases that have increased the need for E-HR over the last decade. As case law is established through hearings the role of human resources with respect to technology will continue to grow to reduce liabilities from future litigation. Below are two cases related to E-HR:\n\nA case from New Jersey<ref>New Jersey Appellate Court, [http://www.internetlibrary.com/pdf/Jane-Doe-XYC-Corporation-NJ-AD.pdf Jane Doe v. XYC Corporation]</ref> demonstrates the need for employers to monitor and discipline employees for misuse of technology. In the case an accounting employee posted nude photographs of his step daughter on the internet from the employer's computer. The mother claimed that the employer knew or should have known that the employee was using company computer systems to view, download and participate in child pornography. The Court stated: \u201cWe agree with plaintiff that defendant [the employer] had a duty to report Employee\u2019s activities to the proper authorities and to take effective internal action to stop those activities, whether by termination or some less drastic remedy.\u201d The Court then sent the case back to the lower court for a trial on whether the employer\u2019s action was the cause of the claimed injuries.\n\nThe Supreme Court ruled in favor of the California police chief which addressed whether the 4th Amendment's ban on \"unreasonable searches\" puts any limits on searches by public employers. The court said the limits were minimal, so long as the employer had a \"work-related purpose\" for inspecting an employee's desk or reading messages sent by the employee on an agency paging system., because it is considered reasonable search.<ref>Savage, David G., LA Times, [http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jun/18/nation/la-na-court-worker-texting-20100618 Supreme Court rules in favor of California police chief who read employee's texts]</ref> The ruling came was based on a situation where police officers who sued after a wireless provider gave their department transcripts of an officer's text messages. The case is on appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court.\n\n==References==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.gvsu.edu/e-hr/ Grand Valley State University: Digital Workplace]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Electronic Human Resources}}\n[[Category:Human resource management]]\n[[Category:Information technology management]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=September 2010}}\n{{orphan|date=September 2010}}\n{{original research|date=September 2010}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Ehr diagram.jpg|thumb|270px| E-HR diagram showing some of the different aspects that affect E-HR]]\n'''E-HR''' is a function of HR that is concerned with the use, management, and regulation of electronic information and processes within an organization.\n\nE-HR is different from [[E-HRM|E-HRM (Electronic Human Resource Management)]] and [[HRIS|HRIS (Human Resource Information System)]] which are uses of technology. More specifically, E-HRM is a system that allows management and employees access to human resource related information and services through an organization's [[intranet]] or [[web portal]]. HRIS refers to enterprise resource planning software that streamlines human resource functions such as payroll.\n\nIn contrast, E-HR is a function of human resources that requires cross-functional knowledge and collaboration between multiple departments, most notably human resources and information technology.\n\n==Management==\nThe Management aspect of E-HR involves drafting policies and controlling both the traffic and collection of electronic information.\n\nAs new technology comes out that is more portable and capable of creating and storing more information, it is the responsibility of HR to define how employees interact with the data. According to a Deloitte study in August 2008, 90% of employer data is electronically stored information (ESI), and 40% of executives say that data volumes are becoming unmanageable. Unmanageable data makes locating relevant data more challenging which can manifest into significant losses through wasted storage space and reductions in productivity. Excessive data volumes is especially troublesome during litigation that requires [[e-discovery|electronic discovery]].\n\nE-HR policies strive to control and organize data within an organization. To accomplish this, effective [[records management]] policies must be created to facilitate lean data storage which involves maintaining pertinent information while removing data as it becomes irrelevant.\n\n==Regulation==\nE-HR also involves the regulation of electronic data and processes. This requires employers to monitor employees and establish security measures to prevent employee data theft and misuse of technology. Regulation is a vital component of E-HR because data is considered a form of collateral. Therefore, similar to other capital assets, it becomes a business necessity and fiduciary duty to protect the assets of a company from theft or exploitation.\n\nToday, data theft is known one of the fastest growing [[white-collar crime]]s globally. Unfortunately, a significant source of data theft is employees and former employees because they have access to intellectual property stored on company networks. As a result, preventing data theft is a primary concern of E-HR specialists. Good.\n\n==Related Case Law==\nThere are numerous legal cases that have increased the need for E-HR over the last decade. As case law is established through hearings the role of human resources with respect to technology will continue to grow to reduce liabilities from future litigation. Below are two cases related to E-HR:\n\nA case from New Jersey<ref>New Jersey Appellate Court, [http://www.internetlibrary.com/pdf/Jane-Doe-XYC-Corporation-NJ-AD.pdf Jane Doe v. XYC Corporation]</ref> demonstrates the need for employers to monitor and discipline employees for misuse of technology. In the case an accounting employee posted nude photographs of his step daughter on the internet from the employer's computer. The mother claimed that the employer knew or should have known that the employee was using company computer systems to view, download and participate in child pornography. The Court stated: \u201cWe agree with plaintiff that defendant [the employer] had a duty to report Employee\u2019s activities to the proper authorities and to take effective internal action to stop those activities, whether by termination or some less drastic remedy.\u201d The Court then sent the case back to the lower court for a trial on whether the employer\u2019s action was the cause of the claimed injuries.\n\nThe Supreme Court ruled in favor of the California police chief which addressed whether the 4th Amendment's ban on \"unreasonable searches\" puts any limits on searches by public employers. The court said the limits were minimal, so long as the employer had a \"work-related purpose\" for inspecting an employee's desk or reading messages sent by the employee on an agency paging system., because it is considered reasonable search.<ref>Savage, David G., LA Times, [http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jun/18/nation/la-na-court-worker-texting-20100618 Supreme Court rules in favor of California police chief who read employee's texts]</ref> The ruling came was based on a situation where police officers who sued after a wireless provider gave their department transcripts of an officer's text messages. The case is on appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court.\n\n==References==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.gvsu.edu/e-hr/ Grand Valley State University: Digital Workplace]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Electronic Human Resources}}\n[[Category:Human resource management]]\n[[Category:Information technology management]]\n", "name_user": "2601:380:c101:f300:ecfe:4948:baae:503e", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_human_resources"}
{"title_page": "Augustus Barrows", "text_new": "'''Augustus R. Barrows''' (also known as '''A. R. Barrows''') (July 30, 1838 \u2013 December 20, 1885) was an American [[lumberman]] from [[Chippewa Falls, Wisconsin|Chippewa Falls]], [[Wisconsin]] who spent one term as an [[Independent (politics)|independent]] [[Greenback Party|Greenbacker]] member of the [[Wisconsin State Assembly]] from [[Chippewa County, Wisconsin|Chippewa County]], serving as the [[Speaker of the Wisconsin State Assembly]] even though his party held only 13 of 100 seats therein.<ref>[http://legis.state.wi.us/LRB/pubs/ib/99ib1.pdf Cannon, A. Peter, ed. ''Members of the Wisconsin Legislature: 1848\u20131999''. State of Wisconsin Legislative Reference Bureau Informational Bulletin 99-1, September 1999; p. 26.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061209014416/http://legis.state.wi.us/LRB/pubs/ib/99ib1.pdf |date=2006-12-09 }}</ref> He later moved to [[Montana]], where he became a rancher, and ran a saloon-hotel, a [[general store]], and a [[sawmill]].\n\n== Background ==\nBarrows was born in [[Olean, New York]] on July 30, 1838; he studied at an academy (later renamed [[Chamberlain Institute]]) in [[Randolph, New York]], where his father was a pioneering lumberman. Augustus assisted his father in his business until on one of their trips to Cincinnati on a [[raft]], his father lost a leg in an accident. He closed out his business in New York and moved with his family to [[Pleasant Grove, Minnesota]] in 1855, and went into farming. Augustus, who had accompanied his family to their new home, \"followed various pursuits\" for a while. He married Alice B. Duncan in Pleasant Grove on November 16, 1862. \n\nBarrows enlisted as a private in the [[11th Minnesota Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] during the [[American Civil War]] and was mustered out as a [[lieutenant]] on June 30, 1865. On mustering out, he returned to Wisconsin, settling in [[Chippewa County, Wisconsin|Chippewa County]].\n\n==Public office == \nBarrows was elected County [[Treasurer]] of Chippewa County in 1869 to fill a vacancy, and re-elected for a full term in 1870; and served one term as [[mayor]] of Chippewa Falls.<ref name=\"Death Notice\">{{cite news|title=Wisconsin News: A. R. Barrows |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4817331/augustus_barrows_18381885/|newspaper=The Weekly Wisconsin|date=December 26, 1885|page=8|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = April 3, 2016}} {{Open access}}</ref> In 1872, he ran for the Assembly as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], losing to incumbent [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Albert Pound]] (who was also a lumberman from Chippewa Falls), with 676 votes to Pound's 1205. In 1876, he ran for the [[Wisconsin State Senate]]'s [[Wisconsin Senate, District 11|Eleventh District]] (again as a Democrat), losing to incumbent Republican [[Thomas Scott (Wisconsin politician)|Thomas Scott]] with 3,700 votes to Scott's 3,925.\n\nHe became a vigorous adherent of the [[Greenback Party|Greenback movement]], becoming known as \"one of its ablest and most logical advocates in the state\". In 1877, he ran for Chippewa County's sole Assembly seat as an independent Greenback, unseating Democratic incumbent [[Louis Vincent]], who polled only 496 votes to 886 votes for Barrows and 555 for Republican O. R. Dahl. He was chosen as [[speaker (politics)|speaker]] on January 9, 1878, because the Assembly now consisted of 45 Republicans, 41 Democrats, 13 Greenbacks and a [[Sewer Socialists|socialist]]: thus, the Greenbacks and socialist had leverage as tie-breakers, since the two major parties held mere pluralities.<ref>[http://digital.library.wisc.edu/1711.dl/WI.WIBlueBk1878 Bashford, R. M., ed. ''The legislative manual of the state of Wisconsin: comprising the constitutions of the United States and of the state of Wisconsin, Jefferson's manual, forms and laws for the regulation of business; also, lists and tables for reference, etc.'' Seventeenth Annual Edition. Madison: David Atwood, Printer and Stereotyper, 1878; pp. 391, 392, 457, 465-466, 486.]</ref> \n\nIn 1879, rather than run for re-election, he ran for [[United States House of Representatives|Congress]] under a [[electoral fusion|fusion]] [[ticket (election)|ticket]] as a Greenback/Democrat in the [[Wisconsin's 8th congressional district|Eighth District]], losing with 11,421 votes to 12,795 for Republican incumbent [[Thaddeus C. Pound]] (brother and partner of Albert Pound). He was succeeded in the Assembly by Republican former Assemblyman [[Hector McRae]].\n\n== Moving to Montana ==\nAfter losing the Congressional election, Barrows (who had suffered financial reverses in the [[real estate]] which constituted most of his wealth) organized a group of colonists who arrived in [[Martinsdale, Montana]] (a [[train stop]] on the main line of the [[Chicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul and Pacific Railroad|Milwaukee Road]]), in June 1879. He brought a herd of [[purebred#Purebred livestock|blooded]] [[cattle]] with him, and went into [[stockraising]], which he pursued for the rest of his life. Soon after his arrival there, he and [[Edward P. Allis]] of [[Milwaukee]] partnered to build a large sawmill, and began the manufacture of lumber at [[Sawmill Gulch, Montana|Sawmill Gulch]] in what was then [[Meagher County, Montana]]. He [[Homestead Act|homesteaded]] 160 acres in a place he called [[Ubet, Montana|\"Ubet\", also known as \"U-Bet\" or \"U-bet\"]] in what was then [[Fergus County, Montana|Fergus County]]. He built a [[stage stop]] hotel, [[Western saloon|saloon]] and [[general store]] on the [[stagecoach]] route, and moved there himself in 1881, becoming (with his family) among the first permanent white settlers of the [[Judith Basin County, Montana|Judith Basin]].\n\nHe died on December 20, 1885 in Ubet,<ref name=\"Death Notice\"/> and was buried back in Chippewa Falls in a [[Freemasonry|Masonic ceremony]] (he was a [[Knights Templar (Freemasonry)|Masonic Knight Templar]]). He left Alice with a family of young children, but she continued to operate the businesses with the aid of her children, eventually increasing the original homestead to an estate of 2,000 acres. The Barrows were the parents of four children: John R.; Mary, who died at two years of age; Olive; and Clarence H.<ref>''Progressive Men of Montana'' Chicago: A. W. Bowen & Co. [n.d.]; vol. 2, pp. 993-994</ref> John, who became a lawyer in [[San Diego, California]], later wrote a memoir of his family's life there titled ''U-Bet: A Greenhorn in Old Montana'' (1934; reprinted in 1990) which was reviewed in the ''[[New York Times]]'' as \"dramatic and colorful.\"\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.smokstak.com/gallery/showimage.php?i=3089&c=member&imageuser=3246 Undated photograph of Ubet Hotel]\n*[http://tokencatalog.com/token_record_forms.php?action=DisplayTokenRecord&td_id=337134&inventory_id=312114&attribution_id=344254 Photograph of a [[token coin]] issued by Barrows circa 1886]\n*[http://www.worldcat.org/title/u-bet-a-greenhorn-in-old-montana/oclc/20561134&referer=brief_results WorldCat listing for ''U-Bet: A Greenhorn in Old Montana]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barrows, Augustus}}\n[[Category:1838 births]]\n[[Category:1885 deaths]]\n[[Category:American hoteliers]]\n[[Category:American loggers]]\n[[Category:American cattlemen]]\n[[Category:American city founders]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Montana]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Members of the Wisconsin State Assembly]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Wisconsin State Assembly]]\n[[Category:People from Olean, New York]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Chippewa Falls, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:People from Judith Basin County, Montana]]\n[[Category:People from Olmsted County, Minnesota]]\n[[Category:People of Minnesota in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Saloonkeepers]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin Democrats]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin Greenbacks]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Randolph, New York]]\n", "text_old": "'''Augustus R. Barrows''' (also known as '''A. R. Barrows''') (July 30, 1838 \u2013 December 20, 1885) was an American [[lumberman]] from [[Chippewa Falls, Wisconsin|Chippewa Falls]], [[Wisconsin]] who spent one term as an [[Independent (politics)|independent]] [[Greenback Party|Greenbacker]] member of the [[Wisconsin State Assembly]] from [[Chippewa County, Wisconsin|Chippewa County]], serving as the [[Speaker of the Wisconsin State Assembly]] even though his party held only 13 of 100 seats therein.<ref>[http://legis.state.wi.us/LRB/pubs/ib/99ib1.pdf Cannon, A. Peter, ed. ''Members of the Wisconsin Legislature: 1848\u20131999''. State of Wisconsin Legislative Reference Bureau Informational Bulletin 99-1, September 1999; p. 26.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061209014416/http://legis.state.wi.us/LRB/pubs/ib/99ib1.pdf |date=2006-12-09 }}</ref> He later moved to [[Montana]], where he became a rancher, and ran a saloon-hotel, a [[general store]], and a [[sawmill]].\n\n== Background ==\nBarrows was born in [[Olean, New York]] on July 30, 1838; he studied at an academy (later renamed [[Chamberlain Institute]]) in [[Randolph, New York]], where his father was a pioneering lumberman. Augustus assisted his father in his business until on one of their trips to Cincinnati on a [[raft]], his father lost a leg in an accident. He closed out his business in New York and moved with his family to [[Pleasant Grove, Minnesota]] in 1855, and went into farming. Augustus, who had accompanied his family to their new home, \"followed various pursuits\" for a while. He married Alice B. Duncan in Pleasant Grove on November 16, 1862. \n\nBarrows enlisted as a private in the [[11th Minnesota Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] during the [[American Civil War]] and was mustered out as a [[lieutenant]] on June 30, 1865. On mustering out, he returned to Wisconsin, settling in [[Chippewa County, Wisconsin|Chippewa County]].\n\n==Public office == \nBarrows was elected County [[Treasurer]] of Chippewa County in 1869 to fill a vacancy, and re-elected for a full term in 1870; and served one term as [[mayor]] of Chippewa Falls.<ref name=\"Death Notice\">{{cite news|title=Wisconsin News: A. R. Barrows |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4817331/augustus_barrows_18381885/|newspaper=The Weekly Wisconsin|date=December 26, 1885|page=8|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = April 3, 2016}} {{Open access}}</ref> In 1872, he ran for the Assembly as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], losing to incumbent [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Albert Pound]] (who was also a lumberman from Chippewa Falls), with 676 votes to Pound's 1205. In 1876, he ran for the [[Wisconsin State Senate]]'s [[Wisconsin Senate, District 11|Eleventh District]] (again as a Democrat), losing to incumbent Republican [[Thomas Scott (Wisconsin politician)|Thomas Scott]] with 3,700 votes to Scott's 3,925.\n\nHe became a vigorous adherent of the [[Greenback Party|Greenback movement]], becoming known as \"one of its ablest and most logical advocates in the state\". In 1877, he ran for Chippewa County's sole Assembly seat as an independent Greenback, unseating Democratic incumbent [[Louis Vincent]], who polled only 496 votes to 886 votes for Barrows and 555 for Republican O. R. Dahl. He was chosen as [[speaker (politics)|speaker]] on January 9, 1878, because the Assembly now consisted of 45 Republicans, 41 Democrats, 13 Greenbacks and a [[Sewer Socialists|socialist]]: thus, the Greenbacks and socialist had leverage as tie-breakers, since the two major parties held mere pluralities.<ref>[http://digital.library.wisc.edu/1711.dl/WI.WIBlueBk1878 Bashford, R. M., ed. ''The legislative manual of the state of Wisconsin: comprising the constitutions of the United States and of the state of Wisconsin, Jefferson's manual, forms and laws for the regulation of business; also, lists and tables for reference, etc.'' Seventeenth Annual Edition. Madison: David Atwood, Printer and Stereotyper, 1878; pp. 391, 392, 457, 465-466, 486.]</ref> \n\nIn 1879, rather than run for re-election, he ran for [[United States House of Representatives|Congress]] under a [[electoral fusion|fusion]] [[ticket (election)|ticket]] as a Greenback/Democrat in the [[Wisconsin's 8th congressional district|Eighth District]], losing with 11,421 votes to 12,795 for Republican incumbent [[Thaddeus C. Pound]] (brother and partner of Albert Pound). He was succeeded in the Assembly by Republican former Assemblyman [[Hector McRae]].\n\n== Moving to Montana ==\nAfter losing the Congressional election, Barrows (who had suffered financial reverses in the [[real estate]] which constituted most of his wealth) organized a group of colonists who arrived in [[Martinsdale, Montana]] (a [[train stop]] on the main line of the [[Chicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul and Pacific Railroad|Milwaukee Road]]), in June 1879. He brought a herd of [[purebred#Purebred livestock|blooded]] [[cattle]] with him, and went into [[stockraising]], which he pursued for the rest of his life. Soon after his arrival there, he and [[Edward P. Allis]] of [[Milwaukee]] partnered to build a large sawmill, and began the manufacture of lumber at [[Sawmill Gulch, Montana|Sawmill Gulch]] in what was then [[Meagher County, Montana]]. He [[Homestead Act|homesteaded]] 160 acres in a place he called [[Ubet, Montana|\"Ubet\", also known as \"U-Bet\" or \"U-bet\"]] in what was then [[Fergus County, Montana|Fergus County]]. He built a [[stage stop]] hotel, [[Western saloon|saloon]] and [[general store]] on the [[stagecoach]] route, and moved there himself in 1881, becoming (with his family) among the first permanent white settlers of the [[Judith Basin County, Montana|Judith Basin]].\n\nHe died on December 20, 1885 in Ubet,<ref name=\"Death Notice\"/> and was buried back in Chippewa Falls in a [[Freemasonry|Masonic ceremony]] (he was a [[Knights Templar (Freemasonry)|Masonic Knight Templar]]). He left Alice with a family of young children, but she continued to operate the businesses with the aid of her children, eventually increasing the original homestead to an estate of 2,000 acres. The Barrows were the parents of four children: John R.; Mary, who died at two years of age; Olive; and Clarence H.<ref>''Progressive Men of Montana'' Chicago: A. W. Bowen & Co. [n.d.]; vol. 2, pp. 993-994</ref> John, who became a lawyer in [[San Diego, California]], later wrote a memoir of his family's life there titled ''U-Bet: A Greenhorn in Old Montana'' (1934; reprinted in 1990) which was reviewed in the ''[[New York Times]]'' as \"dramatic and colorful.\"\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.smokstak.com/gallery/showimage.php?i=3089&c=member&imageuser=3246 Undated photograph of Ubet Hotel]\n*[http://tokencatalog.com/token_record_forms.php?action=DisplayTokenRecord&td_id=337134&inventory_id=312114&attribution_id=344254 Photograph of a [[token coin]] issued by Barrows circa 1886]\n*[http://www.worldcat.org/title/u-bet-a-greenhorn-in-old-montana/oclc/20561134&referer=brief_results WorldCat listing for ''U-Bet: A Greenhorn in Old Montana]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barrows, Augustus}}\n[[Category:1838 births]]\n[[Category:1885 deaths]]\n[[Category:American hoteliers]]\n[[Category:American loggers]]\n[[Category:American cattlemen]]\n[[Category:American city founders]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Montana]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Members of the Wisconsin State Assembly]]\n[[Category:People from Olean, New York]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Chippewa Falls, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:People from Judith Basin County, Montana]]\n[[Category:People from Olmsted County, Minnesota]]\n[[Category:People of Minnesota in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Saloonkeepers]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin Democrats]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin Greenbacks]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Randolph, New York]]\n", "name_user": "Asdasdasdff", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Augustus_Barrows"}
{"title_page": "Ellen Burstyn", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Ellen Burstyn\n| image                     = Ellen Burstyn at the 2009 Tribeca Film Festival.jpg\n| alt                       =\n| caption                   = Burstyn at the May 1, 2009 [[Tribeca Film Festival]] premi\u00e8re of ''[[Poliwood (film)|Poliwood]]''\n| birth_name                = Edna Rae Gillooly\n| birth_date                = {{birth date and age|1932|12|7|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place               = [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], U.S.\n| nationality               = American\n| other_names               = Ellen McRae\n| education                 = [[Cass Technical High School]]\n| occupation                = Actress\n| years_active              = 1955\u2013present\n| spouse                    = {{marriage|William Alexander<br>|1950|1957|reason=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Paul Roberts<br>|1958|1961|reason=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|[[Neil Nephew|Neil Burstyn]]<br>|1964|1972|reason=divorced}}\n| children                  = 1\n| module2      = {{infobox officeholder |embed=yes\n| office       = 10th [[President (corporate title)|President]] of the [[Actors' Equity Association]]\n| term_start   = 1982\n| term_end     = 1985\n| predecessor  = [[Theodore Bikel]]\n| successor    = [[Colleen Dewhurst]]\n| website                   =\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Ellen Burstyn''' (born '''Edna Rae Gillooly'''; December 7, 1932) is an American actress. She is known for her work in dramas, and portrayal of troubled women. Burstyn is the recipient of various accolades, and is among the few performers to have won [[Triple Crown of Acting|Academy, Emmy and Tony Awards]].\n\nBorn in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]], Burstyn left school and worked as a dancer and model. She made her stage debut on Broadway in 1957 and soon started to make appearances in television shows. Stardom followed soon after with her acclaimed role in ''[[The Last Picture Show]]'' (1971), which earned her an Academy Award nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]. Her next appearance in ''[[The Exorcist (film)|The Exorcist]]'' (1973)'','' earned her a second Best Actress nomination. The film has remained popular and several publications have regarded it as [[List of films considered the best|one of the greatest horror films of all time]]. She also starred in [[Martin Scorsese]]'s ''[[Alice Doesn't Live Here Anymore]]'' (1974), which won her the Academy Award for Best Actress.\n\nShe appeared in numerous television movies and gained further recognition from her performances in ''[[Same Time, Next Year (film)|Same Time, Next Year]]'' (1978), which won her a [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Award'','']] and ''[[Resurrection (1980 film)|Resurrection]]'' (1980)'', [[How to Make an American Quilt]]'' (1995)'','' and ''[[Requiem for a Dream|Requiem For a Dream]]'' (2000)''.'' For playing a lonely drug-addicted woman in the last one of these, she was again nominated for an Academy Award and a [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Leading Role|Screen Actors Guild Award]]. In the 2010s, she made appearances in television series including the political dramas, ''[[Political Animals (miniseries)|Political Animals]]'' and ''[[House of Cards (American TV series)|House of Cards]]'', which have earned her Emmy Award nominations. Since 2000, she has been co-president of the [[Actors Studio]], a drama school in [[New York City]]. In 2013, she was inducted into the [[American Theatre Hall of Fame]] for her work on stage. \n\n==Early life==\nBurstyn was born Edna Rae Gillooly in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], the daughter of Correine Marie ([[married and maiden names|n\u00e9e]] Hamel) and John Austin Gillooly.<ref name=lessons>{{cite book| last=Burstyn| first=Ellen |title=Lessons in Becoming Myself| year=2007| publisher=Penguin| isbn=1-594-48268-3| page=4}}</ref> She has described her ancestry as \"Irish, French, [[Pennsylvania Dutch]], a little [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Canadian Indian]]\".<ref name=clark>Clark, John (October 19, 2009).[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/62762742.html?dids=62762742:62762742&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Oct+19%2C+2000&author=JOHN+CLARK&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Movies%3B+Independent+Minded%3B+Academy+Award+winner+Ellen+Burstyn%2C+a+'tough+cookie%2C'+is+back+with+two+gritty+films+and+a+TV+show.&pqatl=google Movies; Independent Minded; Academy Award Winner Ellen Burstyn, \"A 'Tough Cookie', Is Back with Two Gritty Films and a TV Show\"]([[Abstract (summary)|Abstract]]; {{subscription}} {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115195009/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/62762742.html?dids=62762742:62762742&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Oct+19%2C+2000&author=JOHN+CLARK&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Movies%3B+Independent+Minded%3B+Academy+Award+winner+Ellen+Burstyn%2C+a+'tough+cookie%2C'+is+back+with+two+gritty+films+and+a+TV+show.&pqatl=google |date=January 15, 2013 }} for full article). ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' (''via'' ''[[ProQuest|ProQuest Archiver]]''). Retrieved December 20, 2009.</ref><ref name=time>[[Staff writer]] (February 17, 1975). [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,912880,00.html \"Show Business: Gillooly Doesn't Live Here Anymore\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205080527/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,912880,00.html |date=December 5, 2008 }}. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''. Retrieved December 20, 2009.</ref> Burstyn has an older brother, Jack, and a younger brother, Steve.<ref name=lessons /><ref>Burstyn 2007, p. 14</ref> Her parents divorced when she was young, and she and her brothers lived with their mother and stepfather.<ref name=lessons />\n\nBurstyn attended [[Cass Technical High School]], a [[university-preparatory school]] which allowed students to choose a specific field of study. Burstyn majored in fashion illustration.<ref>Burstyn 2007, p. 36</ref> In high school, she was a cheerleader, a member of the student council, and president of her drama club. She dropped out of high school during her senior year after failing her classes.<ref>{{cite book|last=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Incorporated|first=|title=Britannica Book of the Year|year=1976|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|isbn=0-852-29311-9|page=[https://archive.org/details/britannicabookof1976ency/page/29 29]|url=https://archive.org/details/britannicabookof1976ency/page/29}}</ref><ref name=sweeney>{{cite news| title=Burstyn: Women must find own roles in movies| last=Sweeney| first=Louise| date=November 23, 1980| work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]| page=N2}}</ref> Soon afterwards, Burstyn worked as a dancer, and then a model until the age of 23.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Staff|first=Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/nov/05/guardianinterviewsatbfisouthbank|title=Ellen Burstyn|date=2000-11-05|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430200830/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/nov/05/guardianinterviewsatbfisouthbank|archive-date=April 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She later relocated to [[Dallas]], where she continued modeling and worked in other fashion jobs before moving to New York City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/interview-ellen-burstyn-on-inside-the-actors-studio.html|title=Ellen Burstyn Talks Her Dogs, Cosmology, and Co-hosting Inside the Actors Studio|last=Seitz|first=Matt Zoller|date=2019-12-19|website=Vulture|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302215605/https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/interview-ellen-burstyn-on-inside-the-actors-studio.html|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1955 to 1956, Burstyn appeared as an \"away we go\" dancing girl on ''[[The Jackie Gleason Show]]'' under the name Erica Dean.<ref name=bio>[http://www.biography.com/people/ellen-burstyn-9542388 \"Ellen Burstyn Biography,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150428010734/http://www.biography.com/people/ellen-burstyn-9542388 |date=April 28, 2015 }} Biography.com. Retrieved April 23, 2015.</ref> Burstyn then decided to become an actress and chose the name \"Ellen McRae\" as her professional name; she later changed her surname after her 1964 marriage to Neil Burstyn.<ref name=glover>{{cite news| url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=UTAqAAAAIBAJ&sjid=w0YEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6972,407534| title=Ellen Burstyn wants to be director| last=Glover| first=William| date=May 1, 1975| work=[[The Daily News (Kentucky)|Park City Daily News]]| page=28| accessdate=January 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===1958\u20131970: Early work===\nBurstyn debuted on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in 1957 and joined [[Lee Strasberg]]'s [[Actors Studio|The Actors Studio]]<!--n.b. there is no possessive in the studio's name--> in New York City in 1967. In 1975, she won a [[Tony Award]] for [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play|Best Performance by a Leading Actress in a Play]] for her performance in the comedy ''[[Same Time, Next Year (play)|Same Time, Next Year]],'' a role in which she would reprise in a [[Same Time, Next Year (film)|film adaptation in 1978]]. Starting in the late 1950s, and throughout the 1960s, Burstyn frequently played guest roles on a number of [[Prime time|primetime]] television shows, including ''[[Dr. Kildare (TV series)|Dr. Kildare]]'', ''[[77 Sunset Strip]]'', ''[[Ben Casey]]'', ''[[Gunsmoke]]'', ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'', ''[[Wagon Train]]'', ''[[The Big Valley]]'', and ''[[The Virginian (TV series)|The Virginian]]''. During 1964\u20131965, she had a recurring role as Dr. Kate Bartok on the [[National Broadcasting Company|NBC]] [[daytime television]] [[soap opera]] ''[[The Doctors (1963 TV series)|The Doctors]]''. In 1967\u20131968, she co-starred as Julie Parsons opposite [[Dale Robertson]] in the [[American Broadcasting Company (ABC)|ABC]] [[Westerns on television|Western]] ''[[The Iron Horse (TV series)|The Iron Horse]]''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=TrIspiOaqboC&pg=PA79#v=onepage Marill, Alvin H. ''Television Westerns: Six Decades of Sagebrush Sheriffs, Scalawags, and Sidewinders.''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125170936/https://books.google.com/books?id=TrIspiOaqboC&pg=PA79#v=onepage |date=November 25, 2015 }} Scarecrow Press, 2011, p. 79-80. {{ISBN|978-0-8108-8132-7}}.</ref> She was credited as Ellen McRae until 1967, when she and her then-husband Neil Nephew both changed their surname to Burstyn, and she began to be credited as Ellen Burstyn.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=SJKsBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA61#v=onepage Dern, Bruce, et al. ''Bruce Dern: A Memoir.''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125053443/https://books.google.com/books?id=SJKsBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA61#v=onepage |date=November 25, 2015 }} Univ. Press of Kentucky, 2014, p. 61. {{ISBN|978-0-470-10637-2}}.</ref>\n\n===1971\u20131981: Film breakthrough===\nAfter a number of small film roles, Burstyn gained recognition after starring in the 1971's ''[[The Last Picture Show]],'' a coming of age story, directed by [[Peter Bogdanovich]] and adapted from a semi-autobiographical 1966 novel by [[Larry McMurtry]]. The film earned critical acclaim for its nostalgia and visual style that is reminiscent of 1951, the year in which the plot takes place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-last-picture-show-1971|title=The Last Picture Show movie review (1971) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Ebert|first=Roger|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212015438/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-last-picture-show-1971|archive-date=December 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The film was nominated for eight [[Academy Awards]], including [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Actress in a Supporting Role]] for Burstyn and for co-star [[Cloris Leachman]]. Leachman won the award.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1998, the film was selected for preservation in the United States [[National Film Registry]], being deemed \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/loc/lcib/9812/film.html|title=Hooray for Hollywood (December 1998) - Library of Congress Information Bulletin|website=www.loc.gov|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112051533/http://www.loc.gov/loc/lcib/9812/film.html|archive-date=January 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> She next appeared in the drama [[The King of Marvin Gardens|''The King of Marvin Gardens'']] in 1972, with [[Jack Nicholson]], [[Bruce Dern]], and [[Scatman Crothers]]. A story about a daydreamer who convinces his brother to help fund one a get-rich-quick scheme, the film was well received by critics.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Last Picture Show (1971)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/last_picture_show|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105073617/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/last_picture_show|archive-date=January 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Linda Blair and Ellen Burstyn in The Exorcist.jpg|alt=Burstyn and Blair in The Exorcist (1973)|thumb|228x228px|Burstyn and Blair in ''The Exorcist'' (1973).]]\nIn 1972, Burstyn was keen on playing the lead role as Chris MacNeil in the supernatural horror, ''[[The Exorcist (film)|The Exorcist]]'' (1973). The film studio were initially reluctant to cast her, but when no other actors were put forward, Burstyn was secured the part. Her co-stars were [[Max von Sydow]], [[Lee J. Cobb]], [[Kitty Winn]], [[Jack MacGowran]], [[Jason Miller (playwright)|Jason Miller]] and [[Linda Blair]]. ''The Exorcist'' had a production budget of $12 million and its [[principal photography]] was held in various parts of New York City. Filming proved to be challenging for the entire cast, as it took \"six day weeks, twelve hour days for nine months\" to film and director William Friedkin would use a [[Theatrical property|prop gun]] to get genuine shocked reactions.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Bramesco|first=Charles|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/apr/24/william-friedkin-interview-exorcist-director-you-dont-know-a-damn-thing-and-neither-do-i|title=William Friedkin: 'You don\u2019t know a damn thing, and neither do I'|date=2018-04-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301141310/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/apr/24/william-friedkin-interview-exorcist-director-you-dont-know-a-damn-thing-and-neither-do-i|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Burstyn also injured her [[coccyx]], which led to permanent injury to her spine.<ref>[http://blog.koldcast.tv/2011/koldcast-news/10-creepy-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-exorcist/ 10 Creepy Things You Didn't Know About The Exorcist - The Sixth Wall] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121102305/http://blog.koldcast.tv/2011/koldcast-news/10-creepy-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-exorcist/ |date=January 21, 2013 }}. Blog.koldcast.tv (May 6, 2014). Retrieved 2014-06-05.</ref> Film critic [[Roger Ebert]] praised Burstyn for capturing her character's \"frustration\" during her daughter's possession by an evil spirit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-exorcist-1973|title=The Exorcist movie review & film summary (1973) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Ebert|first=Roger|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102153840/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-exorcist-1973|archive-date=November 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Against expectations, ''The Exorcist'' was a commercial success at the theaters. Adjusted for inflation, the film is the ninth [[List of highest-grossing films in the United States and Canada#Adjusted%20for%20ticket-price%20inflation|highest-grossing film of all time in the U.S. and Canada]] and the top-grossing R-rated film of all time. The film won two Academy Awards\u2014[[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]] and [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound Mixing]]\u2014and gained Burstyn a [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] nomination.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.strangemag.com/exorcistpage1.html|title=Part I - The Haunted Boy: the Inspiration for the Exorcist|website=www.strangemag.com|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003052203/http://www.strangemag.com/exorcistpage1.html|archive-date=October 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/16331/The-Exorcist/awards|title=The Exorcist|last=|first=|date=2012-10-22|website=The New York Times|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022111432/http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/16331/The-Exorcist/awards|archive-date=2012-10-22|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n\nBurstyn followed up with a small role in the comedy-drama, ''[[Harry and Tonto]]'' in 1974. Her next major role was in [[Martin Scorsese]]'s ''[[Alice Doesn't Live Here Anymore]]'' (1975) where she played a widowed woman, raising a son and yearning to start a new life for herself as a singer. Drawn to the script, Burstyn selected then-newcomer Scorsese as director and recalled the collaboration as \"one of the best experiences I've ever had\".<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Lee|first=Benjamin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/apr/26/ellen-burstyn-women-on-screen-were-prostitutes-or-victims-i-wanted-to-embody-a-hero|title=Ellen Burstyn: 'Women on screen were prostitutes or victims \u2013 I wanted to embody a hero'|date=2018-04-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311043952/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/apr/26/ellen-burstyn-women-on-screen-were-prostitutes-or-victims-i-wanted-to-embody-a-hero|archive-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Vincent Canby]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote, \"Burstyn never misses the eccentric beat that distinguishes it\u2014that makes Alice such a hugely appealing character who is both banal and very rare.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Canby|first=Vincent|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/02/02/archives/flim-view-terrific-toughtakling-alice.html|title=Film View|date=1975-02-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-01|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301192736/https://www.nytimes.com/1975/02/02/archives/flim-view-terrific-toughtakling-alice.html|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The film earned her Academy Award for Best Actress.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|last=Modderno|first=Craig|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/10/16/movies/shirley-maclaines-words-of-wisdom.html|title=Shirley MacLaine's Words of Wisdom|date=2005-10-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928121524/https://www.nytimes.com/2005/10/16/movies/shirley-maclaines-words-of-wisdom.html|archive-date=September 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1975, she became a graduate of the first group of participants in the [[American Film Institute]] [[Directing Workshop for Women]]. In 1977, she was a member of the jury at the [[27th Berlin International Film Festival]] which was held in Berlin.<ref name=\"Berlinale 1977\">{{cite web|url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1977/04_jury_1977/04_Jury_1977.html|title=Berlinale 1977: Juries|work=berlinale.de|accessdate=July 19, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418172522/https://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1977/04_jury_1977/04_Jury_1977.html|archive-date=April 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nShe had supporting roles in ''[[Providence (1977 film)|Providence]] and [[A Dream of Passion]]'' in 1977 and 1978, respectively. Although these were independent dramas and not widely seen, the latter was nominated for a [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Film]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/film/dream-passion|title=Dream of Passion, A|website=www.goldenglobes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> Also in 1978, Burstyn starred in ''[[Same Time, Next Year (film)|Same Time, Next Year]]'' opposite [[Alan Alda]]'','' a romantic-comedy about two people, married to others, who meet for a romantic tryst once a year for two decades. The film is based on a [[Same Time, Next Year (play)|1975 play of the same title]] by Bernard Slade. Upon its release on November 22, the film garnered mixed reviews, with [[Janet Maslin]] of ''The New York Times'' stating, \"Slade's screenplay isn't often funny, and it's full of momentous events that can't be laughed away\", but praises Burstyn for giving the role \"warmth and grace\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Maslin|first=Janet|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1978/11/22/archives/film-same-timetrysting-annually.html|title=Film: 'Same Time':Trysting Annually|date=1978-11-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-01|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301192734/https://www.nytimes.com/1978/11/22/archives/film-same-timetrysting-annually.html|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Same Time, Next Year'' was nominated for Academy Awards in [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]], [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]], [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Song]], and Best Actress for Burstyn.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1979|title=The 51st Academy Awards {{!}} 1979|website=Oscars.org {{!}} Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> In the Golden Globes Awards, she won [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress in a Motion Picture]], and the film received two other nominations\u2014[[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor]] for Alda and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/film/same-time-next-year|title=Same Time, Next Year|website=www.goldenglobes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n\nBurstyn hosted NBC's ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', a late-night [[sketch comedy]] and [[variety show]], in December 1980.<ref name=\"preston\">{{cite news|last=Preston|first=Marilynn|title=Tempo: No panic, yet, from new 'Saturday Night' boss|date=December 9, 1980|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|page=B12}}</ref> That year, Burstyn starred in the drama ''[[Resurrection (1980 film)|Resurrection]]'', a story about a woman who possesses strange powers after a surviving a automobile crash. She was nominated again for Best Actress in the Academy Awards and Best Actress in the Golden Globes.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1981|title=The 53rd Academy Awards {{!}} 1981|website=Oscars.org {{!}} Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203143244/https://oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1981|archive-date=February 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/film/resurrection|title=Resurrection|website=www.goldenglobes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215165807/http://www.goldenglobes.com/film/resurrection|archive-date=February 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1981, she starred in the biographical television movie ''The People vs. Jean Harris'' (1981), based on the real life murder of [[Herman Tarnower]], a well-known [[cardiologist]] and [[author]] of the best-selling book ''[[Scarsdale medical diet|The Complete Scarsdale Medical Diet]]''. Burstyn was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Miniseries or Television Film|Best Actress in a Miniseries or Television Film]] in the Golden Globes for her portrayal of the murderer, [[Jean Harris]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/tv-show/people-vs-jean-harris|title=People Vs. Jean Harris, The|website=www.goldenglobes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> She was also nominated for an [[Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress \u2013 Miniseries or a Movie|Outstanding Actress in a Mini-Series or Movie]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/people-vs-jean-harris|title=People vs. Jean Harris|website=Television Academy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616145923/http://www.emmys.com/shows/people-vs-jean-harris|archive-date=June 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1981, Burstyn recorded \"The Ballad of the Nazi Soldier's Wife\" for [[Ben Bagley]]'s album ''[[Kurt Weill]] Revisited, Vol. 2''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kritzerland.com/weill2.htm|title=Ben Bagley's KURT WEILL REVISITED, VOL. 2|website=www.kritzerland.com|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>  \n\n=== 1985\u20132005: Television films and continued success ===\nBurstyn followed up the mid-1980s with a number of acting roles in ''[[The Ambassador (1984 American film)|The Ambassador]]'' (1984), [[Surviving: A Family in Crisis|''Surviving'']] (1985), ''[[Twice in a Lifetime (film)|Twice in a Lifetime]]'' (1985), ''Into Thin Air'' (1985), ''[[Act of Vengeance]]'' (1986), ''Something in Common'' (1986) and [[Pack of Lies|play adaptation]], ''Pack of Lies'' (1987). For ''[[Twice in a Lifetime (film)|Twice in a Lifetime]],'' she portrayed Kate, the wife that [[Gene Hackman]]'s character left for when he fell in love with another woman. ''Pack of Lies'' was nominated for three Primetime Emmy Awards, including another for Burstyn as Outstanding Actress in a Mini-Series or Movie.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/pack-lies-hallmark-hall-fame|title=Pack of Lies Hallmark Hall of Fame|website=Television Academy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191019220712/https://www.emmys.com/shows/pack-lies-hallmark-hall-fame|archive-date=October 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, Burstyn starred in a [[ABC Studios|ABC]] television [[situation comedy|sitcom]], ''[[The Ellen Burstyn Show]],'' with co-stars [[Megan Mullally]] as her daughter and [[Elaine Stritch]] as her mother. Created by [[David Frankel]], it ran only for one season. In 1987, she appeared in ''[[Dear America: Letters Home from Vietnam]]'' and ''Look Away'', both were television movies. In 1988, she participated as a member of the jury for the [[38th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlinale 1988\">{{cite web|url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1988/04_jury_1988/04_Jury_1988.html|title=Berlinale: 1988 Juries|work=berlinale.de|accessdate=March 4, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418172438/https://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1988/04_jury_1988/04_Jury_1988.html|archive-date=April 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A variety of acting performances followed suit, including in the dramas [[Hanna's War|''Hanna's War'']] (1987), ''[[When You Remember Me]]'' (1990), ''[[Dying Young]]'' (1991) and ''[[Grand Isle (film)|Grand Isle]]'' (1991). In 1990, Burstyn won the [[Sarah Siddons Award]] for her work in [[Theatre in Chicago|Chicago theatre]].<ref name=\"siddons\">{{cite web| title=The Sarah Siddons Society Awardees| url=http://www.sarahsiddonssociety.org/awardees/| publisher=Sarah Siddons Society| accessdate=December 4, 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224055722/http://sarahsiddonssociety.org/awardees/| archive-date=December 24, 2016| url-status=dead}}</ref> In addition to television movies, Burstyn appeared in ''[[When a Man Loves a Woman (film)|When a Man Loves a Woman]]'' (1994) with co-stars [[Andy Garc\u00eda|Andy Garcia]] and [[Meg Ryan]].\n\nIn 1995, she portrayed Judith in the comedy-drama ''[[Roommates (1995 film)|Roommates]]'' (1995). The film received negative reviews and was a commercial failure, but it did receive a nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling|Best Makeup]] in the Academy Awards.<ref>{{Citation|title=Roommates (1995)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/roommates|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171130154319/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/roommates/|archive-date=November 30, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1996|title=The 68th Academy Awards {{!}} 1996|website=Oscars.org {{!}} Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191002000121/https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1996|archive-date=October 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Also that year, Burstyn appeared in [[How to Make an American Quilt|''How to Make an American Quilt'']] (1995), based on the [[How to Make an American Quilt (novel)|1991 novel of the same name]] by [[Whitney Otto]], which tells the stories of several generations of women who are part of the same [[quilting]] circle. Despite a mixed critical response, the cast received a nomination for [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]].<ref>{{Citation|title=How to Make an American Quilt (1995)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/how_to_make_an_american_quilt|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920121856/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/how_to_make_an_american_quilt|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/2nd-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards|title=The 2nd Annual Screen Actors Guild Awards {{!}} Screen Actors Guild Awards|website=www.sagawards.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325024748/https://www.sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/2nd-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards|archive-date=March 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1998, Burstyn appeared in ''[[Playing by Heart|Playing By Heart]]'', a story of eleven ordinary people in Los Angeles who are connected in different ways. Some critics such as Roger Ebert viewed the film positively despite the lackluster performance at the box office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/playing-by-heart-1999|title=Playing By Heart movie review (1999) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Ebert|first=Roger|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602021057/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/playing-by-heart-1999|archive-date=June 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl3345516033/weekend/|title=Playing by Heart|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n[[File:OIFF 2015-07-17 184409 - Darren Aronofsky.jpg|alt=Director Darren Aronofsky has worked with Burstyn twice.|left|thumb|213x213px|Director Darren Aronofsky has worked with Burstyn twice.]]\nBurstyn next found supporting roles in ''[[The Spitfire Grill]]'' (1996), about a woman starting a new life after being released from prison, and ''[[Deceiver (film)|Deceiver]]'' (1997), a murder crime drama. Although not box office hits, each film garnered mixed to positive responses, according to [[Rotten Tomatoes]], a film review aggregator.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Spitfire Grill (1996)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/spitfire_grill|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171129082500/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/spitfire_grill/|archive-date=November 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Deceiver (1998)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/deceiver|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191228113121/https://rottentomatoes.com/m/deceiver|archive-date=December 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Next, she appeared in [[James Gray (director)|James Gray]]'s [[The Yards|''The Yards'']] (2000) alongside a principal cast of [[Mark Wahlberg]], [[Joaquin Phoenix]], [[Charlize Theron]], [[Faye Dunaway]] and [[James Caan]]. The crime drama was unpopular and a commercial failure, earning less than $1 million worldwide from a budget of $24 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1148880385/weekend/|title=The Yards|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=2020-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302180604/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1148880385/weekend/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Staff|first=Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/nov/05/guardianinterviewsatbfisouthbank1|title=Ellen Burstyn - part two|date=2000-11-05|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430200847/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/nov/05/guardianinterviewsatbfisouthbank1|archive-date=April 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, director [[Darren Aronofsky]] offered Burstyn the role of Sara Goldfarb in ''[[Requiem for a Dream]]'' (2000). She initially rejected the part, objecting to the depressive nature of the story. However, Burstyn changed her mind after seeing Aronofsky's previous work.<ref name=\":1\" /> The film is based on the [[Requiem for a Dream (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Hubert Selby Jr.|Hubert Selby Jr]], which tells the story of four New Yorkers whose lives are affected by drug [[Substance dependence|addictions]]. For the role, Burstyn had to wear [[Fatsuit|fat suits]], lose weight and speak to women in Brooklyn \"to get their speech patterns and outlook on life - and how narrow that is.\" She added, \"their life is about getting enough money to put food on the table to feed their children, and that's it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2001/01/16/ellen_bursytn_requiemforadream_160101_interview.shtml|title=BBC - Films - interview - Ellen Burstyn|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824003906/http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2001/01/16/ellen_bursytn_requiemforadream_160101_interview.shtml|archive-date=August 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0101/14/sm.12.html|title=CNN Transcript - Sunday Morning News: Ellen Burstyn Discusses 'Requiem for a Dream' - January 14, 2001|website=edition.cnn.com|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110129232002/http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0101/14/sm.12.html|archive-date=January 29, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Burstyn and her fellow co-stars, [[Jennifer Connelly]], [[Jared Leto]], and [[Marlon Wayans]], found the filming schedule of forty days challenging and intense.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/uncategorized/dreams-fulfilled-a-darren-aronofsky-interview/|title=DREAMS FULFILLED: A DARREN ARONOFSKY INTERVIEW {{!}} Film Threat|date=2000-11-10|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824182549/https://filmthreat.com/uncategorized/dreams-fulfilled-a-darren-aronofsky-interview/|archive-date=August 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Requiem for a Dream'' premiered at the [[2000 Cannes Film Festival]] and was released to theaters on October 6, 2000. The film was well received and praised for its visual style and depiction of drug abuse. [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' writes, \"Burstyn gives an award-caliber performance that is as raw and riveting as the movie that contains it\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/requiem-for-a-dream-118844/|title=Requiem for a Dream|last=Travers|first=Peter|last2=Travers|first2=Peter|date=2000-12-11|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302144123/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/requiem-for-a-dream-118844/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Burstyn was nominated for Best Actress in the 2001 Academy Awards.<ref name=\"NYT2\">{{cite news|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=OSCAR FILMS/ACTORS: An Angry Man and an Underused Woman; Ellen Burstyn Enjoys Her Second Act|first=Rick|last=Lyman|date=March 4, 2001|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/04/movies/oscar-films-actors-angry-man-underused-woman-ellen-burstyn-enjoys-her-second-act.html|access-date=February 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314042144/http://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/04/movies/oscar-films-actors-angry-man-underused-woman-ellen-burstyn-enjoys-her-second-act.html|archive-date=March 14, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2000 to 2002, Burstyn starred in the [[CBS]] television series ''[[That's Life (2000 TV series)|That's Life]]''. The series, set in suburban [[New Jersey]], ran for two seasons. Burstyn appeared in several more films, including ''[[Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood (film)|Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood]]'' (2002), ''[[Brush with Fate]]'' (2003) and ''The Five People You Meet in Heaven'' (2004). Burstyn starred in the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production of Martin Tahse's ''Oldest Living Confederate Widow Tells All'', based upon [[Oldest Living Confederate Widow Tells All|the novel of the same title]] by [[Allan Gurganus]]. The show played 19 previews and officially opened November 17, 2003. Due to unfavorable reviews, all performances after the opening night were cancelled.<ref name=\"one\">{{cite news|last=Hernanzez|first=Ernio|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/82850-Oldest-Living-Confederate-Widow-Tells-No-More-Show-Closes-on-Broadway/I%3E-Tells-No-More;-Show-Closes-on-Broadway|title=Oldest Living Confederate Widow Tells No More; Show Closes on Broadway|date=November 18, 2003|work=[[Playbill]]|accessdate=December 4, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413155524/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/82850-Oldest-Living-Confederate-Widow-Tells-No-More-Show-Closes-on-Broadway/I%3E-Tells-No-More%3B-Show-Closes-on-Broadway|archivedate=April 13, 2014|df=mdy}}</ref>\n\n=== 2006\u20132015 ===\n[[File:EllenBurstyn07TIFF.jpg|thumb|Burstyn at the [[2007 Toronto International Film Festival]].|alt=Burstyn at the 2007 Toronto International Film Festival.|220x220px]]She provided a supporting role as the mother of two sons in the 2006 romantic drama ''[[The Elephant King]]''. The film originally premiered at the [[Tribeca Film Festival#2006 Tribeca Film Festival|2006 Tribeca Film Festival]], and opened in U.S. theaters October 2008.<ref name=\"goldstein\">{{cite web| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2008/10/27/us-elephant-idUSTRE49Q2BK20081027| title=Little \"Elephant\" roars at box office| last=Goldstein| first=Gregg| date=October 27, 2008| agency=[[Reuters]]| accessdate=January 16, 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413143726/http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/10/27/us-elephant-idUSTRE49Q2BK20081027| archive-date=April 13, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2006, she starred as an [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal]] bishop in the [[NBC]] comedy-drama series ''[[The Book of Daniel (TV series)|The Book of Daniel]]''. The series, which also starred [[Aidan Quinn]] as a drug-addicted Episcopal priest married to an alcoholic wife, was met with controversy from religious and spiritual leaders due to its unconventional portrayals of religious figures.<ref name=\"yonke\">{{cite news| url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=y3BPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YQQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6320,3337576| title='Book of Daniel' opens to controversy| last=Yonke| first=David| date=January 14, 2006| work=[[The Blade (Toledo)|The Blade]] (newspaper)| location=Toledo, Ohio| page=3| accessdate=January 15, 2013}}</ref> Conservative groups including [[American Family Association]] and [[Focus on the Family]] urged supporters to complain to NBC affiliates that carried the show. Subsequently, NBC removed the series from its line-up after four episodes, but did not publicly give a reason for doing so.<ref name=\"camacho\">{{cite news| url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/nbc-drops-book-of-daniel-from-lineup-5847/| title=NBC Drops 'Book of Daniel' from Lineup| last=Camacho| first=Justin| date=January 25, 2006| work=The Christian Post| accessdate=January 16, 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413154552/http://www.christianpost.com/news/nbc-drops-book-of-daniel-from-lineup-5847/| archive-date=April 13, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref>\n \nIn 2006, Burstyn appeared in the epic drama ''[[The Fountain (film)|The Fountain]]'', her second collaboration with Darren Aronofsky. Portraying Dr. Lillian Guzetti, the film is about a scientist (played by [[Hugh Jackman]]) struggling with mortality and is seeking a medical breakthrough to save his wife ([[Rachel Weisz]]) from cancer. Budgeted at $35 million, the screenplay is a blend of [[Fantasy film|fantasy]], [[Historical drama|history]], [[spirituality]], and [[Science fiction film|science fiction]]. ''The Fountain'' premiered on November 22, 2006 to mixed reviews from critics and under-performed at the box office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt0414993/?ref_=bo_se_r_1|title=The Fountain|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=The Fountain (2006)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_fountain|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729221135/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_fountain/|archive-date=July 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Ruthe Stein of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' writes, \"The movie is overloaded with imagery. At times, it's stunning to look at, but gradually becomes too much\", but praises Burstyn for her character's \"impressive depth\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/A-toke-worthy-search-for-fountain-of-youth-2545658.php|title=A toke-worthy search for fountain of youth|last=Stein|first=Ruthe|date=2006-11-22|website=SFGate|access-date=2020-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302202000/https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/A-toke-worthy-search-for-fountain-of-youth-2545658.php|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Since its release, the film has gained a [[Cult film|cult following]] causing media to revisit the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/the-fountain-explained/|title=\u2018The Fountain\u2019 Has Nothing to Do with Time|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|date=2016-11-22|website=Collider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107234618/https://collider.com/the-fountain-explained/|archive-date=January 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\nIn 2006, she was nominated for an Emmy Award for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress \u2013 Miniseries or a Movie|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Mini-Series or Movie]] for the role of Former [[Herman Tarnower|Tarnower]] Steady in [[HBO]]'s ''[[Mrs. Harris]]'', another biopic about Jean Harris.<ref name=\"emmys\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2006/supporting-actress-movie-miniseries|title=Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie - 2006|publisher=emmys.com|accessdate=December 4, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206092827/http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2006/supporting-actress-movie-miniseries|archive-date=December 6, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Soon after the nominations were announced, questions were raised regarding the worthiness of the nomination due to her minor role in the film, consisting of 14 seconds of screen time and 38 words of dialogue. The nominating committee were accused of approving a \"familiar\" name without actually seeing their performance.<ref name=\"bianco\">{{cite news|last=Bianco|first=Robert|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/televisionawards/emmys/2006-08-24-emmy-main_x.htm|title=Emmys need a fast fix|date=August 27, 2006|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=December 4, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628231004/http://www.usatoday.com/life/television/televisionawards/emmys/2006-08-24-emmy-main_x.htm|archive-date=June 28, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]], administrator of the Emmy Awards, insisted it was a legitimate nomination.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.today.com/popculture/emmy-14-seconds-worth-work-wbna14253083|title=An Emmy for 14 seconds worth of work?|website=TODAY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605100135/https://www.today.com/popculture/emmy-14-seconds-worth-work-wbna14253083|archive-date=June 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Burstyn reacted, \"I thought it was fabulous. My next ambition is to get nominated for seven seconds, and ultimately, I want to be nominated for a picture in which I don't even appear\", adding, \"This doesn't have anything to do with me ... work it out yourself.\"<ref name=\"emmynod\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2006-11-03-burstyn_x.htm|title=Ellen Burstyn Sounds Off on Her Emmy Nod|date=November 3, 2006|work=USA Today|accessdate=December 4, 2013|agency=[[Associated Press]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090710075804/http://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2006-11-03-burstyn_x.htm|archive-date=July 10, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> Ultimately, [[Kelly Macdonald]], who starred in ''[[The Girl in the Cafe]]'', won the award.<ref name=\"scots\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/5292128.stm|title=Scots star wins Emmy for TV role|date=August 28, 2006|accessdate=April 13, 2013|publisher=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204101650/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/5292128.stm|archive-date=February 4, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2007, the Academy adjusted the eligibility criteria.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/03/16/AR2007031602142.html|title=Emmy Rules Change After Burstyn Nomination Flap|author=[[Lisa de Moraes]]|date=March 17, 2007|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 13, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026085000/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/03/16/AR2007031602142.html|archive-date=October 26, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nShe also appeared in the thriller ''[[The Wicker Man (2006 film)|The Wicker Man]]'' (2006) which was a commercial flop and negatively received by critics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt0450345/?ref_=bo_se_r_2|title=The Wicker Man|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=The Wicker Man (2006)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_wicker_man_2006|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103015421/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_wicker_man_2006/|archive-date=January 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A year later, Burstyn starred in ''[[The Stone Angel (film)|The Stone Angel]]'', based on the 1964 [[The Stone Angel|novel of the same name]] by [[Margaret Laurence]]. Like its predecessor, the film also received negative reviews, with [[Stephen Holden]] of ''The New York Times'' writing, \"a film of tightly assembled bits and pieces that don\u2019t fit comfortably together despite clever dashes of magical realism connecting past and present ... it leaves you frustrated by its failure to braid subplots and characters into a gripping narrative.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Holden|first=Stephen|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/11/movies/11ston.html|title=A Tenacious Matriarch Who Won\u2019t Go Quietly|date=2008-07-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302221419/https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/11/movies/11ston.html|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Ellen Burstyn 2009.jpg|alt=Burstyn at the 2009 Creative Arts Emmy Awards.|thumb|231x231px|Burstyn at the 2009 [[Creative Arts Emmy Award|Creative Arts Emmy Awards]].|left]]\nA succession of films including ''[[Lovely, Still]]'' (2008), ''[[The Loss of a Teardrop Diamond]]'' (2008) and ''[[The Mighty Macs]]'' (2011), were released in the late 2000s which found success to niche audiences. She then appeared in ''[[Main Street (2010 film)|Main Street]]'' (2010) and ''[[Another Happy Day]]'' (2011), small-scale features with mixed reviews. In addition to film roles, between 2007 and 2011, she had an occasional recurring role on the HBO television drama series ''[[Big Love]]'', playing the mother of [[polygamist]] wife Barbara Henrickson. Burstyn returned to the stage in March 2008, in the [[Off Broadway|off-Broadway]] production of [[Stephen Adly Guirgis]]'s ''The Little Flower of East Orange'', directed by [[Philip Seymour Hoffman]] in a co-production by [[LAByrinth Theater Company]] and [[The Public Theater]].<ref name=\"hernandez\">{{cite news|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/116511-The-Little-Flower-of-East-Orange-Starring-Ellen-Burstyn-Opens-Off-Broadway-April-6 |title=The Little Flower of East Orange, Starring Ellen Burstyn, Opens Off-Broadway April 6 |last=Hernandez |first=Ernio |date=April 6, 2008 |work=Playbill |accessdate=January 16, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105142841/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/116511-The-Little-Flower-of-East-Orange-Starring-Ellen-Burstyn-Opens-Off-Broadway-April-6 |archivedate=November 5, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref> In addition to her stage work, Burstyn portrayed former [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Barbara Bush]] in [[Oliver Stone]]'s biographical film ''[[W. (film)|W.]]'' in 2008.<ref name=\"walker-mitchell\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/good-bad-ugly/2009/01/22/1232471466530.html|title=Good, bad, ugly|last=Walker-Mitchell|first=Donna|date=January 23, 2009|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=December 4, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924200024/http://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/good-bad-ugly/2009/01/22/1232471466530.html|archive-date=September 24, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, she won a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress \u2013 Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series]] for her portrayal of the [[bipolar disorder|bipolar]] estranged mother of Detective [[Elliot Stabler]] on NBC's [[police procedural]] ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8253188.stm|title=Fey wins Emmy for TV Palin spoof|date=September 13, 2009|accessdate=December 4, 2013|publisher=[[BBC News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413145948/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8253188.stm|archive-date=April 13, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2012, she joined the cast of ''[[Political Animals (miniseries)|Political Animals]],'' a television series about the life of a divorced former [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]], serving as [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]]. ''Political Animals'' received generally favorable reviews from critics according to [[Metacritic]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Political Animals|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/political-animals|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824231528/http://www.metacritic.com/tv/political-animals|archive-date=August 24, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> At the 2013 Golden Globe Awards, the series was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Miniseries or Television Film|Best Miniseries or Motion Picture Made for Television]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/tv-show/political-animals|title=Political Animals|website=www.goldenglobes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219014959/http://www.goldenglobes.com/tv-show/political-animals|archive-date=December 19, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Burstyn won an Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Mini-Series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2013/outstanding-supporting-actress-in-a-miniseries-or-a-movie|title=Outstanding Supporting Actress In A Miniseries Or A Movie Nominees / Winners 2013|website=Television Academy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301180025/http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2013/outstanding-supporting-actress-in-a-miniseries-or-a-movie|archive-date=March 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nShe portrayed the grandmother of Lou (played by [[Mackenzie Foy]]) in ''[[Wish You Well (film)|Wish You Well]]'' (2013). A year later, Burstyn and Foy worked together again in [[Christopher Nolan]]'s epic science fiction [[Interstellar (film)|''Interstellar'']].<ref name=\"sneider\">{{cite web| url=http://www.thewrap.com/movies/column-post/twilights-mackenzie-foy-join-christopher-nolans-interstellar-103436| title=Ellen Burstyn, 'Twilight's Mackenzie Foy Join Christopher Nolan's 'Interstellar' (Exclusive)| last=Sneider| first=Jeff| date=July 15, 2015| work=[[Sharon Waxman|The Wrap]]| publisher=thewrap.com| accessdate=July 15, 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107101738/http://www.thewrap.com/movies/column-post/twilights-mackenzie-foy-join-christopher-nolans-interstellar-103436/| archive-date=November 7, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref> Set in a [[Dystopia|dystopian]] future where humanity is struggling to survive, the film follows a group of [[Astronaut|astronauts]] who travel through a [[wormhole]] in search of a new home for humanity. The film grossed over $677 million in the worldwide box office, making it the [[2014 in film|tenth-highest-grossing film of 2014]]. She made a guest appearance in five episodes of ''Louie'' in 2014, and starred in a thriller'', [[The Calling (2014 film)|The Calling]],'' the same year. Burstyn played Flemming, the daughter of [[Blake Lively]]'s immortal character, in the film ''[[The Age of Adaline]]'' (2015). Production started in March 2014, and the film was released in April 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fleming|first=Mike|title=Blake Lively, Ellen Burstyn Set To Star In 'The Age of Adaline'|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/10/blake-lively-ellen-burstyn-set-to-star-in-the-age-of-adaline/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=January 7, 2014|date=October 16, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131222062403/http://www.deadline.com/2013/10/blake-lively-ellen-burstyn-set-to-star-in-the-age-of-adaline/|archive-date=December 22, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016\u2013present ===\nIn 2016, she guest starred in five episodes of ''[[House of Cards (American TV series)|House of Cards]]'', a critically acclaimed political thriller. Burstyn was credited on a succession of low-budget films, including ''[[Custody (2016 film)|Custody]]'' (2016), ''[[The House of Tomorrow (2017 film)|The House of Tomorrow]]'' (2017), ''[[All I Wish]]'' (2017) and ''[[Nostalgia (2018 film)|Nostalgia]]'' (2018). Burstyn also starred in ''[[The Tale]]'', a mystery drama which premiered on HBO on May 26, 2018. Director [[Jennifer Fox (documentary filmmaker)|Jennifer Fox]] was praised for her direction and bringing the \"complex, haunting work\" to life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2018/01/23/sundance-jennifer-foxs-deeply-disturbing-the-tale-explores-the-maze-like-nature-of-memory/|title=Sundance: Jennifer Fox\u2019s Deeply Disturbing \u201cThe Tale\u201d Explores the Maze-Like Nature of Memory {{!}} The Village Voice|website=www.villagevoice.com|access-date=2020-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303214242/https://www.villagevoice.com/2018/01/23/sundance-jennifer-foxs-deeply-disturbing-the-tale-explores-the-maze-like-nature-of-memory/|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Burstyn served as an executive producer for Peter Livolsi's film, ''[[The House of Tomorrow (2017 film)|The House of Tomorrow]]'' (2017)'','' about her friend [[R. Buckminster Fuller]], in which she also stars in.<ref>[http://scienceandfilm.org/projects/514/house-of-tomorrow The House of Tomorrow] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915001704/http://scienceandfilm.org/projects/514/house-of-tomorrow |date=September 15, 2016 }} , Museum of the Moving Image (2018)</ref> As of 2014, Burstyn is working on directing her first feature film, ''Bathing Flo''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/aug/26/ellen-burstyn-direct-film-bathing-flo|title=Ellen Burstyn to direct her first feature-length film at 80|author=Ben Child|work=the Guardian|access-date=December 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826041653/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/aug/26/ellen-burstyn-direct-film-bathing-flo|archive-date=August 26, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2014/08/ellen-burstyn-directing-debut-bathing-flo-movie-824337/|title=Ellen Burstyn To Direct First Movie \u2014 'Bathing Flo' - Deadline|author=Mike Fleming Jr|work=Deadline|access-date=April 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160501123043/http://deadline.com/2014/08/ellen-burstyn-directing-debut-bathing-flo-movie-824337/|archive-date=May 1, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, Burstyn played Katherine in an acclaimed Australian production of [[Mois\u00e9s Kaufman]]'s play, [[33 Variations]] at Melbourne's Comedy Theatre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.limelightmagazine.com.au/reviews/33-variations-cameron-lukey-neil-gooding-productions/|title=\u2605\u2605\u2605\u2605\u00bd 33 Variations (Cameron Lukey & Neil Gooding Productions)|website=Limelight|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBurstyn married Bill Alexander in 1950 and divorced in 1957. The following year, she married Paul Roberts, with whom she [[adoption|adopted]] a son named Jefferson in 1961. The couple divorced that same year.<ref name=timeline>{{cite web| title=Timeline\u2014A Chronology of Key Events from Lessons in Becoming Myself| url=http://www.ellenburstyn.net/timeline.htm| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110307073245/http://www.ellenburstyn.net/timeline.htm| archivedate=March 7, 2011| publisher=archive.org| accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref> In 1964, she married actor [[Neil Nephew]], who later changed his name to Neil Burstyn. She described Neil Burstyn as \"charming and funny and bright and talented and eccentric\", but [[schizophrenia]] made him violent and he eventually left her.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oprah.com/spirit/ellen-burstyn-and-sheryl-crows-live-lessons/all|title=Becoming Yourself|work=Oprah.com|access-date=2020-03-07|language=en-us}}</ref> He attempted to reconcile but they divorced in 1972. In her autobiography, ''Lessons in Becoming Myself'', Burstyn revealed that he [[stalking|stalked]] her for six years after their divorce, and that he broke into her house and raped her. No charges were filed, as [[spousal rape]] was not yet a crime. He committed suicide in 1978.<ref>(December 1, 2006).[http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/article/burstyn%20feared%20death%20as%20abusive%20husband%20stalked%20her_1015128 Ellen Burstyn\u2014Burstyn Feared Death as Abusive Husband Stalked Her\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010185418/http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/article/burstyn%20feared%20death%20as%20abusive%20husband%20stalked%20her_1015128 |date=October 10, 2008 }}. ''[[contactmusic.com]]''. Retrieved December 20, 2009.</ref>\n\nBurstyn was raised [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], but now affiliates herself with all religious faiths. Her spiritual journey began with [[Sufism]]{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}. She explains: \"I am a spirit opening to the truth that lives in all of these religions... I always pray to Spirit, but sometimes, it's to the Goddess. Sometimes, it's to [[Jesus]]... Sometimes, I pray to [[Ganesha]] if I need an obstacle removed. [[Guan Yin]] is one of my favorite manifestations of the divine, the embodiment of compassion... So, I have Guan Yin with me all the time.\"<ref name=\"reiss\">{{cite web| title=Ellen Burstyn's True Face| url=http://www.beliefnet.com/Entertainment/Celebrities/Ellen-Burstyns-True-Face.aspx?p=1#| publisher=[[Beliefnet]]| year=2006| accessdate=December 4, 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140105035541/http://www.beliefnet.com/Entertainment/Celebrities/Ellen-Burstyns-True-Face.aspx?p=1| archive-date=January 5, 2014| url-status=live}}</ref> Burstyn has stated that in her late 30s she began to delve into the spiritual realm, coming under the tutelage of Sufi teacher Pir [[Vilayat Inayat Khan]]{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}; he gave her the spiritual name Hadiya,{{sfn|p=209}} which means \"she who is guided\" in [[Arabic]].\n\nDuring the 1970s, Burstyn was active in the movement to free convicted boxer [[Rubin Carter|Rubin \"Hurricane\" Carter]] from jail.<ref name=\"carter\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-02-20/news/mn-11377_1_carter-hurricane-seeking/16/AR2007031602142.html|title=N.J. Won't Seek a Retrial of Hurricane Carter|date=February 20, 1988|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=December 4, 2013|agency=Associated Press|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120717005948/http://articles.latimes.com/1988-02-20/news/mn-11377_1_carter-hurricane-seeking/16/AR2007031602142.html|archive-date=July 17, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> She is a supporter of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/05/ellen-burstyn-interview-house-of-cards-netflix-1201751198/|title=Ellen Burstyn On \u2018House Of Cards\u2019 And The Presidential Race: \u201cI\u2019m Just Stunned\u201d|last=Utichi|first=Joe|last2=Utichi|first2=Joe|date=2016-05-19|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108125013/https://deadline.com/2016/05/ellen-burstyn-interview-house-of-cards-netflix-1201751198/|archive-date=November 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and appeared in the 2009 documentary ''[[PoliWood]]''. Burstyn served as president of the [[Actors' Equity Association]] from 1982 to 1985.<ref name=\"equity\">{{cite web|url=http://www.actorsequity.org/aboutequity/howigotmyequitycard/Ecard_burstyn.asp|title=How I Got My Equity Card|publisher=[[Actors' Equity Association]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021042600/http://www.actorsequity.org/AboutEquity/HowIGotMyEquityCard/Ecard_Burstyn.asp|archivedate=October 21, 2013|accessdate=December 4, 2013|df=mdy}}</ref> Burstyn is on the Board of Selectors of [[Jefferson Awards for Public Service]].<ref name=\"jefferson\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jeffersonawards.org/board|title=Our Board of Selectors|publisher=Jefferson Awards for Public Service|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101124055949/http://www.jeffersonawards.org/board|archivedate=November 24, 2010|accessdate=December 4, 2013|df=mdy}}</ref> In 1997, Burstyn was inducted into the [[Michigan Women's Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"MIwomens\">{{cite web|url=http://hall.michiganwomen.org/honoree.php?C=0&A=129~88~248~143|title=Ellen Burstyn: Michigan's Women's Hall of Fame|publisher=michiganwomen.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150914070705/http://hall.michiganwomen.org/honoree.php?C=0&A=129~88~248~143|archivedate=September 14, 2015|accessdate=December 4, 2013|df=mdy}}</ref> Since 2000, she has been co-president of the [[Actors Studio]], alongside [[Al Pacino]] and [[Alec Baldwin]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theactorsstudio.org/who-we-are/leadership/|title=Leadership|website=The Official Site of The Actors Studio|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191231183212/https://theactorsstudio.org/who-we-are/leadership/|archive-date=December 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2013, she was inducted into the [[American Theatre Hall of Fame]] for her work on stage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatermania.com/new-york-city-theater/news/whoopi-goldberg-to-host-the-30th-annual-musical-ce_67132.html|title=Whoopi Goldberg to Host the 30th Annual Musical Celebration of Broadway Honoring Neil Patrick Harris {{!}} TheaterMania|website=www.theatermania.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217162252/https://www.theatermania.com/new-york-city-theater/news/whoopi-goldberg-to-host-the-30th-annual-musical-ce_67132.html|archive-date=February 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''[[Goodbye Charlie]]''\n| Franzie Salzman\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Credited as Ellen McRae\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''[[For Those Who Think Young (film)|For Those Who Think Young]]''\n| Dr. Pauline Thayer\n|-\n| 1969\n| ''[[Pit Stop (1969 film)|Pit Stop]]'' (original title: ''The Winner'')\n| Ellen McLeod\n|\n|-\n| 1970\n| ''[[Alex in Wonderland]]''\n| Beth Morrison\n|\n|-\n| 1970\n| ''[[Tropic of Cancer (film)|Tropic of Cancer]]''\n| Mona Miller\n|\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''{{sortname|The|Last Picture Show}}''\n| Lois Farrow\n| \n|-\n| 1972\n| ''{{sortname|The|King of Marvin Gardens}}''\n| Sally\n|\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''{{sortname|The|Exorcist|dab=film}}''\n| Chris MacNeil\n| \n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[Alice Doesn't Live Here Anymore]]''\n| Alice Hyatt\n| \n|-\n| 197