{"title_page": "Pia\u021ba Victoriei metro station", "text_new": "{{Short description|Bucharest metro station}}\n{{Infobox station \n| name          = Pia\u0163a Victoriei\n| type          = \n| style         = RATB\n| image         = Trains at Piata Victoriei.jpg\n| image_caption = The upper deck (M2 platforms) in 2009.\n| address       = [[Victory Square, Bucharest|Victory Square]], <br />[[Sector 1 (Bucharest)|Sector 1]], [[Bucharest]]\n| country       = [[Romania]]\n| coordinates   = \n| line          = <!-- line information is detailed under \"services\" -->\n| other         = \n| structure     = Underground\n| platform      = 4 - [[Side platform|Side]] for the M2 line <br> [[Island platform|Island]] for the M1 line\n| depth         = \n| levels        = \n| tracks        = \n| parking       = \n| bicycle       = \n| baggage_check = \n| opened        = 25 October 1987 (M2) <br> 17 August 1989 (M3, currently M1)\n| closed        = \n| rebuilt       = \n| electrified   = \n| ADA           = \n| code          = \n| owned         = \n| zone          = \n| former        = \n| passengers    = \n| pass_year     = \n| pass_percent  = \n| pass_system   = \n| mpassengers   = \n| services      = {{s-rail|title=Bucharest Metro}}{{s-line|system=RATB|line=M1|previous=\u015etefan cel Mare|next=Gara de Nord}}\n{{s-line|system=RATB|line=M2|previous=Pia\u0163a Roman\u0103|next=Aviatorilor}}\n| map_locator   = \n| web           = \n}}\n'''''Pia\u0163a Victoriei''''' is a metro station in Pia\u0163a Victoriei ([[Victory Square, Bucharest|Victory Square]]), central [[Bucharest]]. It is near the [[Victoria Palace]], the headquarters of the [[Government of Romania|Romanian government]]. This station consists of two stations (Pia\u0163a Victoriei 1 - line 2 -, above, and Pia\u0163a Victoriei 2 - line 1 -, below) and, along with [[Pia\u0163a Unirii metro station|Pia\u0163a Unirii]] is one of the busiest metro stations in Bucharest. It was the setting for many parts of the documentary ''[[Children Underground]]''.\n\nThe M1 station was opened in 1989 as part of the extension from [[Gara de Nord metro station|Gara de Nord]] to [[Dristor metro station|Dristor]].<ref name=\"urbanrail\">{{cite web |last1=Schwandl |first1=Robert |title= Bucure\u015fti |url=http://www.urbanrail.net/eu/ro/buc/bucurest.htm |publisher=urbanrail}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|44.45157|26.08713|display=title|type:landmark_region:RO}}\n\n{{Bucharest Metro navbox}}\n{{Transport in Bucharest}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Piata Victoriei Metro Station}}\n[[Category:Bucharest Metro stations|Victoriei]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1989]]\n[[Category:1989 establishments in Romania]]\n\n\n{{Bucharest-metro-stub}}\n{{Romania-railstation-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Bucharest metro station}}\n{{Infobox station \n| name          = Pia\u0163a Victoriei\n| type          = \n| style         = RATB\n| image         = Trains at Piata Victoriei.jpg\n| image_caption = The upper deck (M2 platforms) in 2009.\n| address       = [[Victory Square, Bucharest|Victory Square]], <br />[[Sector 1 (Bucharest)|Sector 1]], [[Bucharest]]\n| country       = [[Romania]]\n| coordinates   = \n| line          = <!-- line information is detailed under \"services\" -->\n| other         = \n| structure     = Underground\n| platform      = 4 - [[Side platform|Side]] for the M2 line <br> [[Island platform|Island]] for the M1 line\n| depth         = \n| levels        = \n| tracks        = \n| parking       = \n| bicycle       = \n| baggage_check = \n| opened        = 25 October 1987 (M2) <br> 17 August 1989 (M3, currently M1)\n| closed        = \n| rebuilt       = \n| electrified   = \n| ADA           = \n| code          = \n| owned         = \n| zone          = \n| former        = \n| passengers    = \n| pass_year     = \n| pass_percent  = \n| pass_system   = \n| mpassengers   = \n| services      = {{s-rail|title=Bucharest Metro}}{{s-line|system=RATB|line=M1|previous=\u015etefan cel Mare|next=Gara de Nord}}\n{{s-line|system=RATB|line=M2|previous=Pia\u0163a Roman\u0103|next=Aviatorilor}}\n| map_locator   = \n| web           = \n}}\n'''''Pia\u0163a Victoriei''''' is a metro station in Pia\u0163a Victoriei ([[Victory Square, Bucharest|Victory Square]]), central [[Bucharest]]. It is near the [[Victoria Palace]], the headquarters of the [[Government of Romania|Romanian government]]. This station consists of two stations (Pia\u0163a Victoriei 1 - line 2 -, above, and Pia\u0163a Victoriei 2 - line 1 -, below) and, along with [[Pia\u0163a Unirii metro station|Pia\u0163a Unirii]] is one of the busiest metro stations in Bucharest. It was the setting for many parts of the documentary ''[[Children Underground]]''.\n\nThe station was opened in 1989 as part of the extension from [[Gara de Nord metro station|Gara de Nord]] to [[Dristor metro station|Dristor]].<ref name=\"urbanrail\">{{cite web |last1=Schwandl |first1=Robert |title= Bucure\u015fti |url=http://www.urbanrail.net/eu/ro/buc/bucurest.htm |publisher=urbanrail}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|44.45157|26.08713|display=title|type:landmark_region:RO}}\n\n{{Bucharest Metro navbox}}\n{{Transport in Bucharest}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Piata Victoriei Metro Station}}\n[[Category:Bucharest Metro stations|Victoriei]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1989]]\n[[Category:1989 establishments in Romania]]\n\n\n{{Bucharest-metro-stub}}\n{{Romania-railstation-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ymblanter", "label": "safe", "comment": "upd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pia%C8%9Ba_Victoriei_metro_station"}
